heart rudiment: A cone-like structure that is formed when myocardial progenitor cells of the heart field fuse at the midline. The heart rudiment is the first structure of the heart tube.
respiratory system lymphatic vessel smoo: A lymphatic vessel smooth muscle that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].
rapids: An area of broken, fast flowing water in a stream, where the slope of the bed increases (but without a prominent break of slope which might result in a waterfall), or where a gently dipping bar of harder rock outcrops.
drylot: A drylot is an enclosure of limited size usually bare of vegetation and used for fattening livestock.
montane savanna biome: A montane savanna biome is a savanna biome which occurs in regions elevated above sea level and which has community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.
obsolete terrestrial habitat: A habitat that is on or at the boundary of the surface of the Earth.
bee food product: A food product with bees or bee substances as a defining ingredient.
halite: A salt mass which consists of isometric crystals of sodium chloride (NaCl).
planetary structural layer: A planetary structural layer is laminar part of a terrestrial planet or other rocky body large enough to have differentiation by density. Planetary layers have differing physicochemical properties and composition.
coffee, tea, cocoa or infusion (eurofir): Beverage prepared by extracting flavour and other components from food sources by percolation and/or immersion in water, usually at near-boiling temperature. The group includes coffee (e.g. instant coffee, coffee and chicory essence), tea, herbal tea (e.g. green tea, black tea, tisane), cocoa beverage and beverage powder.
liquid air-water interface layer: A liquid surface layer which is in contact with air.
abandoned fishing gear: Fishing gear which is not under the control of or maintained by its custodian.
rainwater: Rainwater is liquid water which has precipitated in the form of droplets through the condensation of atmospheric water vapour.
terrarium: A terrarium is a vivarium which simulates a terrestrial environment.
Taylor column: A Taylor column is a column of deflected fluid flow which is formed in a perturbed, rotating fluid, is parallel to the axis of rotation, and extends above the obstacle perturbing the fluid in a rigid manner.
astronomical body part: A material part of an astronomical body.
fumarole-derived ice tower: A hollow tower of ice formed by the freezing of steam escaping a fumarole.
landform: A solid astronomical body part which has been formed from and is composed primarily of the matter of that astronomical body.
convergent plate boundary: A geomorphological feature which is formed where two or more tectonic plates are actively moving towards one another, resulting in deformation of the lithosphere that forces one plate below the other where it melts in the mantle.
mass plasma flow: A process whereby a large volume of plasma moves due to a disequilibrium of physical forces.
methane ice: Ice which is primarily composed of methane.
lateral moraine: The parallel ridges of till deposited along the sides of an alglacier. The unconsolidated debris is deposited on top of the glacier by frost shattering of the valley walls and from tributary streams flowing into the valley. The till is carried along the glacial margin until the glacier melts.
asphalt: Asphalt also known as bitumen is a sticky, black, and highly viscous liquid or semi-solid form of petroleum.
marine anoxic zone: Marine anoxic zones are areas of marine water that are depleted of dissolved oxygen. This condition is generally found in areas that have restricted water exchange. In most cases, oxygen is prevented from reaching the deeper levels by a physical barrier (sill) as well as by a pronounced density stratification. Anoxic conditions will occur if the rate of oxidation of organic matter by bacteria is greater than the supply of dissolved oxygen.
obsolete organic feature: A prominent or distinctive aspect, quality, or characteristic pertaining to or derived from living organisms.
natural bee hive: A bee hive that occurs naturally without human intervention, typically found in environments such as tree cavities, rock crevices, or underground burrows.
well intervention: A planned process during which an oil or gas well is modified.
endorheic lake: A lake from which there is no outflow of water, either on the surface as rivers, or underground by flow or diffusion through rock or permeable material.
cloacal epithelium: An epithelium that is part of a cloaca.
cloacal mucosa: A mucosa that is part of a cloaca [Automatically generated definition].
volcanic fissure: A linear volcanic vent through which lava erupts, usually without any explosive activity. The vent is usually a few meters wide and may be many kilometers long. Fissure vents can cause large flood basalts and hannels. The volcano can usually be seen as a crack in the ground or on the ocean floor. Narrow fissures can be filled in with lava that hardens.
marine environmental zone: An astronomical body part which is part of a marine environment.
primary cave: A cave formed at the same time as the surrounding rock.
pharyngeal arch mesenchyme from head mes: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a entire pharyngeal arch associated mesenchyme.
biological_process: A biological process is the execution of a genetically-encoded biological module or program. It consists of all the steps required to achieve the specific biological objective of the module. A biological process is accomplished by a particular set of molecular functions carried out by specific gene products (or macromolecular complexes), often in a highly regulated manner and in a particular temporal sequence.
oil paint thinner: A solvent used to thin oil-based paints or clean up after their use.
acidic volcanic ash: Volcanic ash which has increased levels of molecules or ions capable of donating a hydron (proton or hydrogen ion) to other chemical entities, or, alternatively, capable of forming covalent bonds with other chemicals via the acceptance of an electron pair, resulting in a bulk pH measurement of less than 7.
nursing home: A building in which nursing aides and skilled nurses provide care and treatment to residents who have significant difficulty coping with the required activities of daily living.
metalimnion: A cline which is part of a lake and across which temperature changes rapidly with depth.
jaw skeleton: Subdivision of skeleton which includes upper and lower jaw skeletons.
automated teller machine: An electronic telecommunications device that enables the customers of a financial institution to perform financial transactions, particularly cash withdrawal, without the need for a human cashier, clerk or bank teller.
formal settlement: A settlement which has been established and is managed through officially sanctioned processes and is recognised as legal by a competent authority.
IUCN natural monument or feature: An IUCN protected area which includes a primarily natural formation designated to be of high natural heritage value and the environmental systems which it determines (e.g. the spray zone of a waterfall monument).
gypsum: A soft sulfate mineral composed of calcium sulfate dihydrate.
bathtub fixture: A plumbing fixture which may serve as a container for water in which humans or other animals may bathe.
plant stem or spear food product: A food product deriving from a plant stem or spear part.
cloacal muscle: Any muscle organ that is part of a cloaca.
bagasse: The biomass remaining after sugarcane stalks are crushed to extract their juice.
mud exterior wall: A mud exterior wall is an exterior wall that is composed primarily of mud.
enamel thinner: A paint thinner specific for altering the viscosity of enamel paints.
public building: A building which is publically accessible.
natural monument: A natural environment which has been designated by a competent authority as having outstanding or unique value because of its rarity, aesthetic qualities, or cultural significance.
visible spectrum radiation from a manufa: Radiation from a manufactured product during which light between the wavelenghts of 380 nm and 760 nm is emitted.
thermosphere: The thermosphere is a part of the earth's atmosphere that begins at about 50 miles (80 kilometers) above the earth's surface, extends to outer space, and is characterized by steadily increasing temperature with height
material transport process: A process during which material is displaced from its original location and transported either to a new location or back to the original location.
vasculature of retina: A vasculature that is part of a retina [Automatically generated definition].
obsolete cold temperature habitat: A habitat characterized by an average temperature of 15deg C or lower. Inhabited by psychrophilic (cryophilic) organisms.
foregut epithelium: An epithelium that is part of a foregut.
broadleaf forest: A forest biome which contains densely packed populations or communities of broadleaf trees, strongly limiting light penetration to the forest floor.
estuarine coastal lower water column: A layer of estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuarine bed and from the shore to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.
marine white smoker biome: A marine white smoker biome comprises regions of the marine hydrothermal vent biome characterised by lightly hued plumes, typically containing barium, calcium, and silicon. These vents tend to have lower temperature plumes when compared to black smoker environments.
arable soil: Soil which is capable of supporting the growth of crops.
asbestos dust: Dust which is derived from asbestos
forestry: A land use process during which humans access and manage forest ecosystems for 1) the provisioning of wood, forages, water, wildlife, and recreation as well as a broad range of other ecosystem services or 2) the maintenance of the forest ecosystem's health.
emergency unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide emergency medicine services.
food production medium-risk contaminatio: A hygienic food production area in which general food processing occurs.
obsolete alkaline habitat: A habitat in which the pH is >pH9. Inhabited by alkaliphilic organisms.
methyl cellulose paste: An environmental material which is 1) composed primarily of methyl cellulose and water, and 2) formulated to fix wallpaper to walls.
atmospheric escape: A process during which gases that constitute a planetary atmosphere escape that planet's gravitational field and move away into outer space.
mediterranean biome: A biome which is subject to mediterranean climatic conditions.
hill range: A range of mounts which is dominated by hills.
organooxygen compound: An organochalcogen compound containing at least one carbon-oxygen bond.
cyclic compound: Any molecule that consists of a series of atoms joined together to form a ring.
botanical garden: A place where a wide variety of plants primarily categorized and documented for scientific purposes.
ozone layer: The ozone layer is a layer of gases in the stratosphere which contains high concentrations of ozone gas relative to other parts of the atmosphere.
tundra climatic condition: An tundra climatic condition is a polar condition in which at least one month's average temperature exceeds 0 degrees Celsius.
field soil: Soil which is part of an agricultural field.
geyser: A hot spring that erupts periodically, ejecting a column of hot water and steam into the air.
atmospheric layer: A layer that is part of the atmosphere.
landmass: A large continuous area of land, either surrounded by sea or contiguous with another landmass.
solid astronomical body part: A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of solid material.
drumlin: An elongated whale-shaped hill formed by glacial action. Its long axis is parallel with the movement of the ice, with the blunter end facing into the glacial movement. Drumlins are sometimes compared to kames, but their formation is distinctively different. A drumlin is not originally shaped by meltwater, but by the ice itself and has a quite regular shape. It occurs in fine grained material, such as clay or shale, not in sands and gravels. And drumlins usually have concentric layers of material, as the ice successively plasters new layers in its movement.
protoplanet: An astronomical object that forms within a protoplanetary disc when planetesimals and other solid debris aggregate and, due to gravitational forces,  fuse and initiate internal melting to produce a differentiated interior.
pinnacle: A tall, slender, spire-shaped rock projecting from a level or more gently sloping surface.
outer epithelium: The epidermis is the entire outer epithelial layer of an animal, it may be a single layer that produces an extracellular material (e.g. the cuticle of arthropods) or a complex stratified squamous epithelium, as in the case of many vertebrate species[GO].
squall wind: An atmospheric wind which rapidly forms, lasts for a duration in the order of minutes, and then rapidly decreases in speed.
mesotrophic water: Water with a nutrient level intermediate between eutrophic and oligotrophic.
respiratory system basement membrane: A basement membrane of epithelium that is part of a respiratory system.
photophore: A photophore is a light-emitting organ which appears as luminous spots on various marine animals, including fish and cephalopods. The organ can be simple, or as complex as the human eye; equipped with lenses, shutters, color filters and reflectors. The light can be produced from compounds during the digestion of prey, from specialized mitochondrial cells in the organism, called photocytes ("light producing" cells) , or, similarly, associated with symbiotic  bacteria in the organism.
subtropical savanna: A savanna which is subject to subtropical environmental conditions.
non-lead solder: A solder which is composed without lead.
acid rainfall: A water-based rainfall process during which water droplets with increased acidity fall towards a planetary surface.
animal carcass fall: The carcass of an animal that has fallen to the bottom of a body of water.
oasis: An oasis is a vegetated area located in a desert, supplied with water from a water source which it surrounds, and surrounded by arid soil, sand, or rock.
thalassic: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being derived from, part of, or otherwise dependent on the seas or oceans.
meadow biome: A meadow ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
sediment permeated by saline water: Sediment which has its porespace filled by water with increased levels of sodium chloride and other salts.
pressure lamp: A pressure lamp is a portable paraffin or oil lamp in which fuel is forced up into the mantle or burner by air pressure in the reservoir, which can be increased by pumping with a plunger.
USA agency food product type: Food group having common consumption, functional or manufacturing characteristics, e.g. *FRUIT OR VEGETABLE PRODUCT*, *DAIRY PRODUCT*, *CONFECTIONARY*, *PREPARED FOOD PRODUCT*, etc. [FDA CFSAN 1995]
wall of intestine: An anatomical wall that is part of a intestine [Automatically generated definition].
concentration of clay in soil: The concentration of a clay when measured in soil.
aerobic bioreactor: A bioreactor in which the contained material is well-oxygenated.
active permafrost layer: A layer which is composed of ground that is 1) subject to annual thawing and freezing and 2) present in areas underlain by permafrost.
biocrust: A surface layer of a solid environmental material which is formed by the presence and activity of photosynthetic microbial assemblages colonising it.
permafrost methane explosion: An explosion during which methane-rich gas trapped in permafrost combusts.
eaves: A part of a building roof which overhangs the face of a wall and, normally, projects beyond the side of a building.
mucus material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of mucus, a bodily fluid consisting of a slippery secretion of the lining of the mucous membranes in the body. It is a viscous colloid containing antiseptic enzymes (such as lysozyme) and immunoglobulins. Mucus is produced by goblet cells in the mucous membranes that cover the surfaces of the membranes. It is made up of mucins and inorganic salts suspended in water.
nitrogen-oxygen planetary atmosphere: A planetary atmosphere which is composted primarily of dinitrogen and dioxygen gas.
skeleton: Anatomical cluster that consists of all the skeletal elements (eg., bone, cartilage, and teeth) of the body.
geriatric care unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide geriatric medical services.
natural plastic: Plastic which is composed primarily of polymers produced by processes whose agents do not include humans or their technologies.
undersea feature: A hydrographic feature which is located below the surface of a marine water body.
altitudinal condition: An altitudinal condition is an environmental condition in which ranges of factors such as temperature, humidity, soil composition, solar irradiation, and tree density vary with ranges in altitude.
increased efficiency: An efficiency which is relatively high.
decreased distribution: A distribution which is relatively low.
decreased efficiency: An efficiency which is relatively low.
efficient: An efficiency quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having efficiency.
increased distribution: A distribution which is relatively high.
mist: A visible mass of water droplets or ice crystals suspended in the air at or near a planetary surface, formed when humid air cools rapidly.
atmospheric weather: Weather which inheres in an atmosphere.
diurnal marine tidal flow zone: A marine zone in which ocean waters undergo a diurnal (once per day) tidal oscillation - with one high and one low tide per day - due to the supression of a second daily oscillation by the geometry of the ocean basin and obstructions presented by land masses.
forage material: Material which is primarily conposed of the vegetation present in tended pastures: mainly grasses, with an interspersion of legumes and other forbs.
natural arch: A natural formation where a rock arch forms, with a natural passageway through underneath.
biofilter: A bioreactor which captures and, through the biological processes maintained in the medium it contains, degrades pollutants.
monochrome solar rainbow: A solar rainbow which is formed by a narrow band of wavelengths, the rest of the spectrum having been scattered away by an atmosphere.
ice cap climatic condition: An ice cap climatic condition is a polar condition in which the montly average temperature does not exceed 0 degrees Celsius.
sound speed: A physical quality inhering in sound by virtue of the bearer's travelling speed in a given medium under specified conditions.
subtropical desert ecosystem: A desert ecosystem which is subject to subtropical environmental conditions.
meteor: A meteor is any matter- or energy-based entity which is located in the atmosphere of an astronomical body.
montane grassland: A grassland which is subject to montane environmental conditions.
shuga: New ice, which is spongy, lumpy and opaque, and forms from water which freezes in an agitated water body.
stalagmite: A speleothem projecting vertically upwards from a cave floor and formed by precipitation from drips.
dam: A barrier constructed across a watercourse to control the flow or raise the level of water.
apple cider (alcoholic): Cider, hard apple cider, or hard cider in the US, is an alcoholic beverage made from the fermented juice of apples.
knackery: A facility in which non-human animals are slaughtered and processed, but not for human consumption.
food kiosk: A kiosk from which food products are sold.
marine sediment: Sediment which has been transported through the marine water column, settling on the seafloor.
neural keel: An intermediate stage (between the neural plate and neural rod) during the early segmentation period in the morphogenesis of the central nervous system primordium; the keel is roughly triangular shaped in cross section.
bar: A linear shoaling landform feature within a body of water. Bars tend to be long and narrow (linear) and develop where a current (or waves) promote deposition of granular material, resulting in localized shallowing (shoaling) of the water. Bars can appear in the sea, in a lake, or in a river. They are typically composed of sand, although could be of any granular matter that the moving water has access to and is capable of shifting around (for example, soil, silt, gravel, cobble, shingle, or even boulders). The grain size of the material comprising a bar is related: to the size of the waves or the strength of the currents moving the material, but the availability of material to be worked by waves and currents is also important.
handrail: A pole which provides stability or support when grasped by the hand.
cloacal vent: The opening of the cloacal chamber to the outside of the organism. Birds maintain a single cloacal opening throughout their lives.
electromagnetic wave energy: Wave energy which inheres in perpendicular electric and magnetic fields and which is realised when they oscillate and propagate.
atmospheric storm: An atmospheric storm is a process in which a portion of an astronomical body's atmosphere is strongly perturbed from its prevaling weather.
strand crack: Fissure at the junction between an inland ice sheet, ice piedmont or ice rise and an ice shelf, the latter being subject to the rise and fall of the tide.
mantle lamp: A mantle lamp is a central-draught lamp which includes a pear-shaped, fabric mesh containing thorium or other rare-earth salts placed over the burner. On first use the fabric burns away and the rare-earth salts are converted to oxides, leaving a very fragile structure which incandesces (glows brightly) upon exposure to the heat of the burner flame.
sphagnum bog: A peatland dominated by species of the Bryophyte Sphagnum.
retina: The retina is the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.
lens of camera-type eye: Transparent part of camera-type eye that helps to refract light to be focused on the retina.
usage of an environment for community an: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports welfare activities organised by the state or a local authority and carried out by trained personnel.
sandy clay loam: Clay loam which has a high proportion of sand in its composition.
flood plain: An area which is subject to periodic flooding.
private swimming pool: A constructed swimming pool which is owned by a non-governmental legal entity or a collective of such entities.
obsolete physical object of mesoscopic g: An object which is large enough to be visible to humans, but small enough that humans can handle the object (i.e. transport it, examine it, etc) in its entirety with little to no technological assistance.
nest of wasp: An animal habitation that is assembled by a wasp. These may be in the ground, in wall cavities, or in sheltered areas.
circulatory organ: A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, contributes to the circulation of lymph, blood or analogs. Examples: a chambered vertebrate heart; the tubular peristaltic heart of ascidians; the dorsal vessel of an insect; the lymoh heart of a reptile.
manured soil: Soil which has, as a part, a portion of either fresh or processed animal manure.
stomodeum: Anterior part of the embryonic digestive tract that develops into a mouth. The stomodeum includes as parts an invagination of the ectoderm and the stomodeal cavity.
saline aerosol environment: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by a saline aerosol.
temperature of sea surface: A water temperature which inheres in water close to the surface of an ocean or sea.
glacial ice accumulation zone: An ice accumulation zone which overlaps part of a glacier.
freshwater environment: An aquatic environment which is determined by freshwater.
precipitation of sleet: A hydrological precipitation process during which water falls in both liquid and frozen form.
thatched exterior wall: A thatched exterior wall is an exterior wall that is composed primarily of thatch.
brassica food product: A genus of plants in the mustard family (Brassicaceae). The members of the genus are informally known as cruciferous vegetables, cabbages, or mustard plants.
intensive care unit room: A room in which intensive medical care is provided.
tropical marine upwelling biome: A marine upwelling biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
bacon food product: Any of certain cuts of meat taken from the sides, belly or back of a pig that may be cured and/or smoked.
wort food product: The liquid extracted from the mashing process during the brewing of beer or whiskey. Wort contains the sugars that will be fermented by the brewing yeast to produce alcohol.
photoevaporation: A process during which energetic radiation ionises gas and causes it to disperse away from the ionising source.
rainstorm: An atmospheric storm during which intense rainfall occurs.
subtropical grassland: A grassland which is subject to subtropical climatic conditions.
dead flame paraffin lantern: A dead-flame paraffin lantern is a paraffin lantern which has a wick housed in a glass globe with airflow channelled upwards by vents below the burning wick and an open chimney above it.
insect food product: A food product with insects as a defining ingredient.
carvery: A restaurant which provides customers with cooked meat freshly sliced to order.
chonolith: A chonolith is an igneous rock intrusion of irregular shape with a demonstrable base, absent in other types of irregularly-shaped intrusions.
marine ultramafic hydrothermal vent biom: A marine ultramafic hydrothermal vent biome comprises regions of themarine  hydrothermal vent biome hosted on ultramafic (also referred to as ultrabasic) rocks. Ultramafic rocks are igneous and meta-igneous rocks with very low silica content (less than 45%), generally >18% MgO, high FeO, low potassium, and are composed of usually greater than 90% mafic minerals  (dark colored, high magnesium and iron content). The Earth's mantle is composed of ultramafic rocks.
plateau glacier: A glacier on a plateau or high area, smaller than an ice sheet.
estuarine open water surface layer: A layer of estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast.
humic kerogen: Kerogen which derives from land plants, resembles wood or coral in structure, has a hydrogen to carbon ratio under 1, an oxygen to carbon ratio between 0.03 to 0.3, and which primarily produces coal or hydrocarbon gas on degradation.
stalactite: A speleothem hanging downwards from a roof or wall, of cylindrical or conical form, usually with a central hollow tube.
meristematic cell: A native plant cell (PO:0025606) synthesizing protoplasm and producing new cells by division and with only a primary cell wall.
corn exchange: A commercial building where merchants trade grains.
stream channel: A channel of a watercourse which contains a stream.
calving of ice from an iceberg: A process during which a part of an iceberg breaks away from the main mass.
occluded front: A weather front which separates air behind a cold front from air ahead of a warm front.
pit: A depression in the ground resembling a hole or cavity, either natural or anthropogenic.
polar: A polar condition is an environmental condition in which an environmental system receives low, yearly solar irradiance per unit area, resulting in colder climatic conditions.
epeiric sea biome: The epeiric sea (also known as an epicontinental sea) biome comprises a shallow seas that extend over part of a continent. Epeiric seas are usually associated with the marine transgressions of the geologic  past, which have variously been due to either global eustatic sea level changes, local tectonic deformation, or both, and are occasionally semi-cyclic.
constructed barrier: A constructed barrier is a freestanding wall, berm, or fence built to limit movement of entities across a boundary.
fluorescence: A luminous flux quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's emitting longer wavelength light following the absorption of shorter wavelength radiation; fluorescence is common with aromatic compounds with several rings joined together.
color: A composite chromatic quality composed of hue, saturation and intensity parts.
age: A time quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of how long the bearer has existed.
color pattern: A chromatic property that is the relative position of different hues or degrees of saturation.
moist soil albedo: Soil albedo which inheres in moist soil.
marine neritic zone: The water mass of an ocean directly above a continental shelf.
gaseous part of an atmosphere: That part of an atmosphere which is composed of gaseous material.
large freshwater lake biome: A large freshwater lake ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
large river biome: A large freshwater river ecosystem which is in its climactic ecological state.
area of alpine tundra: An area of tundra which is present in a region subject to alpine conditions.
accumulation: A structural quality of the collection or massing of one physical object within another physical object.
semi erect: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being partially upright in position or posture.
3-D shape: A shape that inheres in a 3 dimensional entity.
centered: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located in a position equidistant from edges.
electroplating fume: A fume containing volatile organic compounds produced through the process of electroplating
water intake: A hydraulic-engineering installation which transports water - in specified amounts, of a specified quality, and in accordance with a water-consumption plan - from a source of supply into a conduit.
convective storm: An atmospheric storm which is generated by the heating and convection of moist and unstable air masses.
pressure of atmospheric water vapour: The pressure of some atmospheric water vapour.
power plant: A power plant is a building which contains one or more generators which convert mechanical energy into electrical energy through the relative motion between a magnetic field and a conductor. The energy source harnessed to turn the generator varies widely.
submarine canyon: A steep-sided valley on the sea floor of the continental slope. Many submarine canyons are found as extensions to large rivers; however there are many that have no such association. Canyons cutting the continental slopes have been found at depths greater than 2 km below sea level. Many submarine canyons continue as submarine channels across continental rise areas and may extend for hundreds of kilometers.
embryonic cardiovascular system: A cardiovascular system that is part of a conceptus.
glacial retreat: A glacial ice loss process during which the snout (toe) of a glacier shrinks following successive years of negative mass balance.
glacial abrasion: A glacial abrasion process is an erosional process during which debris in the basal ice scrapes along the bed, polishing and gouging the underlying rocks, similar to sandpaper on wood.
subjacent karst: Karst developed in soluble beds underlying other rock formations; the surface may or may not be affected by the karst development.
frazil: Small, needle-like (spicules), plate-like, or discoid crystals derived from nearly pure fresh water, suspended in a water body.
blood plasma: The liquid component of blood, in which erythrocytes are suspended.
fragmentation due to weathering: A fragmentation process which is caused by weathering.
emmenthal cheese: A semi-hard, yellow cheese that has mild flavor that is slightly buttery.
mammalian milk whey: The serum or watery part of milk that is separated from the thicker or more coagulable part or curd, espcially in the process of making cheese; it contains lactose, minerals and lactalbumin.
marine tidal flow zone: An environmental zone in which varying gravitational forces from astronomical bodies, combined with the rotation of the astronomical body containing the zone, cause marine waters to undergo periodic depth oscillations (tides).
marine lysocline: The marine lysocline denotes the depth in the ocean below which the rate of dissolution of calcite increases dramatically. As water column depth and therefore pressure increases, the corresponding calcite saturation of seawater decreases and the calcite begins dissolve.
aquatic layer: A layer in a water mass, itself composed primarily of water.
freezing rainfall: Water-based rainfall which freezes either 1) on impact with a surface to form a coating of clear ice (glaze) or 2) after percolating through surface layers.
cold front: A weather front which is nonoccluded and  which moves in the direction of the warmer air mass it is adjacent to, such that colder air will occupy the site where warmer air was previously present.
estuarine open water lower water column: A layer of estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to end of the estuary most distal from the coast.
unburnt-brick exterior wall: An unburnt brick exterior wall is an exterior wall that is built from unburnt bricks.
grain dust: Dust that comes from grain and all the other substances associated with its cultivation & harvesting.
polyatomic ion: An ion consisting of more than one atom.
entanglement process: An environmental system process during which material entities become entrapped, wrapped, twisted, entwined, or otherwise caught in one another.
latex: A stable dispersion (emulsion) of polymer microparticles in an aqueous medium.
water-holding capacity: A disposition of a material entity which is realised when it is saturated with liquid water.
bed base: A bed base is a piece of furniture which supports a mattress.
valley: A depression which has been formed as a result of erosion by water or ice and which is low-lying, bordered by higher ground, and especially elongate.
tropical dry broadleaf forest: A tropical broadleaf forest which 1) s subject to a year-round warm climate 2) may receive several hundred centimeters of rain per year and 3) are subject to long dry seasons which last several months.
tropical storm: A an atmospheric storm which originates over tropical or subtropical waters and possesses a warm-core, non-frontal synoptic-scale cyclone with a low pressure centre, spiral rain bands and strong winds.
crevasse: A deep fissure in snow or ice.
wet macroburst: A macroburst during which large amounts of rain are generated.
soybean food product: A soybean food product is a product derived from the soybean plant.
dry toilet fixture: A toilet fixture which uses little to no water; excreta is removed manually or composted in situ.
tidal creek: A tidal water channel. Creeks may often dry to a muddy channel with little or no flow at low tide, but often with significant depth of water at high tide.
spoon: An eating utensil with a scooped end and a long handle.
cryosol: Cryosols comprise mineral soils formed in a permafrost environment. Where water is present, it occurs primarily in the form of ice. Cryogenic processes are the dominant soil-forming processes.
alluvial plain: A relatively flat and gently sloping landform found at the base of a range of hills or mountains, formed by the deposition of alluvial soil over a long period of time by one or more streams coming from the mountains.
alkaline environment: An alkaline environment is an environment in which entities are exposed to high pH, typically greater than a pH of 9.
dense settlement biome: A dense settlement biome is an anthropogenic terrestrial biome which is primarily used for human habitation, recreation, and industry within built structures with little other land use.
smooth muscle layer in fatty layer of su: A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a hypodermis.
allotment garden soil: Soil which is part of an allotment garden.
butte: An isolated hill with steep sides and a small flat top, smaller than mesas and plateaus. Buttes are formed by erosion when a cap of hard rock, usually of volcanic origin, covers a layer of softer rock that is easily worn away. This hard rock avoids erosion while the rock around it wears down.
lightning flash: A lightning process during which electrostatic discharge occurs within a single cloud or between multiple clouds.
urea enriched soil: A portion of urea enriched soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of urea.
rubber plantation soil: Soil which is part of a rubber plantation.
creosote contaminated soil: Soil which has elevated concentrations of creosote.
usage of an environment for industry: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports manufacturing facilities producing commodities that are sold with the expectation of recovering the total cost of production.
marine environment: An enviroment system which is determined by an ocean or sea.
temperate environment: An environment which is subject to temperate environmental conditions.
packaging machine: A device used in packaging operations.
aerosol environment: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by an aerosol.
microfracture: A microfracture is a small fracture which is found in a portion of solid material along which further fracturing tends to occur. Microfractures are considered imperfections which to pre-exist any fractures formed by the application of stress to a material.
wadi mouth: The lower terminus of a wadi where it widens into an adjoining floodplain, depression, or water body.
vertebrate animal food product: A food product which is derived from or produced by an animal that has a vertibrae.
volcanic rock: An igneous rock that results from magma reaching the surface either as lava or fragmental ejecta.
obsolete lava field: A feature formed by cooled lava, the molten rock that is expelled by a volcano during an eruption.
bacterial cell culture: A microbial cell culture which is primarily composed of bacterial biomass.
tripartite: A concave 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being divided into three branches.
decreased circumference: A circumference which is relatively low.
organ: Anatomical structure that performs a specific function or group of functions [WP].
flattened elevation: An elevation which is flattened across its highest surface.
pork chop food product: A cut of meat (a meat chop) cut perpendicularly to the spine of the pig and usually containing a rib or part of a vertebra, served as an individual portion.
footbridge: A bridge designed solely for pedestrians.
desert: A landform which has been rendered barren or partially barren by environmental extremes, especially by low rainfall, and which loses more liquid water by evapotranspiration than is supplied by precipitation.
calving of ice into water: An ice calving process during which a mass of ice falls from a larger mass into a body of water.
exposed: Open to view or not covered by another entity.
formation of a solid aerosol from gaseou: A process during which microscopic solid particulates are formed from gaseous materials in an atmosphere.
public transport hub: A transport hub which is part of public infrastructure.
paint thinner: A solvent that can dissolve paint and reduce viscosity of paint or "thin" it.
insequent stream: A stream that has an almost random drainage often forming dendritic patterns. These are typically tributaries and have developed by a headward erosion on a horizontally stratified belt or on homogeneous rocks. These streams follow courses that apparently were not controlled by the original slope of the surface, its structure or the type of rock.
ice wedge: A geological fracture which is formed during winter months by a narrow or thin piece of ice.
storm: A storm is an environmental process in which an environmental system and the processes it participates in are strongly perturbed by external forcings. These forcings typically increase the rates of processes unfolding in the system, relative to their normal rates.
human-directed construction process: An process during which natural or manufactured materials and products are processed and arranged by humans or their technology into structures.
hay: Hay is grass, legumes or other herbaceous plants that have been cut, dried, and stored for use as animal fodder, particularly for grazing livestock such as cattle, horses, goats, and sheep.
multiplet tectonic earthquake: A tectonic earthquake which has two or more mainshocks of similar magnitude, and which originate from the same fracture zone and stress field.
plastic fragment: A piece of plastic which 1) is hard, 2) has an irregular shape, and 3) has broken off of a larger piece of plastic.
hill: A rounded elevation of limited extent rising above the surrounding land with local relief of less than 300m.
horst: The raised fault block bounded by normal faults. The raised block is a portion of the Earth's crust that has remained stationary while the land has sunk on either side of it or has been crushed by a mountain range against it.
haline environment: A haline environment is an environment in which entities are exposed to high concentrations of salt, typically above 2 molar.
cirrus fibratus cloud: A cirrus cloud which occurs as a detached unit or a thin veil and consists of nearly straight or irregularly curved filaments that do not terminate in hooks or tufts.
evaporation: Evaporation is a form of vaporisation which occurs when a portion of the surface layer of a liquid in contact with a gaseous material, which is not saturated with the evaporating substance, vaporises.
increased fluid flow: A fluid flow that is relatively high.
decreased fluid flow: A flow that is relatively low.
time sampled measurement data set: A data set that is an aggregate of data recording some measurement at a number of time points. The time series data set is an ordered list of pairs of time measurement data and the corresponding measurement data acquired at that time.

polje: A large closed depression draining underground, with a flat floor across which there may be an intermittent or perennial stream and which may be liable to flood and become a lake. The floor makes a sharp break with parts of surrounding slopes.
biofilm: A complex aggregation of microorganisms marked by the excretion of a protective and adhesive matrix; usually adhering to a substratum.
silage: A fermented, high-moisture forage that can be fed to ruminants.
atmospheric aerosol: An aerosol that is suspended in an atmosphere.
lake-effect snow storm: A snowstorm during which intense lake-effect snowfall occurs.
root epidermis: A portion of plant epidermis (PO:0005679) that is part of a root (PO:0009005).
shoot system epidermis: A portion of plant epidermis (PO:0005679) that is part of a shoot system (PO:0009006) and arises from the meristem L1 layer (PO:0009020).
depositional process: A process during which material entities are added to a landform or to a feature upon the landform.
vineyard: A place where grapes are grown for making wine, raisins or table grapes.
dry pea food product: A product of the dry seeds of plants of the genus Pisum.
mouth of liquid discharge conduit: A site at the terminus of a liquid conveyance conduit where the liquid carried is discharged into the sea or a river.
estuarine tidal riverine coastal lower w: A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuarine bed and from the land-water interface to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.
paved parking lot: A constructed pavement which is used for parking vehicles.
marine oligotrophic desert: A marine water mass which is composed primarily of water with low concentrations of nutrients.
Codex Alimentarius classification of foo:
Codex Alimentarius, Volume 2 - 1993, Section 2:  Pesticide Residues in Food.

The Codex Classification of food and animal feed commodities moving in trade and the description of the various items and groups of food and animal feedstuffs included in the present document have been developed by the Codex Committee on Pesticide Residues. It was first adopted by the 18th Session of the Codex Alimentarius Commission, (1989).

The Codex Classification includes food commodities and animal feedstuffs for which Codex maximum residue limits will not necessarily be established. The Classification is intended to be as complete a listing of food commodities in trade as possible, classified into groups on the basis of the commodity's similar potential for pesticide residues.

The Classification may also be appropriate for other purposes such as setting maximum levels for other types of residues or for other contaminants in food. The Codex Classification should be consulted in order to obtain a precise description of the food or animal feed commodities and, especially, in cases where Codex maximum residue limits have been set for groups of food and groups of animal feedstuffs. The Codex Classification is intended to promote harmonization of the terms used to describe commodities which are subject to maximum residue limits and of the approach to grouping commodities with similar potential for residue for which a common group maximum residue limit can be set.
nutricline within a water body: A nutricline which is part of a water body.
dermal skeletal element: Dermis-derived entity that is made of skeletal tissue.
skeletal tissue: A specialized form of connective tissue in which the extracellular matrix is firm, providing the tissue with resilience, and/or mineralized and that functions in mechanical and structural support.[VSAO].
hemopoietic organ: Organ that is part of the hematopoietic system.
temperate marginal sea biome: A marginal sea biome which is located in a region with a temperate climate.
skerry: An island which is small, principally composed of rock, and usually too small for human habitation.
shedability: An organismal quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to lose an entity by natural process.
obsolete pulse: According to the FAO: 'The term "pulses" is limited to crops harvested solely for dry grain, thereby excludingcrops harvested green for food (green peas, green beans, etc.) which are classified as vegetable crops. Also excluded are those crops used mainly for oil extraction (e.g.soybeand and groundnuts) and leguminous crops (e.g. seeds of clover and alfalfa) that are used exclusively for sowing purposes.'
obsolete temperate upwelling biome: Please use the appropriate terms in the marine biome branch in combination with the marine upwelling feature to specify an environment characterised by a marine upwelling (2010-03-15, PLB)
sediment surface: The surface layer of a mass of sediment.
ventilated improved pit latrine: A ventilated improved pit latrine is a pit latrine which includes a vent pipe fitted to the pit with a flyscreen covering the pipe's outlet. Air currents moving across the outlet of the vent pipe create a vaccum which draws odors out of the latrine's superstructure.
meat sausage: A food product that is highly seasoned minced meat and is encased in a skin in the shape of a cylinder.
biota: A collection of organisms which inhabits the same region, ecosystem, or time period.
heart vasculature: An interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure that contains fluid that is actively transported around the heart.
liquid accumulation process: A material accumulation process during which the volume of liquid entity increases.
scalar measurement datum: A scalar measurement datum is a measurement datum that is composed of two parts, numerals and a unit label.
heat stressed soil: Soil which is has been heated such that its chemical, physical, or biological properties are destabilised.
interstitial water: Liquid water which occurs naturally within the pores of rocks and sediments.
fused with: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being merged with another entity.
stream: A watercourse which is linear and flows across the solid portion of a planetary surface.
fine respirable suspended particulate ma: A portion of fine respirable suspended particulate matter is a form of particulate matter composed primarily of solid particles each with a diameter of 2.5 micrometers or less.
stormwater: Water which accumulates on a solid surface during precipitation events and snow/ice melt.
tropical savanna: A savanna which is subject to tropical environmental conditions.
food production environmental monitoring: An object aggregate which comprises objects whose surfaces are not in contact with food during its processing, but which are in close proximity to those in food production environmental monitoring zone 1.
sedimentary intrusion: A rock intrusion which is composed primarily of sedimentary rock.
pig manure: Manure which is primarily composed of pig feces.
glass: Glass is an amorphous (non-crystalline) solid which is often transparent.
snow patch: An accumulation of snow and firn which rests upon land.
stratosphere: The layer of the atmosphere which is sandwiched between the troposphere and mesosphere. Of the energy that reaches the Earth from the sun, only 3% is absorbed in the stratosphere, but that includes the vitally important process of absorption of ultraviolet radiation by the stratospheric ozone layer. The stratosphere is cloudless and dust free, and almost unaffected by the turbulent conditions of the underlying level of the atmosphere. (Source: WRIGHT)
environment associated with an aquatic i: An environment which has its properties and composition largely determined by the presence of a metazoan which lacks a vetebral column and which has a habitat that is found in an aquatic environmental system.
marine nutricline: A nutricline which is part of a marine water body.
dacitic lava: Lava which is high in silica and low in alkali metal oxides.
waste disposal process: A process during which materials deemed to be waste are transported away from a site.
planetary atmosphere: An atmosphere which surrounds a planet.
raised beach: A beach or wave cut platform raised above the shore line by a relative fall in the sea level.
peat drainage: A drainage process during which water is transported away from peat.
maternity unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide materinity care.
obsolete unpasteurized milk product: Raw milk which has not undergone the pasteurization process.
motor boat: A motor boat is a boat which is propelled by a motor.
continuant fiat boundary: b is a continuant fiat boundary = Def. b is an immaterial entity that is of zero, one or two dimensions and does not include a spatial region as part. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [029-001])
gamma-ray radiation: A radiation process during which penetrating electromagnetic radiation is emitted from the radioactive decay (gamma decay) of atomic nuclei.
flooded grassland: A grassland which is inundated with water.
sheet of paper: A paper product which is a thin sheet material made of processed cellulose fibres.
straw: An agricultural byproduct, the dry stalk of a cereal plant, after the nutrient grain or seed has been removed.
ocean planet: A planet which has a surface layer that nearly completely or completely covered by water, and which has a substantial portion of its mass composed of water.
public-private prison: A prison facility which is owned by the state and operated by a private corporation.
refractory astrogeological material: A material which is composed primarily of chemical elements and compounds which have equilibrium condensation temperatures above approximately 1300 Kelvin and which are part of the crust or atmosphere of a moon or planet.
area designated for waste storage: A site which has been designated for the storage of waste material.
hot Jupiter: A giant gas planet which has a jovian-scale mass (0.36–11.8 Jupiter masses), a short orbital period (1.3–111 Earth days), and which is close to the star it orbits, resulting in extreme and exotic atmospheric properties.
ice cap: A dome-shaped ice mass that covers less than 50,000 km2 of land area (usually covering a highland area).
fountain pen ink: Water based ink intended for use with fountain ink pens.
marine abyssalpelagic zone: The zone of the ocean below the bathypelagic zone, with its lowest boundary at about 6000m.
cured meat food product: A meat that is preserved by the addition of a combination of salt, sugar, nitrates  or nitrite and or is smoked.
agricultural landscape diversification p: An active agri-ecosystem management process during which the variability of land use types or the spatial structure of land under agricultural production is increased.
IUCN protected area with sustainable use: An IUCN protected area within which 1) natural ecosystems and their resources are either conserved or used through non-industrial human activities, 2) usage activites contribute to conservation goals, ensuring inter-generational security for local communities' livelihoods, and 3) the majority of benefits derived from the use of ecosystems are received by communities living near or in the area.
noisy environment: An environment in which entities are exposed to either excessive or constant sound.
cloth: A textile comprised of a pliable material made usually by weaving, felting, or knitting natural or synthetic fibers and filaments.
obsolete aquatic habitat: A habitat that is in or on water.
oceanogenesis: A water accumulation process which results in the formation of an ocean by the outgassing, capture, and subsequent condensation of water vapour during the formation of an astronomical body.
primitive heart tube: Multi-tissue structure that arises from the heart rudiment and will become the heart tube.
heterocyclic compound: A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of at least two different elements.
mussel gill tissue material: Gill tissue material which is part of salt-water mussel in the family Mytilidae
main group element atom: An atom belonging to one of the main groups (found in the s- and p- blocks) of the periodic table.
solder: A metallic material which is composed of two or more metals and used to create a permanent bond between metal workpieces.
inorganic molecular entity: A molecular entity that contains no carbon.
bridge: A built structure erected over a depression or obstacle to carry traffic or some facility such as a pipeline.
delta: A landform which is composed of a tract of alluvium formed at the mouth of a river, where the deposition of some of its load exceeds its rate of removal, crossed by the divergent channels (distributaries) of the river.
cardiogenic splanchnic mesoderm: The splanchnic mesoderm in the cardiogenic region where the heart develops; it gives rise to endocardial heart tubes that fuse to form the primordial cardiac tube, the heart primordium[web]. Two migratory heart primordia that move ventrally during the course of neurulation, and then fuse[XAO].
englacial process: An environmental system process which occurs within a glacier or ice sheet.
protoderm: A portion of meristem tissue (PO:0009013) that is the outer layer of an apical meristem (PO:0020144), or the outer layer of a plant embryo proper (PO:0000001), and gives rise to a portion of epidermis (PO:0005679).
chiropractic clinic: A medical clinic which is used to provide chiropractic services.
reproductive structure: Any anatomical structure that is part of the reproductive system.
epithelial fold: An epithelial sheet bent on a linear axis.
homomutatus cloud: An aeroform which is formed as a result of strong upper winds spreading a cirrus homogenitus cloud in the atmosphere and, in turn, causing internal tranformations which result in the cloud taking on the appearnce of natural cirri-form clouds.
lightning strike: A lightning process during which electrostatic discharge occurs between a cloud and an object on a planetary surface, or a planetary surface itself.
soil organic matter: Organic material in soil, which consists of plant and animal residues at various stages of decomposition, cells and tissues of soil organisms, and substances synthesized by soil organisms.
cultured dairy product: A cultured dairy product is a fermented dairy product in which a microbial starter was introduced to the fermentation process.
food product: Food material for humans and animals which is processed with the intention that it be consumable as a whole or added to other food products.
thermoset polymer: A polymer which has been irreversibly hardened by heat-induced curing.
land fire: A fire which occurs on land, typically consuming a terrestrial ecosystem as fuel.
mass ice flow: An advective transport process during which a mass of ice is transported from one location to another.
palsa mire: Peatland typified by characteristic high mounds, each with a permanently frozen core, with wet depressions between the mounds.
desalination process: A recycling process during which the dissolved mineral salts in water are removed
broad bean: A seed of a broad bean plant (Vicia faba).
tectonic plate boundary: A geomorphological feature which is formed where two or more tectonic plates move towards, away from, or along one another, resulting in deformation of the lithosphere.
manufactured plastisphere: A plastisphere which is composed primarily of manufactured plastic.
U.S. code of federal regulations, title: Food and Drugs, title 21, Code of Federal Regulations. Original food classification in LanguaL.
sedimentation in a water body: A material accumulation process during which solid particles are pulled through a water body by gravitation or centrifugal force and which ends when they settle on a solid surface.
obsolete endolithic habitat: A habitat consisting of the spaces within rocks, such as pores between aggregate grains. Inhabited by endolithic organisms.
aquatic biome: A biome which is determined by a water body and which has ecological climax communities adapted to life in or on water.
neural tube derived brain: A brain that develops_from a neural tube.
articulation: Anatomical cluster that connects two or more adjacent skeletal elements or hardened body parts.
ectodermal part of digestive tract: A portion of the gut that is derived from ectoderm.
urogenital sinus epithelium: The fetal urogenital sinus (from which the prostate derives) is a simple cylinder of stratified basal epithelium, surrounded by mesenchyme and positioned between the embryonic bladder and pelvic urethra.
loose connective tissue: Irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a sparse irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: areolar tissue, neuroglial tissue, mucoid tissue.
irregular connective tissue: Connective tissue, which consists of a population of connective tissue cells, the intercellular matrix of which contains an irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: areolar tissue, mucoid tissue, connective tissue of peritoneum, connective tissue of fibrous pericardium.
dense connective tissue: Dense connective tissue is mainly composed of collagen type I. Crowded between the collagen fibers are rows of fibroblasts, fiber-forming cells, that manufacture the fibers. Dense connective tissue forms strong, rope-like structures such as tendons and ligaments. Tendons attach skeletal muscles to bones; ligaments connect bones to bones at joints. Ligaments are more stretchy and contain more elastic fibers than tendons. Dense connective tissue also make up the lower layers of the skin (dermis), where it is arranged in sheets.
dense irregular connective tissue: Irregular connective tissue is an irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a dense irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: connective tissue of peritoneum, connective tissue of fibrous pericardium.
environmental zone: A site which has its extent determined by the presence or influence of one or more components of an environmental system or the processes occurring therein.
ornithogenic soil: Soil which is formed from avian fecal matter.
lacustrine beach: A beach which is part of a lake shore.
lake inlet: An opening of a lake into its shore.
speed of soil drainage: The speed of some soil drainage.
alpine: An altitudinal condition which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer having a monthly mean temperature is less than 10 degrees Celsius and being located at altitudes above the tree line and below the snowline.
ecosystem fragmentation process: A process during which one or more parts of an ecosystem become causally isolated such that the direct flow or exchange of materials, resources, and energy between a given fragment and the remainder of the original system is severely curtailed or entirely halted.
facilitation: A planned process during which agents reduce the resources or effort needed to accomplish other planned process.
desalinated water: Saline water from which minerals have been removed to produce fresh water suitable for human consumption or irrigation.
role: A role is particular behaviour which a material entity may exhibit.
tropical needleleaf forest: A needleleaf forest which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
cyclone: An atmospheric storm during which a large mass of atmospheric gas rotates around a centre of low atmospheric pressure, generating high winds which spiral towards that centre.
decayed: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's decomposition into component parts.
alkaline: An medium acidity quality inhering in a solution by virtue of the bearer's a low concentration of H+ ions.
attachment quality: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having connection or association with another entity.
photosphere: An astronomical body part which is composed of those parts of a star, distal from the star's core, from which light is radiated into space.
observatory system: An observing system which generates long-term data about one or more entities of interest, typically using standardised methodology.
inedible: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer not being suitable for use as food.
irregular density: A density quality which lacks pattern.
fast neutron reactor: A nuclear reactor in which the fission chain reaction is sustained by fast neutrons.
induced magnetosphere: A magnetosphere which either 1) cannot withstand the pressure of the stellar wind interacting with it, thus allowing the stellar wind to interact with the ionosphere, atmosphere, or surface of the planet generating it or 2) is formed by the interaction of the stellar wind with an astronomical body unshielded by its own magnetosphere.
terrestrial natural environment: A natural environment which is located on a land mass.
obsolete animal-associated habitat: A habitat that is in or on a living animal. Here "animal" denotes an individual of a species that is a sub-taxon of NCBITaxon:33208.
neritic pelagic zone biome: The neritic epipelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column above a continental shelf.
external integument structure: Structures of the dermis, epidermis, glands and pigment cells recognizable on the external surfaces of the integument.
pre-chordal neural plate: The portion of neural plate anterior to the mid-hindbrain junction.
presomitic mesoderm: Unsegmented field of paraxial mesoderm present posterior to the most recently formed somite pair, from which somites will form.
solid environmental material: An environmental material which is in a solid state.
waterfall: A sudden descent of water over a step or ledge in the bed of a river.
mussel reef: A marine reef which is primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells.
tropical sclerophyllous dry forest: A sclerophyllous forest which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
mass of environmental material: An object which is composed primarily of an environmental material
mid-elevation mountain: A mountain which has a maximum elevation between 300 and 2499 metres above sea level and slopes greater than or equal to two degrees of inclination.
lagoon: A sheet of saline water separated from the open sea by sand or shingle banks. The sheet of water between an offshore reef, especially of coral and mainland. The sheet of water within a ring or horseshoe shaped atoll.
room: A building part which is separated from other building parts by one or more interior walls and, optionally, outdoor areas by one or more exterior walls.
skin of face: A zone of skin that is part of the face.
steppe soil: A portion of soil which is found in a steppe.
asbestos building roof: An asbestos building roof is a building roof that is built from asbestos.
monsoon wind: An atmospheric wind during which air masses over an ocean flow towards a land mass, driven by disequilibria between land and ocean surface temperatures.
well stimulation: A well intervention during which the production of an oil or gas well is increased by improving the flow of hydrocarbons from the reservoir into the well bore.
stream mouth: The place where a stream discharges into a lagoon, lake, or the sea.
chemically enriched sediment: Sediment which has increased levels of one or more chemical compounds.
GS1 Global Product Classification (GPC):
The Global System 1 (GS1) Global Product Classification (GPC) is a system that gives buyers and sellers a common language for grouping products in the same way, everywhere in the world.$br/$
The GS1 GPC classification in facet A is currently updated based on June 2017 release of GS1 GPC Standard for Food/Beverage/Tobacco, except for codes pertaining to tobacco. See the GS1 site for details [https://www.gs1.org/standards/gpc].
natural nuclear fission reactor: A uranium deposit where self-sustaining nuclear chain reactions have occurred.
frost wedging: A frost action process during which the pressure of water freezing in cracks, crevices, pores, joints or bedding planes results in the mechanical disintegration, splitting or break-up of rock.
chthonian planet: A planet which is formed as a result of a gas giant's hydrogen and helium atmosphere, as well as its outer layers, being stripped away by a stellar wind through photoevaporation and hydrodynamic escape.
cloud forest: A high-elevation forest ecosystem which 1) is evergreen, 2) present on mountains where there is frequent cloud and mist cover, 3) which has a large proportion of ferns and mosses in its plant communities, growing on all tree trunks and branches present in the ecosystem, and 3) harvests aerosolised water and adds it to the terrestrial water supply.
processing plant: A factory where raw materials are treated or prepared for final processing.
lake island: An island that lies in a lake.
sclerophyllous forest biome: A sclerophyllous forest which is in its climactic successional state.
weapons test site: A region at which weapons, typically military, are tested.
enveloping layer of ectoderm: Outermost layer of cells surrounding the embryo.
temperate: A temperate condition is an environmental condition in which an environmental system receives less solar irradiance than those with subpolar conditions, but greater than those with subtropical conditions.
bone meal: A mixture of crushed and coarsely ground bones that is used as an organic fertilizer for plants and formerly in animal feed.
shoot system meristem: A portion of meristem tissue (PO:0009013) that is part of a shoot system (PO:0009006).
marine tidal flow: A marine current which is maintained by a tidal flow process.
chemical entity: A chemical entity is a physical entity of interest in chemistry including molecular entities, parts thereof, and chemical substances.
car: A car is a wheeled motor vehicle used primarily for the transportation of human passengers. Most definitions of the term specify that cars are designed to run primarily on roads, to have seating for one to eight people, to typically have four wheels, and to be constructed principally for the transport of people rather than goods.
aquaculture farm: An agricultural aquatic ecosystem in which fish, crustaceans, mollusks, aquatic plants and algae are cultivated.
subdivision of skeleton: Anatomical cluster consisting of the skeletal elements (i.e. bone elements, cartilage elements, cartilage condensations) that are part of an individual subdivision of the organism. Excludes joints.
termite mound: A termite nest that is built above ground, and is made of soil, saliva, and feces, formed as a large mound.
slurry: An environmental material which is composed of insoluble solid particles suspended in a liquid.
sawah soil: Soil which is part of a sawah, a wet or irrigated rice field.
sacred site: A fiat object part which contains entities of high spiritual or cultural significance to one or more human groups.
acidic water: A portion of acidic water is a portion of water with a pH less than 7.
Y-shaped: A concave 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being shaped in the form of the letter Y.
odorless: An odor quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's lacking odour.
neutral spring: A spring through which water with a neutral pH flows.
mangrove biome: A mangrove ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
tragacanth: A naturally occurring plant-based gum, which functions as a viscous, odorless, tasteless, water-soluble mixture of polysaccharides that absorbs water to become a gel/paste.
pain clinic: A medical clinic which is used to provide pain management services.
radiation shielding disposition: An environmental disposition which inheres in an entity that intercepts, attenuates, or blocks radiation.
manufacturing process: A planned process during which raw or recycled materials are transformed into products for use or sale using labour and machines, tools, chemical and biological processing, or formulation.
cold desert: A cold desert is a desert which has hot summers and cold, dry winters with temperatures below 0 degrees Celsius
cobble sediment: Sediment characterised by an average particle diameter between 64 and 256 mm.
lake shore: That part of the land in immediate contact with a lake.
mass wasting flow: A mass wasting flow is a form of mass wasting during which the moving materials behave similarly to a flowing fluid. Water, air and ice are often involved in enabling fluidlike motion of the material.
pallet: A manufactured product which is a flat transport structure that supports goods in a stable fashion while being lifted and/or moved.
area designated for human defecation: A site which has been designated as a place where humans may defecate.
ferralsol: Ferralsols represent the classical, deeply weathered, red or yellow soils of the humid tropics. These soils have diffuse horizon boundaries, a clay assemblage dominated by low-activity clays (mainly kaolinite) and a high content of sesquioxides.
marine salt marsh sediment: Sediment that is part of a salt marsh.
oceanic mussel reef: A marine reef which is present in the depths beyond (offshore relative to) the continental shelf and primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells.
desert planet: A terrestrial planet which has a surface dominated by hot deserts.
desert scrubland: A scrubland which is located in a desert.
Lagrangian point: A site in which the combined gravitational pull of the two large astronomical bodies is such that a smaller body, affected only by gravity, can maintain a stable position relative to those two large bodies and orbit with them due to centripetal force.
clathrate material: A material which is primarily composed of a substance arranged as a lattice which can trap or contain other molecules.
fungi-associated environment: An environmental system determined by a fungal structure.
cooling of a fluid: A material cooling process during which a portion of fluid environmental material loses thermal energy to its surroundings.
englacial stream: A stream which is primarily composed of meltwater and which flows within a glacier or ice sheet.
miso food product: A food produced by fermenting rice, barley and/or soybeans, with salt and the mold koji-kin (Aspergillus oryzae).
research station: A building or collection of co-located buildings constructed for the purpose of undertaking scientific research.
utensil: A hand tool for domestic use, especially in the kitchen.
transport of waste to a designated stora: A process during which materials deemed to be waste are removed from a site and transported to another site designated for its storage.
siliceous ooze: Siliceous ooze is a marine sediment composed of the debris of plankton with silica shells, such as diatoms and radiolaria. This ooze is limited to areas with high biological productivity, such as the polar oceans, and upwelling zones near the equator. The least common type of sediment, it covers only 15% of the ocean floor. It accumulates at a slower rate than calcareous ooze: 0.2-1 cm / 1000 yr.
atmospheric aerosolised particle formati: An aerosol formation event  which occurs in an atmosphere.
mountain spur: A spur which is part of a mountain.
back-arc basin: A depression in the sea floor that results from the collision of continental plates; the weight of the sinking plate causes the overlying plate to stretch and thin, causing a basin in the overlying plate. Sometimes, the Earth's crust in these basins stretches so much it cracks, allowing magma through from the mantle beneath. Hence, basins often contain active volcanoes and hydrothermal vents.
political entity: A geographical region whose affairs and population are administered by an authority.
tarn: A mountain lake that is formed in a cirque excavated by a glacier. A moraine may form a natural dam below a tarn.
outcrop: A portion of environmental material which protrudes through a surface layer.
hedge: A dense growth of shrubbery planted as a fence or boundary.
cut: An excavation of the Earth's surface to provide passage for a road, railway, canal, etc.
increased velocity: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's increased rate of change of the position.
decreased velocity: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's decreased rate of change of the position.
fish hatchery: A hatchery in which the eggs of fish are hatched under artificial conditions.
ingestion: A feeding behavior during which material is taken into the body of an organism.
bone foramen: Anatomical space that is an opening in a bone, usually for passage of blood vessels or nerves.
saline pan: A flat expanse of ground covered with salt and other minerals, usually shining white under the sun. A salt pan is formed where water pools. A saline pan would be a lake or a pond if it were located in a climate where the rate of water evaporation were not faster than the rate of water precipitation, i.e., if it were not in a desert. If the water is unable to drain into the ground, it remains on the surface until it evaporates, leaving behind whatever minerals were dissolved. Over thousands of years, the minerals (usually salts) accumulate on the surface.
hydroclimate: A climate which is realised through hydrological processes.
lymph material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of lymph, a bodily fluid consisting of a usually clear coagulable fluid that passes from intercellular spaces of body tissue into the lymphatic vessels, is discharged into the blood by way of the thoracic duct and right lymphatic duct, and resembles blood plasma in containing white blood cells and especially lymphocytes but normally few red blood cells and no platelets.
shrubland biome: A shrubland biome is a terrestrial biome which includes, across its entire spatial extent, dense groups of shrubs.
temperature: A physical quality of the thermal energy of a system.
position: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's spatial location relative to other objects in the vicinity.
structure: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's relative position, shape, arrangements and connectivity of an organism's various parts; the pattern underlying its form.
near-infrared radiation: An infrared radiation during which waves with frequencies between 120 THz and 400 THz and with wavelengths between 2.5 micrometers and 750 nanometers are emitted by a source.
bench: A bench is a piece of furniture, on which several people may sit at the same time.
food production low-risk contamination a: A hygienic food production area containing products having a low risk of contamination.
agricultural terrace: A terrace which is used for agricultural activities.
latrine pit: A latrine pit is an artificial hole or cavity in the ground used to collect human excreta.
amorphous solid: A solid material which does not have a regularly organised internal structure.
cylindrical: A convex 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting a consistently-sized round cross section.
U-shaped: A concave 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being shaped in the form of the letter U.
organ component layer: A part of a wall of an organ that forms a layer.
subdivision of digestive tract: A proximal-distal subdivision of the digestive tract.
luvisol: Luvisols are soils that have a higher clay content in the subsoil than in the topsoil as a result of pedogenetic processes (especially clay migration) leading to an argic subsoil horizon. Luvisols have high-activity clays throughout the argic horizon and a high base saturation at certain depths.
future mouth: The primordial mouth region of the developing head.
gravel field: A field which is composed primarily of gravel.
formation of a solid aerosol from liquid: A process during which microscopic solid particulates are formed from liquid materials in an atmosphere.
decreased pressure: A pressure which is relatively low.
flow rate: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's motion characteristic.
increased pressure: A pressure which is relatively high.
slightly stratified estuary: An estuary in which river output is less than the marine input, resulting in the mixing of the whole water column by current-induced turbulence, such that salinity varies more longitudinally rather than vertically.
planted forest: A forest that has been intentionally established by human intervention.
mass liquid flow: A process whereby a volume of liquid moves due to a disequilibrium of physical forces.
concentration of carbon dioxide in seawa: The concentration of carbon dioxide when measured in seawater.
material transformation process: A process during which a portion of some environmental material is converted into a different material or a collection of materials.
tray: A manufactured product consisting of a  shallow platform designed for the carrying of items.
