loam: A soil which is composed of approximately equal proportions of sand and silt, with a smaller proportion of clay.
closure: A morphological quality pertaining to the degree to which an object contains an opening, aperture, orifice or vent.
continental divide: A watershed such that water falling on one side of the line eventually travels to one ocean or body of water, and water on the other side travels to another, generally on the opposite side of the continent.
biomass derived from sieving motile comm: Biomass which is composed primarily of motile communities sieved out of the collection tub of an autonomous reef monitoring structure (ARMS), using a 2 millimeter mesh followed by a 500 micrometre mesh.
material warming process: A process during which the temperature of a portion of environmental material is increased, along with the kinetic energy of its constituent molecules.
boundary layer: A boundary layer is a layer of fluid in the immediate vicinity of a bounding surface where the effects of viscosity are significant enough to distort the surrounding non-viscous flow.
shortwave radiation: An electromagnetic radiation process during which radiant energy with wavelengths in the visible, near-ultraviolet, or near-infrared spectra is realised.
increased area: An area which is relatively high.
decreased area: An area which is relatively low.
beer beverage: Beer is a fermented cereal beverage resulting from the fermentation most commonly of malted barley (though wheat, corn, or rice may included), by a yeast, most commonly Saccharomyces cerevisiae, and flavored by dried flowers of hops, Humulus lupulus.
pediatric unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide pediatric services.
volcanic field: A geothermal field which is prone to localized volcanic activity.
particle of clay: A particle which 1) is composed primarily of hydrous aluminium phyllosilicate minerals, in turn composed of aluminium and silicon ions bonded into tiny, thin plates by interconnecting oxygen and hydroxide ions, and 2) is or was part of a portion of clay.
transportation: A planned process that is the movement of people, animals and goods from one location to another.
bean food product: A bean vegetable food product is a human or animal food product - such as a snap, shell or dry bean product - derived from the fruit pod, seed, or leaf of one of several genera of the flowering plant family Fabaceae.
cooling of a liquid: A material cooling process during which a portion of liquid environmental material loses thermal energy to its surroundings.
elongated: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's length being notably higher than its width.
concentrated: A concentration quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting concentration.
soil percolation rate: A rate which inheres in a soil percolation process.
clastic dike: A dike formed when sediment fills a pre-existing fracture in a mass of rock.
orchard soil: Soil in which trees from an orchard grow.
cooling water: Liquid water which is a participant in a water cooling process.
future nervous system: Primordium that develops into the nervous system.
transitional anatomical structure: An embryonic anatomical entity that will turn into one or more other anatomical entities, perhaps with other anatomical entities, later in development.
entire extraembryonic component: The part of the conceptus that may be lost before birth or will be discarded at birth, or when the embryo becomes an independent organism.
aquifer: An underground layer of water-bearing permeable rock or unconsolidated materials (gravel, sand, silt, or clay) from which groundwater can be usefully extracted using a water well.
land degradation: A process which diminishes the functioning of an ecosystem located on land.
frozen land: Land which is below the freezing point of water.
pathogen-suppressive soil: Soil which has properties that restrict a pathogen's ability to establish itself, persist, or cause disease that results in long-term harm.
geological joint: A joint is a geological fracture which has no measureable shear displacement
taxicab: A taxicab is a car which may be hired, along with its operator, to transport passengers between locations of their choosing.
water ice crystal: A crystal which is primarily composed of water ice.
hydraulic fracturing: A well stimulation technique during which bedrock formations are fractured through the injection of pressurized proppant-bearing liquid into a well-bore.
calcic spring: A mineral spring through which water with elevated concentrations of calcium hydroxide flows.
pectoral girdle skeleton: A subdivision of a limb or fin skeleton consisting of bones which connects the upper limb or fin to the axial skeleton on each side. It consists of the clavicle and scapula in humans and, in those species with three bones in the pectoral girdle, the coracoid. Some mammalian species (e.g. the dog and the horse) have only the scapula. In humans, the only joints between the shoulder girdle and axial skeleton are the sternoclavicular joints on each side. No joint exists between each scapula and the rib cage; instead the muscular connection between the two permits relatively great mobility of the shoulder girdle in relation to the pelvic girdle. In those species having only the scapula, no joint exists between the forelimb and the thorax, the only attachment being muscular[WP]. Examples: There are only two instances, right and left pectoral girdle skeletons.
animal-associated environment: An environmental system determined by an animal.
minor planet: A minor planet is an astronomical object in direct orbit around the Sun that is neither a planet nor exclusively classified as a comet. Minor planets can be dwarf planets, asteroids, trojans, centaurs, Kuiper belt objects, and other trans-Neptunian objects.
vapourisation: A material transformation process during which a liquid material transitions into a gas phase.
anal membrane endodermal component: An endoderm that is part of a anal region.
mobile phone: A mobile phone is a telephone which transmits sound information to a mobile phone network via radio transmissions.
stable bandage: A bandage wrap used on the lower legs of a horse.
heteroorganic entity: A heteroorganic entity is an organic molecular entity in which carbon atoms or organic groups are bonded directly to one or more heteroatoms.
channel of an intermittent stream: A channel through which a directional flow of water periodically occurs, ceasing when bed seepage or evapotranspiration exceed the available water supply.
lixisol: Lixisols are soils that have a higher clay content in the subsoil than in the topsoil as a result of pedogenetic processes (especially clay migration) leading to an argic subsoil horizon. Lixisols have a high base saturation and low-activity clays at certain depths.
subatomic particle: A particle smaller than an atom.
violent environment: An environment in which humans are exposed to regularly occurring physical or emotional violence.
trimethylamine enriched soil: A portion of trimethylamine enriched soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of trimethylamine.
polling booth: A booth which enables a voter to vote confidentially.
alluvial paddy field soil: Alluvial soil whichi is part of a paddy field.
lava flow process: A process in which a volume of lava emitted during an effusive eruption moves along a solid surface.
active anaerobic enrichment culturing un: An active enrichment culturing unit which contains environmental material maintained under conditions with no free oxygen.
river: A stream which, through permanent or seasonal flow processes, moves from elevated land towards lower elevations through a definite channel and empties either into a sea, lake, or another river or ends on land as bed seepage and evapotranspiration exceed water supply.
shoot axis: A plant axis (PO:0025004) that is part of a shoot system (PO:0009006).
root system: A collective plant organ structure (PO:0025007) that produces root meristems (PO:0006085), the plant structures (PO:0009011) that arise from them and the parts thereof.
quality of a foam: A physical quality which inheres in a liquid or solid bearer by virtue of that bearer trapping a gas in a colloidal suspension throughout its volume.
obsolete livestock-associated habitat: Livestock is an animal-associated habitat consisting of any domestic or domesticated animal intentionally raised for food or in the production of food or raised as stock to produce food or fibre, in an agricultural setting or for its labour or pen-raised animals raised on licensed game farm operations. Livestock include: bovine animals (including buffalo and bison), ovine animals, porcine animals, caprine animals, , poultry, bees, equine animals, cervidae animals; animals of the genus Lama; ratites (Emu, Ostrich, and Rhea), fish or shellfish in aquaculture facilities, and enclosed domesticated rabbits or hares raised for human food or fiber.
glue: A function realised by an environmental material when used to bind material entities together.
concentration of nitrogen atom in enviro: The concentration of a nitrogen atom when measured in environmental material.
particle: A mass of solid material which is either 1) a minute fragment of a larger mass or 2) one of a collection of small masses composing an aggregate.
public subway train: A subway train which is owned by a government or other form of public representation.
algal production: A process during which the algal cells constituting an algal bloom produce biomass from abiotic components during photosynthesis.
lake water: Water which is part of a lake.
endorheic basin: A drainage basin from which there is no outflow of water, either on the surface as rivers, or underground by flow or diffusion through rock or permeable material.
thermoplastic material: An environmental material which is capable of, repeatedly, becoming plastic when heated and hardening again when cooled.
morphological feature: A part of an organism or organ that is continuous with its surroundings and distinguished from its surroundings based on morphology.
material diffusion process: A material transport process during which material moves from a region of higher concentration to a region of lower concentration.
heavy fraction material: An environmental material which is denser than bromoform.
cerumen: The yellow or brown waxy secretions produced by vestigial apocrine sweat glands in the external ear canal[MESH].
organic molecular entity: Any molecular entity that contains carbon.
lateral ventricle choroid plexus epithel: A choroid plexus epithelium that is part of a lateral ventricle [Automatically generated definition].
eye muscle: A muscle that is part of the eye region.
umbrisol: Umbrisols are soils in which organic matter has accumulated within the mineral surface soil (in most cases with low base saturation) to the extent that it significantly affects the behaviour and utilization of the soil.
supranational geopolitical entity: A political entitity established by more than one state and with at least some influence over the affairs of its member states.
area of sedge- and forb-dominated herbac: An area of a planet's surface which is primarily covered by sedges or forbs, possibly interpersed with grasses or grass-like plants. This area is in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.
atmosphere: An atmosphere is a layer of gases surrounding a material body of sufficient mass that is held in place by the gravity of the body.
area designated as a nature reserve: A protected area of importance for wildlife, flora, fauna or features of geological or other special interest, which is reserved and managed for conservation and to provide special opportunities for study or research. Nature reserves may be designated by government institutions in some countries, such as the United Kingdom, or by private landowners, such as charities and research institutions, regardless of nationality.
obsolete submarine volcano: An underwater fissures in the earth's surface from which magma can erupt.
shear fracture: A geological fracture across which shear displacement has occurred
planned burn: A fire which is planned and executed deliberately under human supervision.
wing dam: A dam that only partly restricts a waterway, creating a faster channel that resists the accumulation of sediment.
man-made tunnel: A tunnel constructed by human means.
flood meadow ecosystem: An area of grassland or pasture beside a river, subject to seasonal flooding.
nest of ant: A pile of earth, sand, pine needles, or clay or a composite of these and other materials that build up at the entrances of the subterranean dwellings of ant colonies as they are excavated. A colony is built and maintained by legions of worker ants, who carry tiny bits of dirt and pebbles in their mandibles and deposit them near the exit of the colony. They normally deposit the dirt or vegetation at the top of the hill to prevent it from sliding back into the colony, but in some species they actively sculpt the materials into specific shapes, and may create nest chambers within the mound.
frost heaving process: Frost heaving is a process during which an upwards swelling of soil occurs due to freezing conditions caused by an increasing presence of ice as it grows towards the surface.
atmospheric zone: An environmental zone which is part of an atmosphere.
cow material: Material that derives from some cow.
hot dog: A hot dog is a moist sausage of soft, even texture and flavor, often made from advanced meat recovery or meat slurry. Most types are fully cooked, cured or smoked. It is often placed hot in a special purpose soft, sliced hot dog bun.
vascular plexus: A vascular network formed by frequent anastomoses between the blood vessels (arteries or veins) of a part.
marine pycnocline: A pycnocline which is part of a marine water body and composed primarily of ocean water.
tectonic lake: A lake which is contained in a depression formed by the deformation and resulting lateral and vertical movements of a lithosphere.
waste recycling process: A process during which materials deemed as waste are separated and converted into a form which can be used as input by the same processes which generated them.
bakery food product: Food material which is output of or is part of a home or commercial bakery process.
mine drainage: The outflow of water from a mine.
vasculature: An interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure contains fluid that is actively transported around the organism[ZFA]. Examples: vasculature of lung, vasculature of face.
second year ice: Sea ice which is thicker than first year ice, and has survived a seasonal melting process.
biodegradation: A biological process during which a material entity is broken down.
plant litter: Leaf litter is dead plant material, such as leaves, bark, needles, and twigs, that has fallen to the ground.
ethnic food shop: A food shop in which the food products on offer are restricted to those produced in a region and cultural setting other than that of the shop's locality.
Limburger cheese food product: A very strong smelling, soft cow's milk cheese made by fermentation involving the bacterium Brevibacterium linens.
soda spring: A mineral spring through which water with elevated levels of dissolved carbon dioxide gas flows.
petroleum enriched sediment: Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of petroleum.
open cage mariculture facility: A construction which contains the equipment needed to perform mariculture in open cages - permitting the exchange of material with the surrounding marine water.
ecosystem-wide respiration: A process which consists of all respiration processes instantiated in an ecosystem.
gastrointestinal system epithelium: An epithelium that is part of a digestive system [Automatically generated definition].
respiratory system epithelium: An epithelium that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].
landslide lake: A lake which fills a depression where drainage is blocked by solid material transported by a landslide.
human house: A human house is a house which provides a dwelling-place for humans.
marine tidal flow process: A tidal flow process which occurs in an ocean or sea and during which tidal movements generate advective flows, often amplified in velocity when moving through an inlet, pass or channel.
water table: A surface layer which is 1) part of a phreatic zone in contact with a vadose zone and 2) contains interstitial water with a pressure head equal to atmospheric pressure.
outhouse: An outhouse is a small structure, separate from a main building, which covers a pit latrine or a dry toilet.
galaxy: A galaxy is a gravitationally bound system of stars, stellar remnants, interstellar gas, dust, and dark matter.
salt glacier: A mass of salt which has erupted onto a planetary surface, usually through sedimentary rock.
andosol: Andosols are soils that develop in volcanic ejecta or glasses under almost any climate (except under hyperarid climate conditions). However, Andosols may also develop in other silicate-rich materials under acid weathering in humid and perhumid climates.
healthcare environment: An anthropogenic environment which is bounded by a healthcare facility in which health care services are provided by specialized staff and equipment.
decreased rate of occurrence: A rate of occurrence that is relatively low.
increased rate of occurrence: A rate of occurrence that is relatively high.
immune organ: An organ that is part of a immune system [Automatically generated definition].
safe environment for living organisms: An environment in which living organisms have a low likelihood of being harmed or killed
prepared food product (eurofir): This subgroup includes multicomponent meals, sauces, retail salads, desserts, soups, snacks and other foods where similarity of the product type is more significant than the source of the principal ingredient(s).
decreased amount: An amount which is relatively low.
organismal quality: A quality that inheres in an entire organism or part of an organism.
neonatal intensive care unit: An intensive care unit (ICU) specializing in the care of ill or premature newborn infants.
water-based rainfall: A hydrological precipitation process in which atmospheric water vapour condenses to form droplets of liquid water massive enough to fall to a planetary surface due to the planet's gravity.
tephra: Tephra is fragmental material produced by a volcanic eruption regardless of composition, fragment size or emplacement mechanism.
glacial surface layer: A solid surface layer which is that part of a glacier in contact with a planetary atmosphere, water body, or solid material partially surrounding that glacier.
pasture: A grassland ecosystem which is used for grazing of ungulate livestock as part of a farm or ranch.
mediterranean forest biome: A mediterranean forest in which is in its climactic successional state.
concentration of nitrate and nitrite in: The concentration of nitrate and nitrite when measured in liquid water.
amniotic fluid material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of amniotic fluid, a bodily fluid consisting of watery liquid surrounding and cushioning a growing fetus within the amnion. It allows the fetus to move freely without the walls of the uterus being too tight against its body. Buoyancy is also provided.
peat cut: An artificial working of peatland to remove the peat.
wetland ecosystem: A terrestrial ecosystem which is inundated or saturated by surface or ground water at a frequency and duration sufficient to support, and that under normal circumstances does support, a prevalence of vegetation typically adapted for life in saturated soil conditions.
tombolo: A deposition landform such as a spit or bar which forms a narrow piece of land between an island or offshore rock and a mainland shore, or between two islands or offshore rocks. They usually form because the island causes wave refraction, depositing sand and shingle moved by longshore drift in each direction around the island where the waves meet. Eustatic sea level rise may also contribute to accretion as material is pushed up with rising sea levels.
increased functionality: A functional quality held by the bearer when the latter exhibits increased ability to perform a regular function(s).
decreased functionality: A functionality quality held by the bearer when the latter exhibits decreased ability to perform a regular function(s).
aggregated: A spatial pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being gathered or tending to gather into a mass or whole.
Bailey bridge: A bridge which is a truss bridge, pre-fabricated, and portable.
fruit or fruit product (us cfr): Fruit in all forms; includes fruit juices and fruit juice drinks, fruit butters, jellies, preserves, and related products.
interplate earthquake: A tectonic earthquake which occurs at the boundary between two tectonic plates.
hypersaline water environment: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by hypersaline water.
lava planet: A planet which has a surface layer that nearly completely or completely covered by lava, and which has a substantial portion of its mass composed of lava.
hailstorm: An atmospheric storm during which intense hailfall occurs
gas molecular entity: Any main group molecular entity that is gaseous at standard temperature and pressure (STP; 0degreeC and 100 kPa).
hydrothermally-influenced sediment: Sediment through which hydrothermally modified fluids flow, altering its properties through interaction with their own.
river channel: A stream channel which contains a river.
beverage food product: A liquid prepared for consumption, or a product that can be combined with water or milk to make one.
spice food product: A food product derived from a spice.
NSIDC blizzard: A blizzard which has 1) winds of 35 miles per hour (approximately 56 kilometers per hour), 2) lasts for a period of at least three hours, and 3) occurs in extremely cold temperatures.
amictic lake: A lake which is permanently covered by ice, does not mix, and exhibit inverse cold water stratification whereby water temperature increases with depth below the ice surface.
kame: An irregularly shaped hill or mound composed of sorted or stratified sand and gravel that is deposited in contact with the glacial ice. It can have an irregular shape. Kames are often associated with kettles, and this is referred to as kame and kettle topography. When the ice retreats further, the delta kame often collapses. Kame terraces are frequently found along the side of a glacial valley and are the deposits of meltwater streams flowing between the ice and the adjacent valley side.
gravel pit: A quarry from which gravel is extracted.
composting toilet: A composting toilet fixture is a dry toilet fixture in which managed, aerobic decomposition converts human excreta into organic matter suitable for the fertilisation or amendment of soils.
area of low atmospheric pressure: A gaseous part of an atmosphere in which gases have reduced atmospheric pressure.
along-front current: A marine surface current that flows along an oceanic front.
mediterranean forest: A forest ecosystem which is subject to mediterranean environmental conditions.
saddle dam: An auxiliary dam constructed to confine the reservoir created by a primary dam either to permit a higher water elevation and storage or to limit the extent of a reservoir for increased efficiency.
tectonic earthquake: An earthquake caused by the sudden release of energy accumulated in an astronomical body's crust, as the elastic strain placed on constituent rock masses causes them to fracture.
lupin seed food product: A product of the  dry seeds of Lupinus spp.
termite subterranean nest: A termite nest that is underground, often connected to food sources through a network of tunnels.
subtropical broadleaf forest: A broadleaf forest which is subject to subtropical climate conditions.
area of attached faunal communities: An environmental zone within which ecological communities of  animals are attached to some substrate.
piece(s) of animal: One or more pieces of animals.
englacial: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being located within a glacier or ice sheet, between their summer surface or bed.
lake coast: The general region of indefinite width that extends from a lake inland to the first major change in terrain features.
graben: A depressed block of land bordered by parallel faults. A graben is the result of a block of land being downthrown producing a valley with a distinct scarp on each side. Grabens often occur side-by-side with horsts. Horst and graben structures are indicative of tensional forces and crustal stretching.
permafrost congelation ice: Water ice which has formed in a mass of permafrost.
mangrove biome soil: Soil which is located in a mangrove biome.
organism: A material entity that is an individual living system, such as animal, plant, bacteria or virus, that is capable of replicating or reproducing, growth and maintenance in the right environment. An organism may be unicellular or made up, like humans, of many billions of cells divided into specialized tissues and organs.
fossil worm burrow: A channel which was formed as a result of an annelid burrowing through soil, where organic residues lining the burrow have subsequently initiated fossilization.
sheet-iron exterior wall: A sheet-iron exterior wall is an exterior wall that is built from sheets of iron.
badland: An arid terrain with clay-rich soil that has been extensively eroded by wind and water.
dry microburst: A microburst during which no or very little rain is generated.
ice calving process: A process during which a part of an ice mass breaks away from the main mass.
nitrogen cycling: A biogeochemical cycle which has nitrogen-bearing chemical entities as participants.
biopolymer: A polymer which is the output of a biological process.
charcuterie shop: A delicatessen which prepares and sells preserved meat products.
polluted river: A river which has elevated levels of contaminants.
archaeal cell culture: A microbial cell culture which is primarily composed of archaeal biomass.
contaminated animal feed: Contaminated animal feed is an animal feed that has become contaminated with or come contact with microorganisms or toxic chemicals.
scrubland area: Area covered with low-growing or stunted perennial vegetation and usually not mixed with trees.
quicksand bed: A bed which is composed of quicksand forming a soft, shifting mass that yields easily to pressure.
small freshwater river ecosystem: A freshwater river ecosystem which has its functions and composition determined by a small freshwater river.
geological subsidence: A material transport process during which a geological surface shifts downward relative to a datum such as sea-level.
seep: A seep is a spring in which water has filtered through permeable earth to the surface.
slush ice: A slurry of frazil, snow, and liquid water.
saline water aquarium: A saline water aquarium is an aquarium which contains saline water as its primary ecological medium.
resin (gum) varnish: A varnish containing a natural, plant- or insect-derived substance dissolved in a solvent, called spirit varnish or solvent varnish.
pier: A raised walkway over water, supported by piles or pillars.
vegetated hill: A hill which has a surface that is partially or wholly covered by plant communities.
concentration of chloride in water: The concentration of a chloride when measured in water.
autoclaved sand: Autoclaved sand is sand that has been sterlised by exposure to high pressure saturated steam at at least 121 degrees Celsius.
nival: An altitudinal condition which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer having extremely limited vegetation cover, silica-enriched soils, and ground cover dominated by snow and ice at altitudes above the snowline.
pus material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of pus, a bodily fluid consisting of a whitish-yellow or yellow substance produced during inflammatory responses of the body that can be found in regions of pyogenic bacterial infections. Pus is produced from the dead and living cells which travel into the intercellular spaces around the affected cells.
hydrogel: A gel which is primarily composed of a network of polymer chains that are hydrophilic, sometimes found as a colloidal gel in which water is the dispersion medium.
tropical thorn forest: This class is one of the forest types as identified by the updated Global Forest Map (GFM 2000).
musculature of pectoral complex: Any collection of muscles that is part of a pectoral complex. The pectoral complex comprises the pectoral girdle and the associated limb or fin.
covered pit latrine with slab floor: A covered pit latrine with slab is a building which comprises a pit latrine with a slab floor sheltered by an outhouse.
haematology unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide haematological medical services.
spacecraft: A vehicle designed to fly in outer space.
petting zoo: A petting zoo is a zoological garden which contains domesticated non-human animals and some wild non-human animals that are docile enough for humans to touch and feed.
chalybeate spring: A spring through which water with elevated concentrations of iron salts flows.
neonatal unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide neonatal medical services.
deformed: A morphological quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being distorted in form.
calf shed: A cow shed for baby cows/bulls.
area: A 2-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's two dimensional extent.
tertiary referral hospital: A hospital which is used to provide tertiary care.
rapid transit system: A public transit system which is owned by a government or other form of public representation.
wheel: A manufactured product consisting of a  disk-shaped material that rotates around an axle bearing placed through a hole in its center.
environmental material: A material entity which other material entities in an environmental system are primarily or partially composed of.
littoral rainforest biome: A littoral rainforest which is in its climactic successional state.
pneumatic drill: A hand tool that uses air-power to drill holes or destroy hard surfaces like rock, concrete, or asphalt
cardinal direction: The four cardinal directions or cardinal points are the directions north, east, south, and west, commonly denoted by their initials, N, E, S, W. East and west are at right angles to north and south, with east being in the clockwise direction of rotation from north and west being directly opposite east.
north: North is one of the four compass points or cardinal directions. It is the opposite of south and is perpendicular to east and west.
west: West is one of the four cardinal directions or points of the compass. It is the opposite direction from east.
south: South is one of the four cardinal directions or compass points. South is the polar opposite of north and is perpendicular to east and west.
east: East is one of the four cardinal directions or points of the compass. It is the opposite direction from west.
texture: A morphologic quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's relative size, organization and distribution of its surface elements or the representation or invention of the appearance of its surface; visual and tactile surface characteristics.
stagnant water: A liquid water which has no current or flow and is susceptible to contamination by pathogens or pathogenic vectors.
brown sea ice: Sea ice which has a brown colouration, either due to 1) the presence of pigments which are or were contained in the members of ecological assemblages, such as algal communities, living or trapped within the ice or 2) due to the presence of trapped sediments.
school building: An institutional building in which students are educated.
icefall: A portion of a glacier characterized by rapid flow, a chaotic crevassed surface, and a pronounced, at times vertical, slope.
piece of gravel: A piece of rock which is between two and 64 millimetres in length along its largest dimension.
igneous extrusion: A mass of igneous rock formed when hot magma flows out (extrudes) onto a planetary surface as lava or explodes violently into the atmosphere to fall back as pyroclastics or tuff.
illegal settlement: A settlement on land that the inhabitants have no legal claim to or occupy illegally.
occurrent: An entity that has temporal parts and that happens, unfolds or develops through time.
atmospheric Taylor column: An atmospheric Taylor column is a Taylor column that is formed in the atmosphere. Atmospheric Taylor columns often form above islands resulting in vortex streets in the atmosphere.
moist-adiabatic process: An adiabatic process which involves air saturated with water vapour and the presence of liquid water.
shady environment: An environmental system which is shielded from direct stellar irradiation by material entities.
nesting material: Nesting material is an animal habitation consisting of matierals used to cushion, insulate and protect the young of the organism. The adult will use the material to form a protective structure to house and raise their young. Nests are built primarily by birds, but also by mammals, fish, insects and reptiles.
magnetic energy: potential energy due to or stored in magnetic fields.
gravitational energy: potential energy due to or stored in gravitational fields.
chemical energy: Potential energy which is stored in chemical bonds and realised through reactions which break them..
chromodynamic energy: Potential energy due to the energy of the gluon-mediated field of the strong force, binding quarks together into hadrons.
sound wave energy: Mechanical wave energy which is realised when an acoustic wave propagates through a material.
electric energy: potential energy due to or stored in electric fields.
ionization energy: potential energy that binds an electron to its atom or molecule.
elastic energy: potential energy due to the deformation of a material (or its container) exhibiting a restorative force.
nuclear energy: potential energy that binds nucleons to form the atomic nucleus (and nuclear reactions).
mechanical wave energy: Wave energy which inheres in an elastic material and is realised when a deformational wave passes through that material.
independent continuant: b is an independent continuant = Def. b is a continuant which is such that there is no c and no t such that b s-depends_on c at t. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [017-002])
podzol: Podzols are soils with a typically ash-grey upper subsurface horizon, bleached by loss of organic matter and iron oxides, on top of a dark accumulation horizon with brown, reddish or black illuviated humus and/or reddish Fe compounds. Podzols occur in humid areas in the boreal and temperate zones and locally also in the tropics.
sandy desert: A desert plain characterized by a surface veneer of sand.
acrisol: Acrisols are soils that have a higher clay content in the subsoil than in the topsoil as a result of pedogenetic processes (especially clay migration) leading to an argic subsoil horizon. Acrisols have in certain depths a low base saturation and low-activity clays.
hair ice: A type of water ice that forms on dead wood with the assistance of the fungus Exidiopsis effusa and takes the shape of fine, silky hair.
fermented soybean food product: A food product having fermented soyabeans as a defining ingredient
white smoker: A hydrothermal vent found on the ocean floor which emits lighter-hued minerals, such as those containing barium, calcium and silicon. These alkaline hydrothermal vents also continuously generate acetyl thioesters, providing both the starting point for more complex organic molecules and the energy needed to produce them.
freshwater macrophyte farming process: An aquaculture process during which humans rear freshwater macrophytes.
cardiopharyngeal field: An region of the mesoderm that includes anterior lateral mesoderm of the first heart field plus contiguous pharyngeal mesoderm that gives rise to second-heart-field-derived regions of the heart and branchiomeric muscles.
biodegradation of plastic: A biodegradation process during which plastic is broken down.
garden soil: A portion of soil which is found in a garden.
marine Taylor column: A marine Taylor column is a Taylor column that is formed in a marine body of water. Currents flowing over shoaling topography such as seamounts are accelerated and destabilised, resulting in Taylor columns. Eddies and internal waves are generated downstream of the topological feature and may extend 1000 m or so above them. This may result in a localised increase in primary production where the Taylor column reaches surface waters.
food production high-risk contamination: A hygienic food production area containing food products that are not subjected to subsequent microbial decontamination, and where there is a risk of pathogen or microbial spoilage growth.
full-spectrum EM radiation quality: An EM radiation quality that is independent of the EM wavelength range.
albedo: A reflective quality restricted to a particular wavelength.
luminous flux: A scalar optical quality which obtains by the magnitude of the light emitted by the bearer.
radiation reflective quality: A scalar EM radiation quality which obtains by the capacity of the bearer to scatter or reflect radiation.
microplastic particle: A piece of plastic which has a diameter less than five millimetres.
freshwater lake biome: A freshwater lake ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
ocean strait: An ocean strait is a strait which connects two oceans.
nautical squall: A storm which is nautical, localised, and of high severity local storm considered as a whole: that is, winds and cloud mass and (if any) precipitation, thunder and lightning.
carbon sequestration process: A material accumulation process during which atmospheric carbon dioxide is captured and stored.
marine cold-water sphere: The marine cold-water sphere describes a water mass extending from the polar seas and across low latitudes at depths of ca. 800 to 1000 m, which is separated from the marine warm-water sphere by the permanent marine thermocline
sea ice formation process: A material transformation process during which seawater freezes into sea ice.
lacquer: A category of hard and potentially shiny (clear or colored) finishes which can be applied to materials including wood or metal.
feed storage space: A physical space, which may or may not be in a construction, which is used to store animal feed for agricultural purposes.
convective: A physical quality of a process which is characteristic of processes that transport material within a volume due to the combined effects of material property heterogeneity and body forces across that volume.
peeler: A hand tool used to remove the outer layer of vegetables and fruit, consisting of a handle attached to a metal blade with a slot with a sharp edge.
temperate mixed needleleaf forest: A temperate mixed forest which has communities of trees composed primarily of species with needle-like leaves (e.g. conifers).
obsolete tropical upwelling biome: Please use the appropriate terms in the marine biome branch in combination with the marine upwelling feature to specify an environment characterised by a marine upwelling (2010-03-15, PLB)
frozen soil: Soil which is below the freezing point of water.
water raindrop: This is the class intended for use when describing raindrops on Earth. These typically have a diamter of  0.1 to 9 millimetres.
polytunnel: An industrial building made from steel and covered in polyethylene used for plant cultivation.
warehouse: An industrial building which is used to store goods.
air filter: An air filter is a device that removes some substance from air.
talus slope: A talus slope is a slope which has a surface layer composed of scree.
area of perennial snow: An area of a planet's surface which is primarily composed of snow, present throughout multiple years, in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.
cold environment: An environment which has a lower temperature than some local or global average.
odor: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's molecules being are aerially dispersed and perceived by an odorant receptor.
morphology: A quality of a single physical entity inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer's size or shape or structure.
shape: A morphological quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ratios of distances between its features (points, edges, surfaces and also holes etc).
occurrence: A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's occurrence.
environment determined by a biofilm on a: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by a biofilm on a surface which is exposed to non-saline materials.
skeleton of lower jaw: A subdivision of the skeleton that corresponds to the lower part of the mouth. The lower jaw skeleton includes the following elements, when present: lower jaw teeth, the mandible and other lower jaw bones, and Meckel's cartilage.
usage of an environment for recreation: A planned environmental usage process during which humans access an environment in order to promote the refreshment of their physical and psychological health through relaxation and leisure activities.
swamp forest: A class created to group GFM 2000 terms by the dominant vegetation type. Definitions pending.
surface of an astronomical body: A surface layer where the solid or liquid material of an astronomical body comes into contact with an atmosphere or outer space.
desublimation of water vapour into ice: A desublimation process during which water vapour is frozen into water ice.
mariculture process: An aquaculture process during which marine organisms are cultivated in the open ocean, an enclosure in the ocean, or in tanks, ponds or raceways which are filled with seawater.
glacial run: A water flow process which comprises a sudden‐onset high‐magnitude discharge of water and sediment from a glacial source
emulsion: A mixture of two immiscible (unblendable) substances. One substance (the dispersed phase) is dispersed in the other (the continuous phase).
hindgut: The caudalmost subdivision of a digestive tract.
foregut: Anterior subdivision of a digestive tract.
neural tube: In the developing vertebrate, the neural tube is the embryo's precursor to the central nervous system, which comprises the brain and spinal cord. The neural groove gradually deepens as the neural folds become elevated, and ultimately the folds meet and coalesce in the middle line and convert the groove into a closed tube, the neural tube or neural canal (which strictly speaking is the center of the neural tube), the ectodermal wall of which forms the rudiment of the nervous system. [WP,unvetted].
intermittently filled reservoir: A reservoir that is not permanently filled with water, at times being dry.
Haber-Bosch process: A chemical engineering process that produces ammonia en masse via artificial nitrogen fixation.
objective specification: A directive information entity that describes an intended process endpoint. When part of a plan specification the concretization is realized in a planned process in which the bearer tries to effect the world so that the process endpoint is achieved.
hydrological evaporation: Hydrological evaporation is the evaporation of water, generally as part of a planetary water cycle.
recreational cruise ship: A boat which provides short-term residential and entertainment facilities to passengers.
globular star cluster: A group of gravitationally bound stars.
tropical lower montane forest: A high-elevation forest which is located in a region subject to tropical climate patterns modulated by sufficient elevation to encounter lower montane climatic patterns.
headwater: The upper part of a river system, denoting the upper basin and source streams of a river.
opacity: An optical quality which obtains by virtue of the ability of the bearer to absorb visible light.
brown: A color consisting of dark orange, red, of very low intensity.
water filter: A manufactured product which is used to remove contaminants from water impeding the flow of particles or solutes.
usage of an environment for defence: A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports activities which aim to protect citizens or any geographical area by preparing for or by using military means to resist the attack of an enemy.
grooved: Texture quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being marked with one or more channels.
platelike: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being roundish, flattish shape, possibly with a slightly angled edge.
flattened: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's surface becoming more extended in a plane.
marine park area: A protected area of the sea usually established to preserve a specific habitat and ensure the ecosystem is sustained for the organisms that exist there. Most marine parks are designated by governments, and organized like watery national parks.
environmental zone of processual equilib: An environmental zone in which the rates of two or more processes are roughly equal to one another.
hydrological condensation process: Hydrological condensation is a process in which atmospheric water vapour undergoes a phase transition from the gas phase to the liquid phase.
decreased length: A length quality which is relatively small.
increased length: A length quality which is relatively large.
warm season: A season during which the average temperature of a planetary part exceeds that of all other seasons it endures during a season generating process.
erosionally enriched ice: Water ice which contains material liberated during an erosion process.
biotransformation of biomass into mixed: A biotransformation process that produces mixed alcohols from from biomass via fermentation.
aftershock: A tectonic earthquake which 1) is embedded in a series of tectonic earthquakes, linked to the same release of energy in the crust and 2) occurs after the mainshock.
postcranial axial skeleton: The postcranial subdivision of skeleton structural components forming the long axis of the vertebrate body; in Danio, consisting of the notochord, vertebrae, ribs, supraneurals, intermuscular bones, and unpaired median fins; in human consists of the bones of the vertebral column, the thoracic cage and the pelvis[ZFA+FMA].
appendicular skeleton: Subdivision of skeleton which which consists of all the skeletal elements in in the pectoral and pelvic appendage complexes[cjm].
skin of body: The organ covering the body that consists of the dermis and epidermis.
cardiac septum: The thin membranous structure between the two heart atria or the thick muscular structure between the two heart ventricles.
gravel: An environmental material which is composed primarily of pieces of gravel.
atmosphere-exposed melt pond: A melt pond which has a surface exposed to the atmosphere.
pain management unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide pain management.
environmental system process quality: The quality of a environmental system process.
marine bathyal zone biome: The marine bathyal zone biome comprises regions of the marine benthic biome between approximately 200 m and 3000 m depth. This zone generally coincides with the continental slope.
ice calf: An ice mass which has calved off an larger mass of ice.
container of an intermittent saline lake: A depression that is periodically filled with saline water, forming a saline lake.
geological fracture: A geological fracture is any separation in a geologic formation, such as a joint or a fault that divides a mass of rock into two or more pieces.
solubility of carbon atom in soil: The solubility of a carbon atom when measured in soil.
flood control reservoir: A reservoir constructed for the purpose of containing a flood, an overflow of water from a body of water that sumerges land.
baseboard: A building part consisting of a board covering the joint between the lowest part of an interior wall surface and the floor.
candle: A candle is a lamp composed of a wax within which an ignitable wick is embedded.
urban biome: An urban biome is a dense settlement biome which has been urbanised.
Bathymodiolus gill tissue material: Mussel gill tissue material which is part of a member of the genus Bathymodiolus.
area of attached mussel assemblages: An area which is dominated by dense accumulations of mussels attached to a substrate other than conspecifics, including the associated faunal communities and predators present on the mussels (e.g., starfish).
contaminated soil: A portion of contaminated soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of some contaminant.
pour-flush toilet fixture: A flush toilet fixture into which water is manually poured to dispose of excreta.
arid: An environmental condition in which annual precipitation is less than half of annual potential evapotranspiration.
primary atmosphere: A planetary atmosphere which is formed as a result of the accretion of gaseous matter from the accretion disc of the planet's star.
ice ablation zone: An environmental zone which overlaps a glacier or an ice sheet, and in which ice loss exceeds ice gain.
light fraction material: An environmental material which is less dense than bromoform.
saliva material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of saliva, a slightly alkaline secretion of water, mucin, protein, salts, and often a starch-splitting enzyme (as ptyalin) that is secreted into the mouth by salivary glands, lubricates ingested food, and often begins the breakdown of starches.
marine subtidal rocky reef biome: The marine rocky subtidal reef biome comprises regions of the marine reef biome composed mainly of rock and which harbour abundant communities of algae and invertebrates. These reefs are often very patchy, with alterations of rocks dominated by rich invertebrate assemblages and turf-forming calcareous red algae.
chair: A chair is a piece of furniture with a raised surface commonly used to seat a single person.
organic dairy farm: A dairy farm which is managed using practices certified to be organic by a competent authority.
plant aquaculture process: An aquaculture process during which humans rear plants.
biological waste material: Biological waste is waste containing mostly natural organic materials (remains of plants, animal excrement, biological sludge from waste-water treatment plants and so forth).
refrigerant: A substance used in a thermodynamic heat pump cycle or refrigeration cycle that undergoes a phase change from a gas to a liquid and back. Refrigerants are used in air-conditioning systems and freezers or refrigerators and are assigned a "R" number (by ASHRAE - formerly the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air Conditioning Engineers), which is determined systematically according to their molecular structure.
whirlpool: A large, swirling body of water produced by ocean tides.
polar mountain: A mountain that is part of a polar environment.
refinery: A human construction which is used to process materials into forms that have increased value or utility in downstream processes.
range of mounts: A field which includes at least two mounts connected by high ground and arranged in an approximately linear fashion.
soil surface layer: A surface layer which is composed primarily of soil.
wet microburst: A microburst during which large amounts of rain are generated.
processed material: Is a material entity that is created or changed during material processing.
cropland biome: A cropland ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
fluid environmental material: An environmental material which is unable to resist shear forces and continuously deforms when subject to them.
alkaline water: A portion of alkaline water is a portion of water with a pH greater than 7.
dermis: The dermis is a layer of skin between the epidermis (with which it makes up the skin) and subcutaneous tissues, and is composed of two layers, the papillary and reticular dermis[WP].
transvasement: An aquaduct to transport water from one river basin to another one, to solve problems of hydrographic imbalance. It can decrease floods, moving the water to lands with droughts.
thoracic segment bone: A bone that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].
nerve of thoracic segment: A nerve that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].
bone of reproductive organ: A bone that is part of a reproductive organ.
mid-ocean ridge: An underwater mountain range, formed by plate tectonics. This uplifting of the ocean floor occurs when convection currents rise in the mantle beneath the oceanic crust and create magma where two tectonic plates meet at a divergent boundary. The mid-ocean ridges of the world are connected and form a single global mid-oceanic ridge system that is part of every ocean.
respiratory system connective tissue: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].
ephemeral island: An island, usually the consequence of the activity of a submarine volcano, that only exists for a short period or short periods of time after its formation, then being eroded or otherwise disappearing beneath the surface of a body of water.
saline marsh: A marsh whose water contains a considerable quantity of dissolved salts.
old plant: A whole plant which is relatively old
obsolete WWF biome: This grouping class is now obsolete. A subset for wwfBiome classes now gathers all WWF biome classes.
tropical rainforest: A rainforest which is subject to tropical environmental conditions.
dry river valley: A dry stream valley which was formed as a result of erosion due to river formation and flow.
dry stream valley: A dry valley which was formed as a result of erosion due to stream formation and flow.
peripheral nervous system: A major division of the nervous system that contains nerves which connect the central nervous system (CNS) with sensory organs, other organs, muscles, blood vessels and glands.
zone of skin: Any portion of the organ that covers that body and consists of a layer of epidermis and a layer of dermis.
camera-type eye: An organ of sight that includes the camera-type eyeball and supporting structures such as the lacrimal apparatus, the conjunctiva, the eyelid.
human nursery: A child care facility in which child care services are provided to young children and babies.
dune slack: A valley or trough between two dunes.
haze formation process: An environmental process during which a haze is formed by the aerosolisation of solid particles, including natural materials and anthropogenic pollutants, in an atmosphere.
freshwater stream: A stream which is composed primarily of fresh water.
emissions from petroleum combustion: An environmental material which is composed primarily of gases and particles produced by the combustion of petroleum fuels.
water ice formation process: A material transformation process during which water ice is formed.
fault cave: A cave developed along a fault or fault zone, either by movement of the fault or by preferential solution along it.
terrestrial environmental zone: An environmental zone which is bounded by material parts of a land mass or the atmosphere or space adjacent to it.
pit latrine: A pit latrine is a latrine which is constructed by digging a hole in the ground.
accumulation of matter on aerosolised pa: A material accumulation process during which the solid or liquid parts of an aerosol increase in mass due to mechanical aggregation of existing particles or through chemical conversion of gas-phase material.
ash: An environmental material that is the non-aqueous, non-gaseous residues that remain after something is burned.
municipal landfill: A landfill that receives household waste.
phacolith: A phacolith is an intrusion parallel to the bedding plane or foliation of folded country rock. More specifically, it is a typically lens-shaped intrusion that occupies either the crest of an anticline or the trough of a syncline.
midden: A dump for domestic waste. A term used to describe any kind of feature containing waste products relating to day-to-day human life.
supraglacial: A positional quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer in being in physical contact with the upper surface of a glacier or objects on top of the glacier.
non-saline aerosol environment: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by an aerosol with a low concentration of dissolved solutes.
tube well: A water well in which a long, 100–200 millimetres-wide, stainless steel tube or pipe is bored into an underground aquifer to lift water using a pump.
India ink: A black or colored ink which is 1) used for writing, printing, and drawing and 2) made from fine soot (lampblack) and water.
water trough: An anthropogenic geographic feature consisting of a receptacle intended to provide drinking water to animals.
pyroclastic cone: A cone made of material ejected from a volcano. The material can range from finest particles. In comparison, cinder cones are more uniform. They are usually found in or on larger features, such as stratovolcanoes, shield volcanoes and can be found inside calderas, however they can also be an independent feature. They can range from a few metres in height and are usually formed by a single eruption.
sunken: Flattened from above downward; below the normal level or the level of the surrounding parts.
area of attached Modiolus assemblages: An area which is dominated by dense accumulations of mussels, of the genus Modiolus, attached to a substrate other than conspecifics, including the associated faunal communities and predators present on the mussels (e.g., starfish).
place of worship: A human construction in which individuals or a group of people such as a congregation come to perform acts of devotion, veneration, or religious study.
falciform: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having the shape of a scythe or sickle.
fan-shaped: A quality inhering in a bearer that is shaped in the form of a fan.
slender: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being small or narrow in circumference or width in proportion to length or height.
iris blood vessel: A blood vessel that is part of a iris [Automatically generated definition].
trunk blood vessel: A blood vessel that is part of a trunk [Automatically generated definition].
drainage basin: An extent or area of land where surface water from rain and melting snow or ice converges to a single point at lower elevation, usually the exit of the basin, where the waters join another waterbody.
V-shaped: An angular shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having a single angle in its length giving the bearer the form of the letter V.
winter sports facility: A sports facility constructed for skiing and allied sports that require snow and/or ice.
obsolete air temperature: A temperature that inheres in some portion of air.
anthropogenic modulatory intervention pr: A process during which humans apply technology to alter the magnitude, duration, rate, or impact of an environmental process.
marine thermocline: A thermocline which is part of a marine water body.
temperate grassland biome: A temperate grassland which is in its climactic successional state.
degreaser: A cleaning agent which 1) contains organic solvents and 2) dissolves oils and fats for the removal of grease.
carbon dioxide pooling disposition: The disposition of an environment to sequester carbon dioxide, subsequently storing the carbon component thereof.
fly ash: A very fine, powdery material composed mostly of silica made from the burning of finely ground coal in a boiler.
hydrographic feature: A geographical feature associated with water.
food waste: A waste material which is primarily composed of uneaten food and removed from the food supply chain.
endoderm of foregut: An endoderm that is part of a foregut [Automatically generated definition].
marine biota: A biota which inhabits a marine ecosystem.
stream bank: The sloping margin of a stream, serving to confine it to its natural channel.
delicatessen: A food shop which sells a selection of food products that are not typical dietary components of the human population it is co-located with.
oxidising agent: A substance that removes electrons from another reactant in a redox reaction.
hail stone: An ice mass which 1) occurs in a ball-shape or irregular lump, 2) has a minimum diameter of 5 millimeters (or 0.2 inches), and 3) is formed within convective clouds.
photometeor: A meteor that is primarily composed of light.
edible seed food product:
SIREN DB annotation:
* whole, natural shape FOODON:03430150
* seed (anatomical part) FOODON:03420155
photosynthetic photon flux: A flux which inheres in photosynthetically active radiation.
anthropised ecosystem: An ecosystem which is formed as a result of human activity or impact.
oncology unit facility: A hospital unit facility which provides treatment for cancer.
long-term care facility: A residential building which is used to provides long-term care for residents.
sheet-iron building roof: A sheet-iron building roof is a building roof that is built from sheets of iron.
fissure water: Water which is partially contained within a fissure or a geological fracture.
suspension bridge: A bridge which has its deck hung on vertical suspenders via suspension cables.
fence: A fence is a constructed barrier which is  generally of lighter construction than a wall and used to provide visual sectioning of spaces.
high atmospheric level: A part of the troposphere which extends from 3 km to 8 km (10 000 – 25 000 ft) height in the polar region, from 5 km to 13 km (16 500 – 45 000 ft) height in the temperate region, and from 6 km to 18 km (20 000 – 60 000 ft) height in the tropical region.
colloid suspended in a hydrosphere: A colloidal suspension which is dispersed through a part of a hydrosphere.
discontinuous: A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being marked by breaks or interruptions.
presumptive mesoderm: Presumptive structure of the blastula that will develop into mesoderm.
presumptive ectoderm: Presumptive structure of the blastula that will develop into ectoderm.
biogenous sediment: Biogenous sediment is derived from living organisms, typically planktonic organisms possessing shells, frustules or coccoliths.
illegal informal settlement: A populated place where groups of housing units have been constructed on land that the occupants have no legal claim to, or occupy illegally, or where dwellings are not in compliance with current planning and building regulations.
native plant cell: A plant cell (PO:0009002) that is either part of a multicellular whole plant (PO:0000003) 'in vivo' or a unicellular organism 'in natura' (i.e. part of a natural environment).
plant resin: A portion of plant substance (PO:0025161) that consists of a complex mixture of organic aromatic compounds such as mono-, sesqui-, and diterpenoids.
strait: A narrow channel of water that connects two larger bodies of water, and thus lies between two land masses.
contaminated land: Land which has elevated levels of some contaminants or substances that are potentially hazardous to health or the environment.
adiabatic process: An environmental process during which a system does not thermally interact with its surroundings by virtue of a temperature difference between them.
resin: A solid or highly viscous plant or synthetic based substance that is typically convertible into polymers.
juniper woodland: A woodland which has a tree community primarily composed of trees of the genus Juniperus.
trattoria: A restaurant which is of Italian cultural origin and which is generally less formal than an Italian ristorante, but more formal than an osteria.
marine faunal bed: A marine bed which is covered by animals which have benthic habitats, including attached, clinging, sessile, infaunal, burrowing, laying, interstitial, and slow-moving animals, but not animals that have created substrate.
soil cryoturbate: A mass of soil moved or disturbed by frost action.
warm polymictic lake: A warm polymictic lake is a polymictic lake which is not covered by ice at any point during the year.
surface soil: A soil consisting of the upper layer of soil on the surface consisting of loose material capable of supporting life composed of a mixture of mineral and organic matter.
mosque: A building which is a place of worship for Muslims.
periphytic biofilm: Biofilm consisting of a mixture of algae, cyanobacteria, microbes, and detritus.
glaze ice layer: A glaze ice layer is a smooth, transparent and homogeneous ice layer which coats some surface and which is formed when freezing rain or drizzle hits that surface.
primary microplastic particle: A microplastic particle which is the direct output of a manufacturing process.
stream run: A hydroform which is that part of a stream where water flows swiftly and uniformly with low surface water agitation.
plumbing fixture: An exchangeable device which can be connected to a plumbing system to deliver and drain water.
glacier ice field: An ice field which is constituted by a continuous accumulation of snow and glacier ice that completely fills a mountain basin or covers a low-relief mountain plateau.
truck: A truck is a motor vehicle which, as its primary funcion, transports cargo rather than human passangers.
secondary microplastic particle: A microplastic particle which is derived from the breakdown of larger plastic debris.
planosol: Planosols are soils with a light-coloured, surface horizon that shows signs of periodic water stagnation and abruptly overlies a dense, slowly permeable subsoil with significantly more clay than the surface horizon.
freshwater river ecosystem: A freshwater stream ecosystem which has its functions and composition determined by a freshwater river.
choroid plexus: A network formed by blood vessels and the tela choroidea which secretes CSF into the ventricular spaces.
outwash fan: A fan-shaped body of sediments deposited by braided streams from a melting glacier.
artificial island: An island constructed by human effort.
fermentation starter: A manufactured product which assists starting a fermentation process which is intended to prepare foods and alcoholic drinks.
non-hydraulic cement: Non-hydraulic cement is a cement which sets by reacting with carbon dioxide in the air and will not set in wet conditions or underwater. It is susceptible to attack by aggresive chemicals after setting.
lumber production process: A process during which wood is processed into beams or planks.
chaparral area: A shrubland area found primarily in regions with a Mediterranean climate (mid, wet winters and hot dry summers) often shaped by wildfires.
lithosphere: A lithosphere is the outermost shell of a terrestrial-type planet or natural satellite that is defined by its rigid mechanical properties.
vegetable fat food product:
SIREN DB annotation:
* fat or oil FOODON:03420190
rift zone: A compound astronomical body part in which extensional tectonic processes occur and where the lithosphere is being pulled apart.
primary aerosol formation process: A material transport process during which solid or liquid particles are directly introduced into a volume of gas.
rhombencephalon neural crest: A neural crest that has_potential_to_developmentally_contribute_to a hindbrain.
gonad mesenchyme: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing gonad [Automatically generated definition].
post-anesthesia care unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide care for patients recovering from anesthesia.
permanent wilting point: A concentration of liquid water in soil at or below which a plant will wilt and no longer recover its turgidity when placed in a water saturated atmosphere.
fault escarpment: An escarpment resulting from a fault.
chloropicrin enriched soil: A portion of chloropicrin enriched soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of chloropicrin.
concentration of slit in soil: The concentration of a slit when measured in soil.
cabinet: A cabinet is a roughly cuboidal piece of furniture which is used to store miscellaneous items in compartments accessible through doors or drawers.
understory: An understory is a layer of plant life which grows below the canopy without penetrating it.
mandibular process mesenchyme from head: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a mandibular process mesenchyme.
mandibular process mesenchyme from neura: Mesenchyme that develops_from a neural crest and is part of a mandibular process mesenchyme.
1st arch mandibular mesenchyme from head: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a 1st arch mandibular mesenchyme.
body of liquid: A liquid astronomical body part which is continuous and is delimited by physical discontinuities or non-liquid boundaries.
island arc: A volcanic arc formed by the subduction of oceanic crust other oceanic crust on an adjacent tectonic plate.
advective: A physical quality of a process which is characteristic of process that transport material without, themselves, changing the qualities of those materials or the processes that are unfolding within them.
lacustrine mudflat: A wetland that forms when mud is deposited by a stream.
process quality: A quality which inheres in an process.
strength: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's power or force.
distal to: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located further from a more centrally located entity.
tectonic movement: A process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move.
forest biome: A forest ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
pelagic isohaline surface: A roughly planar, pelagic region characterised by equal salinity.
mediterranean woodland ecosystem: A woodland ecosystem which is subject to mediterranean environmental conditions.
musculature of body: The subdivision of the musculoskeletal system that consists of all the muscles of the body[VSAO, modified].
university campus: An area of land on which a college or university and related institutional buildings are situated.
strand swamp: A strand swamp is a swamp that forms linear drainage channels on flatlands.
ice: An ice is an environmental material which is either frozen or which is maintained in a solid state by gravitational forces or pressure.
subdivision of organism along main body: A major subdivision of an organism that divides an organism along its main body axis (typically anterio-posterior axis). In vertebrates, this is based on the vertebral column.
polar desert biome: .A polar desert ecosytem which is in its climactic successional state.
small river biome: A small freshwater river ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
cocoa food product:
