dung building floor: A dung building floor is a building floor which is composed primarily of dried animal feces.
ecological succession: An ecosystem process during which the species composition of an ecosystem gradually changes as species which are more adapted to the prevailing conditions in the ecosystem replace those which are less adapted.
estuarine tidal riverine coastal surface: A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from the land-water interface to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.
flue gas desulfurization material: a material leftover from the process of reducing sulfur dioxide emissions from a coal-fired boiler that can be a wet sludge consisting of calcium sulfite or calcium sulfate or a dry powered material that is a mixture of sulfites and sulfates.
subglacial volcano: A volcano produced by subglacial eruptions or eruptions beneath the surface of a lake melted into a glacier or ice mass by the rising lava.
drinking water reservoir: A reservoir constructed for the purpose of providing drinking water.
soil biocrust: A biocrust which is formed by photosynthetic microbial assemblages colonising the surface layer of a portion of arid soil. Through their successional dynamics, these communities reduce the soil surface's albedo, impart it with stability against erosion, modify its hydrology, and promote its fertility.
gasoline vapor: A fume produced by liquid gasoline, containing aerosolized components of the gasoline.
dissolved nitrogen atom in water: The nitrogen atom in a dissolved state when measured in water.
latrine slab: A latrine slab is a  broad, flat, thick piece of solid material (typically stone or concrete) used as the floor of a latrine and which includes a hole through which excreta are deposited into a latrine pit.
powdery snow: Uncompacted snow containing trapped atmospheric gases.
appendicular skeletal system: Subdivision of the skeletal system which consists of the appendicular skeleton plus associated joints.
cloud droplet: A droplet which is spherical in shape and suspended in an atmosphere, being of too small a mass to be pulled to a planetary surface by gravity.
cultivated environment: A cultivated environment is an environment that has been modified by humans by the preparation of the land, usually for the purposes of growing crops.
rock dust: Dust which is composed of minerals and trace elements, generated by  finely crushed rock.
tuff: Tuff is a type of rock made of volcanic ash ejected from a vent during a volcanic eruption.
sake food product: Sake is a fermented rice beverage resulting from the fermentation of rice with the mold Aspergillus oryzae and, in parallel, with the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae [wikipedia:sake]
life of whole plant stage: A maximal whole plant development stage.
sublimation process: A material transformation process during which a solid material transitions into a gas phase.
pelagic isothermal surface: A roughly planar, pelagic region characterised by equal water temperature.
marine lake water: Liquid water which is either part of or was removed from a marine lake.
developing mesenchymal structure: A mesenchyme-derived anatomical entity undergoing a transtion to become another structure.
river island: An island that lies in a river.
textile: A textile is a manufactured product comprised of a network of natural or artificial fibers (often referred to as thread or yarn).
litter role: A role which 1) inheres in a material entity 2) is realised when that entity is discarded outside waste management systems by humans or their technologies.
industrial fire: A fire which occurs in an industrial area or building.
oil refinery: An industrial building in which crude oil is transformed and refined into useful products.
borehole: A channel which is constructed by removing materials from land or submerged beds.
cropland ecosystem: An ecosystem which 1) is determined by communities of annual crops, perennial woody crops, or by actively tilled land, 2) is primarily used for agricultural activity, and 3) contains no village or larger human settlement.
skeletal element: Organ consisting of skeletal tissue. Encompasses whole bones, fused bones, cartilaginious elements, teeth, dermal denticles.
cranial bone: A bone that is part of a cranium.
bone of lower jaw: Any bone that is part of the lower jaw skeleton. This includes (when present): the dentary/mandible, the articular, the splenial, the suprangular.
cloud formation process: A process during which water vapour condensing in the atmosphere aggregates into clouds.
lithification: A process during which sediments compact under pressure, expel connate fluids, and gradually become solid sedimentary rock.
tectonic plate: A part of a lithosphere which is separated by other such parts by geographic faults or similar geomorphological discontinuities.
mass of solid material: An mass of environmental material which is composed primarily of a solid environmental material
disturbed ecosystem: An ecosystem which has been subject to a perturbation, that is, the ecosystem has undergone a pronounced change in response to a change in environmental conditions or other perturbation.
bedding-plane cave: A cavity developed along a bedding-plane and elongate in cross-section as a result.
tropical mixed forest biome: A tropical mixed forest which is in its climactic successional state.
waterhole: A pond, often temporary or seasonal, used as a drinking place by mammals and birds.
talc dust: Dust which is primarily composed of hydrated magnesium silicate (talc) particles.
salt dome: A dome-shaped mass of salt formed when a thick bed of evaporite minerals (mainly salt, or halite) found at depth intrudes vertically into surrounding rock strata, forming a diapir.
water truck: A water truck is a truck which transports water.
tea based beverage product: A beverage product derived from leaves of the tea plant (Camellia sinensis).
tidewater glacier: A glacier which terminates in a lake or the sea, with terminus either floating or grounded
thermokarst depression: A geographic basin which is formed due to the erosion of thermokarst by meltwater released from thawing permafrost.
vein: A vein is a geological fracture which is filled with minerals precipitated out of an aqueous solution.
dissolved nitrogen atom in soil: The nitrogen atom in a dissolved state when measured in soil.
landlocked sea: An inland sea which is not connected with an ocean by a lentic or lotic water body.
subpolar: A subpolar condition is an environmental condition in which an environmental system receives low, yearly solar irradiance per unit area and is surrounded by large land masses. This results in very cold winters with temperatures potentially falling to around -40 degrees Celsius and summers which last no more than 3 months of the year with a 24-hour average temperature of at least 10 degrees Celsius.
gouda cheese food product: A hard cow's milk cheese with an almost orange yellow paste. Older cheeses are coated in black wax.
barn: An agricultural building used for crop storage or animal husbandry.
planetary subsurface zone: Regions of a planet which are not exposed to the planet's atmosphere or space, often comprising parts of one or more planetary structural layers.
natural gas: Natural gas is a hydrocarbon gas mixture consisting primarily of methane, but commonly includes varying amounts of other higher alkanes and sometimes a usually lesser percentage of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and/or hydrogen sulfide. Natural gas is a fossil fuel formed when layers of buried plants and gases are exposed to intense heat and pressure over thousands of years.
second-order administrative region: A subdivision of a first-order administrative division.
information content entity: A generically dependent continuant that is about some thing.
irrigation reservoir: A reservoir constructed for the purpose of providing water for irrigation.
biodiversity conservation process: A conservation process during which the variability of life - from genes to ecosystems - is preserved.
ballast tank: A ballast tank is a compartment within a boat, ship or other floating structure that holds water, which is used as ballast to provide stability for a vessel.
public toilet: An indoor toilet that is available for public use.
combustion process: Combustion or burning is a high-temperature exothermic redox chemical reaction between a fuel and an oxidant that produces oxidized, often gaseous products, in a mixture termed as smoke.
fecal environment: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by feces.
marine reef biome: A biome expressed by strips or ridges of rocks, sand, or coral that rises to or near the surface of a body of marine water.
stone exterior wall: A stone exterior wall is an exterior wall that is composed primarily of rock.
intermittent estuary: An estuary which varies dramatically in its volume as a result of intermittent freshwater input, and is capable of changing from a wholly marine embayment to any other type of estuary.
milled food product: A food product made from milling plant material.
fresh water body: A body of water which is primarily composed of freshwater, with low solute content.
fissure cave: A narrow, vertical cave passage, often developed along a joint but not necessarily so. Usually due to solution but sometimes to tension.
smog: A fog which is intermixed with smoke or other combustion products and their derivatives.
presumptive neural plate: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a neural plate.
presumptive segmental plate: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a presomitic mesoderm.
presumptive paraxial mesoderm: The part of the blastula that has the potential to develop into a paraxial mesoderm.
brick material: A portion of brick material is a material derived from a brick which is composed of  kneaded clay-bearing soil, expanded clay aggregate, sand and lime, or concrete that has been fire-hardened or air-dried.
biosphere reserve: An international conservation designation given by UNESCO under its Programme on Man and the Biosphere (MAB).
cold seep:
MERGED DEFINITION:
TARGET DEFINITION: A cold seep is a seep in which methane and other hydrocarbon-rich fluids rise to the sea floor.
--------------------
SOURCE DEFINITION: An area of the ocean floor where hydrogen sulfide, methane and other hydrocarbon-rich fluid seepage occurs. Cold seeps are distinct from hydrothermal vents: the former's emissions are of the same temperature as the surrounding seawater, whereas the latter's emissions are super-heated.
lamp: A lamp is an object which generates heat, light, or any other form of radiation.
intermediate lava: Intermediate lava is lava which, relative to felsic lava, is lower in aluminium and silica (between 52 and 63 percent by weight), and usually somewhat richer in magnesium and iron. The temperature of intermediate lava ranges from 750 to 950 degrees Celsius, destroying polymerized bonds and promoting more fluid behaviour relative to felsic lavas and also a greater tendency to form phenocrysts. Higher iron and magnesium tends to manifest as a darker groundmass, and also occasionally amphibole or pyroxene phenocrysts.
estuarine coastal surface layer: A layer of estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from the shore to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.
residential environment: An anthropogenic environment which provides long-term shelter for its inhabitants.
quality of a substance: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of its constitution.
water-based planetary surface: This includes the surface layers of all volumes of water exposed to space or the planet's atmosphere.
desert island: An island that is not permanently populated by humans.
arable: A quality inhereing in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being periodically and mechanically manipulated to loosen and mix any soil which it has as a part.
planned environmental usage process: A planned process during which humans access and obtain resources, benefits, or services from a natural or anthropised ecosystem.
fish product (unspecified species): A fish product is a home-made or commercially produced or retail or wholesale product containing substantial amounts of freshwater or saltwater fish and/or shellfish flesh. Note that this category should avoid items that mention a particular species of fish or shellfish.
second year ice formation: A sea ice formation process during which seawater freezes onto first year ice during the cold season, forming second year sea ice.
dermatome: A transitional population of migrating mesenchymal cells that derive from somites and that will become dermal cells.
pigeon pea (dried): A product of the dry seeds of Cajanus cajan.
young ice formation process: A sea ice formation process during which water freezes to the bottom of an existing nilas ice floe creating a thicker ice floe known as young ice.
astronomical body: An object which is naturally occuring, bound together by gravitational or electromagnetic forces, and surrounded by space.
pump: A device that moves fluids (liquids or gases), or sometimes slurries, by mechanical action.
bone of jaw: A bone element that is part of a jaw region.
labile kerogen: Kerogen from which heavy hydrocarbons (such as oils) are derived following chemical break down.
sea coast: The general region of indefinite width that extends from the sea inland to the first major change in terrain features.
extreme high temperature environment: An extreme high temperature environment is a high temperature environment in which entities are exposed to temperatures above 80 degrees Celsius.
public prison: A prison facility which is owned and operated by a state.
moatan: An annular depression that may not be continuous, located at the base of many seamounts, islands, and other isolated elevations.
terracette: A ridge on a hillside formed when saturated soil particles expand, then contract as they dry, causing them to move slowly downhill.
sea surface height: A elevation quality which inheres in a marine water body by virtue of the position of that water body's surface layer (adjacent to an atmosphere) relative to some reference elevation.
fruit jelly (us cfr): Jelled product made from one or more fruit juices and optional ingredients. Includes both fruit jelly, which may be sweetened with nutritive carbohydrate sweeteners, (21 CFR 150.140), and artificially sweetened fruit jelly (21 CFR 150.141). The finished fruit jelly must have a soluble solid content of no less than 65% and the ratio by weight of the fruit ingredient to sweetener in the starting mixture must be no less than 45:55. Artificially sweetened fruit jelly must contain no less than 55% fruit ingredient by weight.
obsolete geothermal field: An area where wells can be drilled to obtain elements contained in solution in hot brines or to tap heat energy.
ice accumulation process: A material accumulation process during which ice forms in an environmental material or an existing accumulation of ice increases in mass.
choroidal blood vessel: A blood vessel that is part of a choroid [Automatically generated definition].
channel of a watercourse: A depressed landform which physically confines a river, slough or ocean strait, and which consists of a bed and banks.
adsorption: A material accumulation process during which material adheres to a solid or liquid surface.
coal ash: Ash that is produced from the burning of coal.
soil profile characterization: A planned process during which a soil profile is examined and the soil horizons that compose it are described.
concentration of carotene in liquid wate: The concentration of carotene when measured in liquid water.
concentration of alloxanthine in liquid: The concentration of alloxanthine when measured in liquid water.
concentration of ammonium in liquid wate: The concentration of ammonium when measured in liquid water.
concentration of beta-carotene in liquid: The concentration of beta-carotene when measured in liquid water.
concentration of chlorophyll b in liquid: The concentration of chlorophyll b when measured in liquid water.
concentration of alpha-carotene in liqui: The concentration of alpha-carotene when measured in liquid water.
concentration of bacteriochlorophyll a i: The concentration of bacteriochlorophyll a when measured in liquid water.
concentration of Adenosine 5-triphosphat: The concentration of Adenosine 5-triphosphate when measured in liquid water.
concentration of chlorophyll a in liquid: The concentration of chlorophyll a when measured in liquid water.
frontal surface of a weather front: A gaseous surface layer which is composed of the warmer air mass(es) along the horizontal density and temperature discontinuity in a weather front.
achondrite: A stony meteorite that is made of material similar to terrestrial basalts or plutonic rocks.
cup: A utensil which is a hand-sized container with an open top.
ice piedmont: A glacier covering a coastal strip of low-lying land backed by mountains, and sloping gently seaward over a distance up to 30km or more to terminate in ice cliffs or to merge with an ice shelf.
estuarine open water upper water column: A layer of estuarine water which extends from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast.
burned soil: Soil which has been transformed through a combustion process.
concentration of pesticide in surface wa: The concentration of a pesticide when measured in surface water.
articular system: Anatomical system that consists of all the joints of the body.
solubility of nitrogen atom in environme: The solubility of a nitrogen atom when measured in environmental material.
concentration of tritium in sea water: The concentration of tritium when measured in sea water.
concentration of helium-3 in sea water: The concentration of helium-3 when measured in sea water.
concentration of carbon-13 atom in sea w: The concentration of carbon-13 atom when measured in sea water.
concentration of carbon-14 atom in sea w: The concentration of carbon-14 atom when measured in sea water.
concentration of chloroflurocarbon in se: The concentration of chloroflurocarbon when measured in sea water.
concentration of nitrite in sea water: The concentration of nitrite when measured in sea water.
concentration of calcium carbonate in se: The concentration of calcium carbonate when measured in sea water.
concentration of ammonium in sea water: The concentration of ammonium when measured in sea water.
concentration of carbon atom in sea wate: The concentration of carbon atom when measured in sea water.
concentration of sulfur hexafluoride in: The concentration of sulfur hexafluoride when measured in sea water.
multicellular anatomical structure: An anatomical structure that has more than one cell as a part.
cirrus homogenitus cloud: A cloud which is cirriform and is formed by condensation events centred on an aircraft's contrail.
flower-rich field margin strip: A flower strip which is present at the margins of cultivated fields.
transport feature: A construction which enables the movement of humans, their animals or their vehicles.
ice fog: Fog which is composed of particles of ice.
permanent spring: A spring whose flow is continuous.
crystal: A solid material whose constituents, such as atoms, molecules or ions, are arranged in a highly ordered microscopic structure, forming a crystal lattice that extends in all directions.
environment determined by a plant substa: An environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by a substance produced by a plant.
lake-effect snowfall: Snowfall which 1) is localized, 2) is convective, and 3) occurs as a result of a cold, dry air mass absorbing heat and moisture as it flows over a lake with warmer waters.
muscle organ: Organ consisting of a tissue made up of various elongated cells that are specialized to contract and thus to produce movement and mechanical work[GO].
aquatic natural environment: A natural environment which is within a water body.
grease ice layer: A layer which consists of a thin aggregate of frazil ice crystals, which float upon the surface of a water body.
lava field: A lava field is an expanse of flat-lying lava flows. Such features are generally composed of highly fluid basalt lava, and can extend for tens or even hundreds of miles across the underlying terrain.
public ferry: A ferry which is owned by a government or other form of public representation.
histosol: Histosols comprise soils formed in organic material. These vary from soils developed in predominantly moss peat in boreal, arctic and subarctic regions, via moss peat, reeds/ sedge peat (fen) and forest peat in temperate regions to mangrove peat and swamp forest peat in the humid tropics. Histosols are found at all altitudes, but the vast majority occurs in lowlands.
wax: A wax is an environmental material which is primarily composed of lipids or other organic compounds that consist of long alkyl chains. Waxes are are malleable near ambient temperatures and melt at approximately 45 degrees Celsius.
stream water: Water which is part of a stream.
oceanic gyre: A gyre in oceanography is any large system of rotating ocean currents, particularly those involved with large wind movements. Gyres are caused by the Coriolis Effect; planetary vorticity  along with horizontal and vertical friction, which determine the circulation patterns from the wind curl (torque).
metallic dust: Dust which is composed primarily of some metallic material.
mixed forest biome: A mixed forest which is in its climactic successional state.
ammonia: An azane that consists of a single nitrogen atom covelently bonded to three hydrogen atoms.
vetch seed: A seed of a vetch plant.
animal manure: Manure which is derived from the waste products of animals.
loamy sand: Soil which is primarily composed of sand with silt and clay in progressively smaller proportions.
algal material: An organic material which is primarily composed of living or dead algae, along with their exudates.
mesoderm blood island: A blood island that is part of a mesoderm.
planetary landmass: A landmass which is part of a planet.
asphalt road: A road which is primarily composed of asphalt.
anchialine cave: An anchialine cave is a cave which contains an anchialine pool.
ice-bearing permafrost thawing process: A permafrost thawing process during which water-based ice or snow present in permafrost is converted into meltwater.
gypsum plaster: Gypsum plaster is a plaster which is formed by partially dehydrating gypsum by heating it to approximately 150 degrees Celsius and grinding the product into a powder. Gypsum anhydride - formed by heating gypsum above 200 degrees Celsius - may also be used as plaster.
joint-plane cave: A cavity developed along a joint and elongate in cross-section.
storm surge process: A storm surge process is a coastal flooding process which is caused by low pressure weather systems such as tropical cyclones and strong extratropical cyclones, the severity of which is affected by the shallowness and orientation of the water body relative to storm path, and the timing of tides.
mesoplastic particle: A piece of plastic which is between 5 and 25 millimetres in its longest dimension.
carcass: The dead body of an animal.
bottle: A container which is typically made of glass or plastic and having a tapered neck, used primarily for holding liquids.
sugar (refined):

* fully heat-treated FOODON:03440014
