petroleum: A naturally occurring flammable liquid consisting of a complex mixture of hydrocarbons of various molecular weights and other liquid organic compounds, that are found in geologic formations beneath the planetary surfaces.
botanical fruit food product: Mature ovary of a plant, with a fleshy part of the carpel that develops with the seed to attract animals for aid in dispersal. Botanically, nuts are considered fruits.
desert spring: A spring that is located in the desert.
dry-adiabatic process: An adiabatic process during which no condensation of water vapor occurs and no liquid water is present.
land consumption process: A process in which natural ecosystems present over an expanse of land are removed and replaced with anthropogenic ecosystems.
smooth: A texture quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's processing a surface free of roughness or irregularities.
channel: A structure which traverses a mass of one or more environmental materials, and encloses a roughly tubular site.
agricultural experimental station: A research station in which food production and/or agribusinness research is performed.
skeletal joint: Anatomical cluster that consists of two or more adjacent skeletal structures, which may be interconnected by various types of tissue[VSAO].
concentration of praseodymium in water i: The concentration of praseodymium when measured in water ice.
concentration of tin in water ice: The concentration of tin when measured in water ice.
concentration of molybdenum in water ice: The concentration of molybdenum when measured in water ice.
concentration of samarium in water ice: The concentration of samarium when measured in water ice.
concentration of thallium in water ice: The concentration of thallium when measured in water ice.
concentration of titanium in water ice: The concentration of titanium when measured in water ice.
concentration of niobium in water ice: The concentration of niobium when measured in water ice.
concentration of neodymium in water ice: The concentration of neodymium when measured in water ice.
concentration of silver in water ice: The concentration of silver when measured in water ice.
concentration of yttrium in water ice: The concentration of yttrium when measured in water ice.
sweat material: An excreta material which is composed primarily of sweat, an excreta consisting primarily of water as well as a smaller amount of sodium chloride that is excreted by the sweat glands in the skin of mammals.
basalt: Basalt is a volcanic rock which is formed by the rapid cooling of basaltic lava.
waste stabilization pond: A human construction which confines wastewater in a depression enclosed by earthen structures.
future central nervous system: Primordium that develops into the central nervous system.
blood material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of blood, a bodily fluid composed of blood plasma and blood cells suspended within the plasma that circulates around the organism's body. Blood performs may important functions including the supplying of oxygen and nutrients, removal of waste, circulation of white blood cells, detection of antibodes, coagulation, transportation of antibodies and the regulation of pH and body temperature.
psychiatric intensive care unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide  intensive psychiatric care.
dissolved carbon atom in water: The carbon atom in a dissolved state when measured in water.
rainbow: A rainbow is a photometeor which consists of a spectral separation of light, formed as a result of the reflection, refraction, and dispersion of light in water droplets suspended in an astronomical body's atmosphere.
coniferous forest biome: A coniferous forest biome is a forest biome which contains densely packed populations or communities of coniferous trees, strongly limiting light penetration to the forest floor.
snow and ice accumulation process: A material accumulation process during which a accumulation of snow and ice forms or increases in mass.
organ culture: Organ culture is the aseptic culture of complete living organs of animals and plants outside the body in a suitable culture medium. Animal organs must be small enough to allow the nutrients in the culture medium to penetrate all the cells.
house: A house is a building that provides a dwelling-place for a living entity.
non-saline environment: This class (term) is defined by the lack of a quality (i.e. the lack of salinity or increased osmolarity), which is not best-practice ontologically. Use for annotation is generally discouraged and users should use classes which positively describe the material or environment sampled (i.e. stating the qualities the entity has, rather than those it does not).
sea cliff: A cliff that is a margin of a sea or ocean.
protoplanetary disk: An astronomical object which is composed of dense gas and dust rotating around a young newly formed star, a T Tauri star, or a Herbig Ae/Be star in a disk-shaped configuration.
playground: A park which has been designed for the recreation of children.
chorioretinal region: The part of the eye that consists of both the retina and the optic choroid.
skin epithelium: Any region of epithelium that is part of a skin region.
glacial sintering: A sintering process during which snow is compacted into glacial ice.
resequent stream: A stream whose course follows the original relief, but at a lower level than the original slope (e.g., flows down a course determined by the underlying strata in the same direction). These streams develop later and are generally a tributary to a subsequent stream.
lymph: Lymph is the fluid that is formed when interstitial fluid enters the conduits of the lymphatic system through lymph capillaries[WP].
hematopoietic system: Anatomical system that is involved in the production of hematopoietic cells.
subtropical dry broadleaf forest biome: A subtropical dry broadleaf forest which is in its climactic successional state.
non-neurogenic ectodermal placode: Ectodermal placode that does not develop into a component of the nervous system.
chopstick: An eating utensil which is a thin stick used in equal length pairs to manipulate food and bring it into a mouth.
rhizosphere: The narrow region of soil that is directly influenced by root secretions and associated soil microorganisms.
mesenchyme: Portion of tissue composed of mesenchymal cells (motile cells that develop from epthelia via an epithelial to mesenchymal transition) and surrounding extracellular material. Mesenchyme has different embryological origins in different metazoan taxa - in many invertebrates it derives in whole or part from ectoderm. In vertebrates it derives largely from mesoderm, and sometimes the terms are used interchangeably, e.g. lateral plate mesoderm/mesenchyme.
compound organ: Anatomical structure that has as its parts two or more multi-tissue structures of at least two different types and which through specific morphogenetic processes forms a single distinct structural unit demarcated by bona fide boundaries from other distinct anatomical structures of different types.
surface structure: Anatomical structure that overlaps the outer epithelial layer and is adjacent to the space surrounding the organism.
urban pollution: A pollution process that results in increased levels of pollutants in an urban environment.
lichen material: An organic material which is derived from lichen mats.
natural harbor: A harbor which is formed by a natural landform where a part of a body of water is protected and deep enough to furnish anchorage.
sports facility: A facility which supports the performance of sporting activities.
oil-based paint: A slow-drying paint that consists of particles of pigment suspended in a drying oil, commonly linseed oil.
rocky reef: A ridge of rocks, lying near the surface of the sea, which may be visible at low tide, but is usually covered by water.
gel ink: A colorant fluid which is 1) manufactured and 2) composed of copper phthalocyanine, iron oxides, water, and biopolymers.
oceanic sea surface microlayer biome: The oceanic sea surface microlayer (SML) biome comprises the top 1000 micrometers of the marine surface waters occurring offshore, away from a continental shelf. It is the boundary layer where all exchange occurs between the atmosphere and the ocean. The chemical, physical, and biological properties of the SML differ greatly from the sub-surface water just a few centimeters beneath.
clay dust: Dust which is derived from clay material.
raceway pond: A pond which humans have constructed for the cultivation of algae.
primordial vasculature: A portion of tissue that will develop into vasculature.
complex volcano: A volcano with more than one feature. They form because changes of their eruptive characteristics or the location of multiple vents in an area. Stratovolcanoes may form complex volcanoes, because they may overlap another from explosive eruptions, lava flows, pyroclastic flows and by repeated eruptions, to make multiple summits and vents. Stratovolcanoes could also form a large caldera that gets filled in by multiple small cinder cones, lava domes and craters may also develop on the caldera's rim.
diapir: A diapir is a type of geologic intrusion in which a more mobile and ductily deformable material is forced into brittle overlying rocks due to its higher buoyancy.
vasculature of musculoskeletal system: A vasculature that is part of a musculoskeletal system [Automatically generated definition].
anatomical projection: A projection or outgrowth of tissue from a larger body or organ.
vasculature of muscle organ: A vasculature that is part of a muscle organ [Automatically generated definition].
axial skeleton plus cranial skeleton: Subdivision of skeleton which consists of cranial skeleton, set of all vertebrae, set of all ribs and sternum[FMA, modified].
acidic hot spring: An acidic spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows.
vacuum cleaner: A device that causes suction in order to remove debris from surfaces.
mesoderm-derived structure: An anatomical structure that develops (entirely or partially) from the mesoderm.
ectoderm-derived structure: An anatomical structure that develops (entirely or partially) from the ectoderm.
genitourinary system: Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs concerned with the production and excretion of urine and those concerned with reproduction.
optic vesicle: The optic vesicle is the evagination of neurectoderm that precedes formation of the optic cup[GO]. Portion of tissue that is comprised of neuroepitheium which has pinched off from the anterior neural keel and will form the optic cup[ZFA].
temple: A building reserved in which religious or spiritual rituals and activities such as prayer and sacrifice are performed.
shield volcano: A large volcano with shallowly-sloping sides.
bedrail: A poll which is attached to the head, foot, or side of a bed frame.
brasserie: A type of restaurant which is of French cultural origin and which provides more service or food variety than a bistro.
amount of nitrogen atom in environmental: The amount of a nitrogen atom when measured in environmental material.
land conversion process: An anthropisation process during which terrestrial environments - natural or anthropised - or parts thereof are altered to facilitate human activities such as agriculture, settlement, or commerce.
anthropisation: A process during which a natural environmental system is altered by human action.
sea ice floe: An ice floe which is formed from frozen sea water, and floats upon the surface of a marine water body.
cold season: A season during which the average temperature of a planetary part is below that of all other seasons it endures during a season generating process.
air vent: A manufactured product consisting of a duct opening which allows air to circulate.
large river headwater biome: A large freshwater river headwater ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
aquatic environment: An environment whose dynamics are strongly influenced by water.
aerosolisation of dust: A primary aerosol formation process during which dust particles are suspended in a gaseous medium.
attractive environment: An environment which includes components which are deemed to be aesthetically pleasing by a population of humans.
building corridor: A building part which is a narrow hall or passage in a building with rooms leading off it.
mountain pass: A lower point that allows easier access through a mountain range. A pass has the general form of a saddle between two mountains.
open animal house: An animal house which is only partially surrounded by a building envelope.
feasting pit site: An archeological site which contains holes humans had dug in the ground, or their remnants, for the purpose of storing and distributing food, drink, and both functional or ritualistic implements during communal eating and drinking.
plant root food product: A food product derived from or produced by a plant root.
mandibular neural crest: Cranial neural crest that migrates into the mandibular arch.
massif: A section of the Earths's crust that is demarcated by faults or flexures. In the movement of the crust, a massif tends to retain its internal structure while being displaced as a whole.
humid air: Air which has increased levels of water vapour.
wave-cut platform: The narrow flat area often seen at the base of a sea cliff caused by the action of the waves.
cuboidal epithelium: An epithelium consisting of cuboidal epithelial cells.
earthquake-driven seismic vibration: A seismic vibration process which is caused by an earthquake.
single strain cell culture: A cell culture which is composed of a single population of bacterial or archaeal cells.
thatched building roof: A thatched building roof is a building roof that is built by thatching (or out of thatch).
high dependency unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide high dependency care.
nerve of head region: A nerve that is part of a head.
fringed: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having an ornamental border consisting of short straight or twisted threads or strips hanging from cut or raveled edges or from a separate band.
bowl shaped: A concave 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being shaped in the form of a bowl.
tailings pond: A human construction which is used as a storage area for mining tailings.
hot tub: A manufactured product which may hold a volume of heated water suitable for one or more humans to bathe in, usually for the purposes of hydrotherapy or pleasure.
water table depth: An elevation which inheres in a water table by virture of its vertical distance from a land surface.
eutrophic pond: A pond which has nutrient-rich water.
thermosetting disposition: A disposition which inheres in materials capable of becoming rigid when cured by heating.
food product by meal type: A meal type is the name of an eating occasion that may have location, food type, or other customary contextual features. (Damion's 1st draft definition)
coastal ocean water: Coastal ocean water is sea water that is adjacent to a coast.
squeegee: A tool with a flat, smooth rubber blade, used to remove or control the flow of liquid on a flat surface.
transform tectonic movement: A process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move along each other in a predominantly horizontal manner, either in a sinistral (left lateral) or dextral (right lateral) direction.
ocean biome: A marine biome which is determined by an ocean.
paraffin wax: A white or colourless soft solid derivable from petroleum, coal or oil shale, that consists of a mixture of hydrocarbon molecules containing between twenty and forty carbon atoms.
pantothenate enriched soil: A portion of pantothenate enriched soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of pantothenate.
radiation from a manufactured product: An electromagnetic radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted from a manufactured product.
stratus cloud: A cloud which 1) occurs in the form of a layer with a fairly uniform base or, less frequently, ragged patches, 2) is composed of small water droplets, 3) is located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage).
size: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's physical magnitude.
jaw mesenchyme: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing jaw [Automatically generated definition].
step pool: A stream pool which is formed as a result of high-gradient, steep streams where water cascades over a rock or woody snag.
interstitial fluid material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of interstitial fluid, a bodily fluid consisting of a solution which bathes and surrounds the cells of multicellular animals. It is the main component of the extracellular fluid, which also includes plasma and transcellular fluid.
environmental system: A system which has the disposition to environ one or more material entities.
western boundary current: A warm water, narrow marine surface current flowing from the equator to high latitudes at speeds between 40 and 120 kilometers per day. Western boundary currents are the deepest ocean surface flows, usually extending 1000 meters below the ocean surface.
visible spectrum radiation: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted at wavelengths between 380 nm and 760 nm.
marine bathypelagic zone: The one of an ocean below the 10degC thermocline down to a temperature of 4degC.
xeric shrubland biome: Preliminary definition. The semantics and definitions of "mediterranean", "subtropical", "tropical", "temperate", "polar", and similar climate types may be transferred to an "environmental condition" class once the semantics of this class have been established.
UNEP-WCMC class 1 mountain: A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation greater than 4500 metres above sea level.
excretory system: An anatomical system that eliminates waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity.
material entity: An independent continuant that is spatially extended whose identity is independent of that of other entities and can be maintained through time.
nest of alligator: An animal habitation which is built by alligators from plants and decomposing vegetation in order to protect their eggs from predators.
tundra biome: A tundra ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
cyanobacterial bloom: A feature which arises from a rapid multiplication of cyanobacteria, causing marked visible discoloration of the water.
ice tongue: A long and narrow sheet of ice projecting out from the coastline. An ice tongue forms when a valley glacier moves very rapidly out into the ocean or a lake.
discharge unit facility: A hospital unit facility which houses patients ready to leave the hospital facility.
building: A permanent walled and roofed construction.
transudate: Any bodily fluid that has passed through a membrane such as the capillary wall, as a result of unbalanced hydrostatic and osmotic forces.
ice decumulation zone: A material decumulation zone in which the rates of ice formation processes are below those of ice decumulation processes, leading to a net decrease in some mass of ice.
child care environment: An anthropogenic environment which is designed for child care.
proglacial: A positional quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer in being in physical contact with, or close to, a glacial margin.
burnt-brick exterior wall: A burnt brick exterior wall is an exterior wall that is built from burnt bricks.
microwave radiation: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted at wavelengths and frequencies which travel exclusively in a line-of-sight fashion and which may produce molecular rotation and torsion on contact with matter.
extraembryonic epithelium: An epithelium that is part of a extraembryonic structure.
increased speed: A speed which is relatively high.
old: An age which is relatively high.
decreased speed: A speed which is relatively low.
young: An age which is relatively low.
solonchak: Solonchaks are soils that have a high concentration of soluble salts at some time in the year. Solonchaks are largely confined to the arid and semi-arid climate zones and to coastal regions in all climates.
train car: A vehicle which is used for carrying cargo or passengers on a rail transport system.
habitat fragmentation process: An ecosystem fragmentation process during which discontinuities emerge in the habitats of one or more ecological populations.
patient room: A room which is used for patient care during a patient's visit or stay in a healthcare facility.
canal head reservoir: A reservoir constructed for the purpose of maintaining water levels in a canal or canals.
anoxic lake: A lake which is primarily composed of anoxic water.
dry distillation: Distillation during which a solid material is vapourised and the resulting vapours condensed into either solid or liquid component materials.
compressed natural gas: Compressed natural gas is a natural gas stored at high pressures, typically 20–25 Megapascals.
ice gain: A material accumulation process during which the mass of an existing ice mass increases.
prison: A human construction which is used to forcibly confine humans.
area of national forest: A protected forest or woodland area in the United States. National forests are controlled by the federal government and managed by the United States Forest Service, under the direction of the United States Department of Agriculture.
subsequent stream: A stream whose course has been determined by selective headward erosion along weak strata. These streams have generally developed after the original stream. Subsequent streams developed independently of the original relief of the land and generally follow paths determined by the weak rock belts.
fishing gear: A manufactured product which is used for fishing.
sea ice: Water ice which has formed by the freezing of sea water.
observing system: A system of constructed and manufactured products which are used by humans to produce data, information, or knowledge about material, immaterial, or processual entities.
breast milk material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of breast milk, is a bodily fluid produced that is secreted from two milk-secreting glandular organs on a female's chest.
electrical conductivity: A conductivity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ability to convey electricity.
granular: A composition quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's containing granules.
heat conductivity: A conductivity quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to spontaneous transfer of thermal energy from a region of higher temperature to a region of lower temperature.
underground water: Water which has physicochemical properties determined by processes which occur beneath the planetary crust.
interface layer: A layer which separates two portions of environmental material which possess 1) differing compositions, 2) a discontinuity of some property, or 3) some derivative of some property in a direction normal to the interface.
artificial channel: A channel of a watercource which has been constructed by humans or their technologies.
particle radiation: A radiation process during which energy is transmitted or emitted by means of fast-moving subatomic particles.
tropical marginal sea biome: A marginal sea biome which is located in a region with a tropical climate.
polar front: A weather front which separates air masses of tropical and polar origin.
interdigitated: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's parts or projections being interlocked; for example, the fingers of two hands that are clasped.
activity (of a radionuclide): A radiation quality inhering in a radioactive substance by virtue of its transformation (disintegration) rate.
radioactive: A radiation quality inhering in bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting or being caused by radioactivity.
mesosphere: The mesosphere is part of the earth's atmosphere which is between the stratosphere and the thermosphere in which temperature decreases with altitude to the atmosphere's absolute minimum
occupational environment: An anthropogenic environment which is the product of a particular human occupational acitivity.
migration path: An ecological corridor through which organisms move during a migration process.
bicycle: A bicycle is a human-powered, pedal-driven, single-track vehicle, having two wheels attached to a frame, one behind the other.
tundra mire: Peatlands with a shallow peat layer, only about 500 mm thick, dominated by sedges and grasses. They form in permafrost areas, covering around 110,000 to 160,000 km2 in Alaska, Canada, and the former USSR.
brush fire: A land fire which consumes low-growing plants such as scrub and brush.
slope: A solid astronomical body part which is part of the planetary surface between the peak of an elevation or the bottom of a depression and relatively flat surrounding land.
solid waste material: Solid material that has a waste role.
dry soil albedo: Soil albedo which inheres in dry soil.
wildfire: A conflagration which is uncontrolled and combusts material in a vegetated area, be it rural or wild.
climate change: The long-term fluctuations in temperature, precipitation, wind, and all other aspects of the Earth's climate. External processes, such as solar-irradiance variations, variations of the Earth's orbital parameters (eccentricity, precession, and inclination), lithosphere motions, and volcanic activity, are factors in climatic variation. Internal variations of the climate system, e.g., changes in the abundance of greenhouse gases, also may produce fluctuations of sufficient magnitude and variability to explain observed climate change through the feedback processes interrelating the components of the climate system.
paper dye: Dyes used for the coloration or brightening of paper.
mass of fluid: An object which is composed primarily of a fluid.
varnish: A clear transparent hard protective film or finish, primarily used for wood finishing applications.
marine neritic benthic zone biome: The marine neritic zone biome comprises sea floor from the high tide mark to a continental shelf break. This zone generally extends to 200 m below average sea level.
fossil material: A solid environmental material which is formed by the replacement of organic substances (including those in soils and sediments) with mineral material.
kiosk: A booth with an open window on one side.
amount of carbon atom in environmental m: The amount of a carbon atom when measured in environmental material.
stock: A stock is a discordant igneous intrusion having a surface exposure of less than 100 square kilometres. Stocks differ from batholiths only in being smaller.
freshwater ice: Water ice which is formed by the freezing of fresh water.
straight: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being free of curves, bends, or angles.
molecular quality: A quality which inheres in a molecular entity, a single molecule, atom, ion, radical etc.
displaced: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue the bearer's being changed in position.
water-body-derived ice: Ice which has formed as the result of freezing of water which was part of a water body.
deep chlorophyll maximum layer: A subsurface layer in a water body, typically an ocean or lake, in which chlorophyll concentrations reach their maximum.
mineral: In general, a mineral is a chemical substance that is normally crystalline formed and has been formed as a result of geological processes. The term also includes metamict substances (naturally occurring, formerly crystalline substances whose crystallinity has been destroyed by ionising radiation) and can include naturally occurring amorphous substances that have never been crystalline ('mineraloids') such as georgite and calciouranoite as well as substances formed by the action of geological processes on bigenic compounds ('biogenic minerals').
cardiac chamber: A cardiac chamber surrounds an enclosed cavity within the heart.
office: A building part within which administrative work is done by an organisations users in order to support and realise the objectives of that organization.
residual water in soil: Liquid water which is present in soils as discontinuous volumnes of water in contact with solid and gaseous components of the soil.
commercial building: A building which is primarily used to facilitate the buying or selling of goods or services.
bottom ash: a coarse, angular ash particle that is too large to be carried up into the smoke stacks so it forms in the bottom of the coal furnace.
arable or pasturable land: Land which either hosts plant communities upon which animals may graze has been manipulated by tilling, ploughing, or other human activity for the purposes of seed sowing or planting crops.
riverine flooding: Riverine flooding is a process in which the flow rate of river water exceeds the capacity of its channel, thus flooding neighbouring land. Bends and meanders in a river channel are particularly disposed to such flooding.
marine hydrothermal plume: A marine hydrothermal vent plume, part of a marine hydrothermal vent, is a high temperature water jet laden with dissolved metals and minerals that is driven by heat generated due to tectonic activity below the vent.
glaciation: An interval of time within an ice age and during which temperatures fall resulting in planet-wide glacier advances.
refinement process: A planned material transformation process which takes as input a material and removes impurities.
groundwater flow: A water flow process during which water is transported through an aquifer.
chalk soil: Soil which has increased levels of chalk.
concentration of liquid water in soil: The concentration of a liquid water when measured in soil.
constructed transport system: A system which has components that have been constructed to allow the movement of people or goods.
azane: Saturated acyclic nitrogen hydrides having the general formula NnHn+2.
continuant: An entity that exists in full at any time in which it exists at all, persists through time while maintaining its identity and has no temporal parts.
domestic building: A building which is primarily used for the long-term habitation of humans.
ornamentation: A surface feature shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the degree of the bearer's highly topographical with ridges, pits, rugosity or other surface structures.
level with: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being located at the same level as another entity.
ornamented: A surface feature shape in which the bearer's surface is highly topographical with ridges, pits, rugosity or other surface structures.
mass of ice and snow: A object which is composed primarily of water-based snow and ice.
figure: An information content entity consisting of a two dimensional arrangement of information content entities such that the arrangement itself is about something.
cloud cover: An area density which inheres in a clouds by virtue of some influence exerted their mass exerts on a given area.
limestone: A sedimentary rock which is composed primarily of calcium carbonate in the form of calcite or aragnoite.
integumentary projection: Anatomical projection that is part of the integumentl system.
body proper: The region of the organism associated with the visceral organs.
main body axis: A principle subdivision of an organism that includes all structures along the primary axis, typically the anterior-posterior axis, from head to tail, including structures of the body proper where present (for example, ribs), but excluding appendages.
ant dump: An animal construction created by leaf-cutter ants that is composed of various materials that result from the ants' activities and behaviors, including degraded plant material, microbial communities, organic material, dead ants and fungus.
plant tissue culture: Plant tissue culture is the growth or maintenance of plant cells, tissues, organs or whole plants in vitro.
psychiatric unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide psychiatric medicine.
active enrichment culturing unit: An enrichment culturing unit which contains environmental material bearing ecological assemblages undergoing selection through experimentally imposed conditions.
non alcoholic beverage (eurofir): Beverage containing no more than 0.5% alcohol; it may be flavoured, sweetened or carbonated; includes soft drinks and steeped beverages; excludes milk in all forms, fruit juices and vegetable juices.
chemical role: A role played by the molecular entity or part thereof within a chemical context.
sclerophyllous forest: A forest ecosystem which is dominated by trees adapted to dry or arid environmental conditions.
flaxseed oil: An oil used as a nutritional supplement and is a traditional European ethnic food, highly regarded for its nutty flavor.
litter: Environmental material consisting of waste products that have been discarded at an unsuitable location.
elemental molecule: A molecule all atoms of which have the same atomic number.
anatomical system: Multicellular, connected anatomical structure that has multiple organs as parts and whose parts work together to achieve some shared function.
organism substance: Material anatomical entity in a gaseous, liquid, semisolid or solid state; produced by anatomical structures or derived from inhaled and ingested substances that have been modified by anatomical structures as they pass through the body.
immaterial anatomical entity: Anatomical entity that has no mass.
multicellular organism: Anatomical structure that is an individual member of a species and consists of more than one cell.
anatomical space: Non-material anatomical entity of three dimensions, that is generated by morphogenetic or other physiologic processes; is surrounded by one or more anatomical structures; contains one or more organism substances or anatomical structures.
diesel fuel: A liquid fuel used in diesel engines, whose fuel ignition takes place, without any spark, as a result of compression of the inlet air mixture and then injection of fuel.
infrared radiation: A radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted when molecules change their rotational-vibrational movements, usually at wavelengths between 760 nm and 1 mm.
institutional building: A building which is used by an organization which serves a long-established role in human society.
depth of water ice: The depth of some water ice.
lipid food product: A lipid food product is a food product made primarily of plant or animal fat or oil
central nervous system cell part cluster: A multi cell part structure that is part of a central nervous system.
organ system subdivision: A subdivision of an anatomical system.
freezing fog: A fog the droplets of which freeze upon contact with exposed objects, forming a coating of rime or glaze.
slate: Slate is a metamorphic rock which is fine-grained, foliated, homogeneous, Slates are derived from clastic sedimentary rocks.
restaurant: A building within which food and drink are prepared and served to customers in exchange for money or other goods and/or services.
motor: A motor is a machine designed to convert one or more forms of energy into mechanical energy.
artificial reef: Chains of rocks or coral at or near the surface of water constructed by man.
carbonate system of ocean water: A system which is composed of carbon-based chemical entities dissolved in or otherwise part of an ocean or sea and the atmosphere adjacent to it, undergoing constant exchange through biogeochemical cycling.
gill tissue material: An organic environmental material which is primarily composed of gill tissue.
kaolin dust: Dust which is primarily composed of kaolinite particles.
glacial ice gain: A process during which the mass of ice constituting a glacier increases.
ecosystem: An environmental system which includes both living and non-living components.
sound: A large sea or ocean inlet larger than a bay, deeper than a bight, wider than a fjord, or it may identify a narrow sea or ocean channel between two bodies of land.
meltwater: Meltwater is the water released by the melting of snow or ice, including glacial ice, tabular icebergs and ice shelves over oceans.
trunk: Organism subdivision which is the part of the body posterior to the cervical region (or head, when cervical region not present) and anterior to the caudal region. Includes the sacrum when present.
visual system: The sensory system subserving the sense of vision.
slate dust: Dust which is primarily composed of slate particles.
protected area: An environmental zone which 1) contains ecosystems, constructed features, or other entities deemed to be of natural, historical, cultural, or other significance and 2) has been afforded legal protections restricting one or more forms of use by a competent authority.
impact-driven seismic vibration: A seismic vibration process which is caused by the impact of a solid object on the surface of an astronomical body.
environmental monitoring program area: An environmental monitoring area which is under observation by humans belonging to organisations with a legislative mandate to monitor the area.
dry lake bed: A lake bed which is dry. That is, the bed of a dry lake.
foreshock: A tectonic earthquake which precedes the strongest tectonic earthquake in a series, linked to the same release of energy in the crust.
alpine tundra biome: An alpine tundra ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
sarcosine enriched soil: A portion of sarcosine enriched soil is a portion of soil with elevated levels of sarcosine.
Mohorovicic discontinuity: The Mohorovicic discontinuity, usually referred to as the Moho, is the boundary between the Earth's crust and the mantle, indicating a change in composition.
desert-alpine tree line ecotone: A tree line ecotone across which trees cease to grow due to insufficient water availability caused by exposure to increased solar radiation and a lack of rainfall.
IUCN strict nature reserve: An IUCN protected area in which human visitation, use and impacts are strictly controlled and limited to ensure protection and conservation of natural biodiversity and/or geodiversity, natural ecosystem assemblages and processes, and any associated cultural and spiritual values.
upper front: A weather front which is part of a mass of upper air.
inlet: An opening of the sea into the land, or of a lake into its shore.
outdoor environment: An environmental system which is not sheltered.
mediterranean woodland biome: A mediterranean woodland ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
thoracic segment blood vessel: A blood vessel that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].
respiratory system muscle: Any muscle organ that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].
thoracic segment connective tissue: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].
area of lichen-dominated vegetation: An area of a planet's surface which is primarily covered by fruticose or foliose lichens and which is in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.
ranch: An area of land used for the herding and grazing of livestock.
single-species collection of organisms: A material entity that has as parts two or more organisms, viruses, or viroids of the same species and no members of any other species.
renal system: The renal system in an anatomical system that maintains fluid balance and contributes to electrolyte balance, acid/base balance, and disposal of nitrogenous waste products.
skin epidermis: The outer epithelial layer of the skin that is superficial to the dermis.
circulatory system: Organ system that passes nutrients (such as amino acids and electrolytes), gases, hormones, blood cells, etc. to and from cells in the body to help fight diseases and help stabilize body temperature and pH to maintain homeostasis[WP].
digestive system: Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs devoted to the ingestion, digestion, and assimilation of food and the discharge of residual wastes.
respiratory system: Functional system which consists of structures involved in respiration.
meadow ecosystem: A grassland ecosystem which contains a variety of annual, biennial and perennial plants growing on rolling or flat terrain.
metallic material: A material which is composed primarily of one or more pure metals and which shows their properties.
tailings dam: An earth-filled dam which is used for the storage of mining operations byproducts, after separating the ore from the gangue.
sandy sediment: Sediment characterised by an average particle diameter between 62.5 micrometers and 2 mm.
broad bean food product: A broad bean food product is a product derived from the broad bean plant.
biosphere: An astronomical body part which includes all the living entities within the gravitational sphere of influence of that body, as well as the non-living and dead entities with which they interact.
Superfund site: A highly contaminated site designated by the United States of America's Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act.
stellar wind: A stream of plasma primarily composed of electrons, protons, and alpha particles ejected from the upper atmosphere of a star.
skin of clavicle region: A zone of skin that is above the clavicle zone in the pectoral girdle region.
European Union agency food product type: LanguaL curation note: This term is for CLASSIFICATION ONLY; DO NOT USE term in indexing. Use a more precise narrower term.
volcanic soil: An andosol which derives its silica content from glass and tephra ejected during a volcanic eruption.
asthenosphere: An asthenosphere is a layer of a terrestrial-type planet or natural satellite which is highly viscous, mechanically weak, and ductilely deforming.
neritic epipelagic zone biome: The neritic epipelagic zone biome comprises the marine water column that occurs above a continental shelf and extends from the surface of the ocean to a depth of ca. 200-250m. Throughout the zone the light field tends to be asymmetrical vertically, so that the direction and elevation of the sun can still be detected. The epipelagic zone encompasses the euphotic zone and, where and when it occurs, the seasonal thermocline.
fermented agave beverage: This food product type includes beverage products which are made from the fermented sap of the maguey (agave) plant.
slightly saline water: Water which contains a slightly increased concentration of dissolved salts, relative to their concentration in freshwater.
freshwater marsh: A marsh in which soils are saturated with water that contains low concentrations of salts.
marine current: A water current which is maintained by a continuous, directed movement of marine water, generated by forces caused by breaking waves, wind, Coriolis force, temperature and salinity differences, and tides caused by the gravitational pull of astronomical bodies. Depth contours, shoreline configurations and interaction with other currents influence a current's direction and strength.
swamp ecosystem: A wetland ecosystem in which land mass is permanently inundated by shallow bodies of water, generally with a substantial number of hummocks, or dry-land protrusions.
cold occluded front: An occluded front which is adjacent to a cold front 1) that is moving away from the coldest air in the vicinity,  2) where the neighbouring cold front undercuts the neighbouring warm front in the occulsion zone, and 3) where the coldest air in the vicinity replaces less cold air towards the surface of the astronomical body.
carbon monoxide ice: Ice which is primarily composed of carbon monoxide.
phreatic zone: A compound astronomical body part which is located beneath the land surface and in which all interstices are filled with water that has a hydraulic head greater than atmospheric pressure due to the weight of overlying groundwater.
bulk soil: Soil that is not penetrated by the root systems of plants.
potato food product: A potato food product is any product derived from potatoes.
atmospheric secondary aerosol formation: A process during which gas-phase molecules form solid or liquid particles that are stable enough to continue growing in size - via the condensation or aggregation of other gas-phase molecules - at a greater rate than their constituents re-enter gas phase.
structural basin: A structural basin is a geological depression formed by tectonic warping of previously flat lying rock strata.
blood vessel layer: Any of the tissue layers that comprise a blood vessel. Examples: tunica media, tunica adventitia.
ice loss process: A material decumulation process during which the mass of an existing ice mass decreases in size.
disconnected: A structural quality inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer consisting of multiple structures lacking any physical connection to each other.
biogas: Biogas is a mixture of different gases produced by the breakdown of organic matter in the absence of oxygen,  is primarily composed of methane and carbon dioxide, and may have small amounts of hydrogen sulfide, water, and siloxanes.
day care facility: A child care facility in which day care services are provided, by specialized staff and equipment, to a human child during the working day.
generically dependent continuant: b is a generically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant that g-depends_on one or more other entities. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [074-001])
thoracic segment organ: An organ that part of the thoracic segment region. This region can be further subdividied chest and thoracic cavity regions.
lentic water body: A lentic water body is a water body in which the accumulated water, in its totality, has very little to no directed flow.
tubular paraffin lantern: A tubular paraffin lantern is a paraffin lantern which includes metal tubes in its casing that direct air to the burning wick.
rangeland ecosystem: An terrestrial ecosystem which is primarily used for the rearing and grazing of livestock.
continental island: An island that lies on a continental shelf.
compacted soil: A soil which has a high bulk density and/or a low porosity. A compacted soil has a reduced rate of both water infiltration and drainage
currency note: A paper product which is used as legal tender in economic or other monetary trasactions.
coastal anthropogenic litter: Anthropogenic litter which is present in a coastal environment.
coastal shrimp pond: A shrimp pond which is embedded in a coastal water body.
tributary glacier: A glacier which flows into a larger glacier.
hydrothermal field: A geothermally active field within which geothermally heated aqueous fluids are discharged from the the surface of a rocky planet.
bean (cooked): Bean material which has been cooked.
presumptive structure: Portion of embryonic tissue determined by fate mapping to become a structure.
presumptive endoderm: Presumptive structure of the blastula that will develop into endoderm.
temperate broadleaf evergreen forest: A broadleaf evergreen forest which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
ophthalmology unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide ophthalmological services.
firn: Granular snow which contains a proportion of fused granules formed through melting and re-thawing while being compacted by the weight of overlying material and which contains interconnected gaseous pores.
oceanic mesopelagic zone biome: The oceanic mesopelagic zone biome comprises regions of the marine water column that occur offshore, beyond a continental shelf. This biome extends through the water column from approximately 200-1000 m depth - the maximal depth of light penetration in all but the clearest oligotrophic ocean regions. In comparison to the epipelagic zone, dominant forms of pelagic organisms do not change very much; however, there are marked changes in species composition and the proportion of smaller-sized individuals decreases.
area density: A density quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of some influence exerted by the bearer's mass on a given area.
translucent: A optical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting low opacity.
volumetric density: A density quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of some influence exerted by the bearer's mass on a given volume.
splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesode: Layer of lateral plate mesoderm that forms the circulatory system and future gut wall - overlies endoderm[WP].
alum spring: A spring through which water with elevated concentrations of hydrated double sulfate aluminium salts flows.
glycan: Any oligosaccharide, polysaccharide or their derivatives consisting of monosaccharides or monosaccharide derivatives linked by glycosidic bonds. See also http://www.ontobee.org/ontology/GNO?iri=http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GNO_00000001.
caldera: A feature formed by the collapse of land following a volcanic eruption.
mesophilic sediment: Sediment characterised by a temperature of 15-45 degrees Celsius and high-to-low oxygenation. Often impacted by hydrothermal fluid flows.
whale fall: Whale fall is the term used for a whale carcass that has fallen to the ocean floor. When a whale dies in shallow water, its carcass is typically devoured by scavengers over a relatively short period of time: within several months. However, in deeper water (depths of 2,000 m/6,600 ft or greater), fewer scavenger species exist, and the carcass can provide sustenance for a complex localized ecosystem over periods of decades.
neonatal intensive care unit facility: A hospital unit facility which is used to provide intensive neonatal medical care.
subtropical woodland ecosystem: A woodland ecosystem which is subject to subtropical environmental conditions.
microbial community: An ecological community which is composed of co-existing populations of microbial organisms that interact, directly or indirectly, such that they impact one another's ecological fitness.
subpolar environment: An environment which is subject to subpolar environmental conditions.
thawing process: A warming process during which the thermal energy in a portion of environmental material is sufficient to melt water-based ice or snow.
ice cap ridge: A linear elevation on an icecap.
aligned with: An alignment quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being in a proper spatial positioning with respect to an additional entity.
increased osmolarity: A osmolarity which is relatively high.
alignment: A spatial quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's spatial positioning with respect to an additional entity.
osmolarity: A concentration quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's amount of osmoles of solute per liter of solution.
misaligned with: An alignment quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being in a improper spatial positioning with respect to an additional entity.
riverine flood: A riverine flood is a flood which is formed as a result of a river's flow rate exceeding the capacity of its channel.
skyscraper: A building which historically has at least 10 floors.
marine mud: Mud which is part of a marine ecosystem.
warm core cyclone: A cyclone which rotates around an area low atmospheric pressure with increased temperature.
agricultural pollution: An environmental pollution process during which contaminants derived from agricultural activity are released into an environmental system.
entanglement of organisms in marine debr: An entanglement process during which organisms become entrapped in anthropogenic marine debris.
wet pitfall trap: A pitfall trap in which the container used to hold trapped animals is filled with a liquid solution formulated to hold, kill, and preserve any animal or animals which falls within it.
burrow: A burrow is a hole or tunnel excavated into the ground by an animal to create a space suitable for habitation, temporary refuge, or as a byproduct of locomotion
blue: A color hue with low wavelength of that portion of the visible spectrum lying between green and indigo, evoked in the human observer by radiant energy with wavelengths of approximately 420 to 490 nanometers.
concentration of salt in soil: The concentration of a salt when measured in soil.
dune: A hill of sand built by eolian processes.
surface layer: A layer of some material entity which is adjacent to one or more of its external boundaries and directly interacts with its immediate surroundings.
abattoir: A facility in which non-human animals are slaughtered and processed for human consumption.
wildlife management area: A protected area with the purpose of protecting and managing wild life.
anlage: Anlagen are populations of contiguous cells, typically arranged in one plane, that are morphologically indistinct, but that already correspond in extent to a later organ/tissue.
seafood or related product (eurofir): The group includes marine or freshwater fish, molluscs, crustaceans, and other fauna such as reptiles, insects or frogs not in the Meats group. The group also includes seafood product analogs and seafood-based sausage or luncheon meat as well as such products as squid ink and clam juice.
continental temperate: A continental temperate condition is a temperate condition which is influenced by large land masses. Summers are warm to hot and winters are often  long, cold, and snowy.
immune system: Anatomical system that protects the body from foreign substances, cells, and tissues by producing the immune response and that includes especially the thymus, spleen, lymphoid tissue, lymphocytes including the B cells and T cells, and antibodies.
1st arch mandibular mesenchyme: Mesenchyme that is part of a 1st arch mandibular component.
oceanic transient tracer: A transient tracer role which inheres in chemical entities in seawater.
lost stream: A surface stream that disappears into an underground channel, or dries up in an arid area.
atom: A chemical entity constituting the smallest component of an element having the chemical properties of the element.
vinasse: A manufactured product which is formed as a liquid byproduct generated during the rectification and distillation of ethanol.
coffee beverage: A brewed drink prepared from roasted seeds, commonly called coffee beans, of the coffee plant.
mass gaseous flow: A process whereby a large volume of gas moves due to a disequilibrium of physical forces.
oil pipeline network: A pipeline network which is used to transport oil to consumers.
waterspout: A tornado which connects a cumulus or cumulonimbus cloud to a body of water, often transporting water from that water body along the spiraling winds constituting  its vortex.
land ice mass: An ice mass which has formed over land.
mouth mucosa: A mucous membrane that lines the mouth.
lake: A body of water or other liquid of considerable size contained in a depression on a landmass.
electromagnetic radiation: A radiation process during which waves (or their quanta, photons) of the electromagnetic field propagate (radiate) through space carrying electromagnetic energy.
biomaterial containment unit: A manufactured product which has been designed to contain a mass of biomaterial.
flash flooding: Flash flooding is a process in which low-lying land is inundated with water for a short period of time and are usually the result of precipitation or a breach in the container of a water body.
satellite imaging: A remote sensing process during which image data about an astronomical body or object is generated by sensors mounted on a satellite.
building wall: Building walls are bulding parts which serve to support roofs, floors and ceilings; enclose a space as part of the building envelope; give buildings form; and to provide shelter and security.
meteoroid: An astronomical body which is composed of rocky or metallic materials and is considerably smaller than asteroids.
marine streamer: Marine streamers are tongues of cold water that extend > 100 km offshore from upwelling regions. Enhanced primary productivity may occur in these waters as they are typically more nutrient rich than marine surface waters.
motorscooter: A scooter or motor scooter is a motorcycle with step-through frame and a platform for the rider's feet.
volcanic crater lake: A lake contained within a volcanic crater.
brewery: A brewery is a building in which alcoholic beverages are produced by brewing, that is, steeping a starch source (commonly cereal grains) in water and fermenting the resulting sweet liquid with yeast. At times, the products are also sold from the brewery.
spruce forest soil: Soil which is part of a forest whose communites of arborescent plants are dominated the genus Picea.
agricultural waste material: Agricultural waste is waste produced as a result of various agricultural operations. It includes manure and other wastes from farms, poultry houses and slaughterhouses; harvest waste; fertilizer run- off from fields; pesticides that enter into water, air or soils; and salt and silt drained from fields.
continental rise: A slope which a) bridges, and thus lies between, a continental slope and an abyssal plain, b) is formed by the accumulation of sediments transported from a continental slope by processes including turbidity currents c) has a gradient less than a continental slope yet greater than a continental shelf.
dry soil: Soil which has little to no water content and in which minerals and other soluble chemical entities have either bonded or become adsorbed to sold particles due to insufficient water availability.
drawbridge: A bridge which is hinged and can be raised.
mobile intensive care ambulance: An ambulance which is equiped to enable intensive care service provision.
multiple vortex tornado: A tornado which comprises two or more columns of spinning air rotating about their own axis and at the same time around a common center.
cupboard: A cupboard is a cabinet which is used indoors to store household objects such as food, crockery, textiles and liquor, and to protect them from dust and dirt
whole plant development stage: A plant structure development stage (PO:0009012) that has as primary participant a whole plant (PO:0000003).
cinder cone: A cone built almost entirely of loose volcanic fragments called cinders (pumice, pyroclastics, or tephra). They are built from particles and blobs of congealed lava ejected from a single vent. As the gas-charged lava is blown violently into the air, it breaks into small fragments that solidify and fall as cinders around the vent to form a circular or oval cone. Most cinder cones have a bowl-shaped crater at the summit.
river bank: The sloping margin of a river, serving to confine it to its natural channel.
sporophyte development stage: A whole plant development stage (PO:0007033) that has as primary participant a whole plant (PO:0000003) during the interval between fertilization (or apogamy) and death.
application: Intended use of the molecular entity or part thereof by humans.
pharmacy: A healthcare facility which is used to prepare, dispense, or sell medical drugs.
carr: A fen which has developed to the point where it supports trees.
velvet bean food product: A bean food product made from velvet bean.
ephemeral spring: A spring through which fluid intermittently flows.
particulate organic carbon: Particulate organic matter which is composed primarily of carbon.
compost biofilter: A biofilter which contains compost and avails of the microbial communities within it to degrade pollutants.
forest process: To be populated through inference. Do not use for annotation.
diatomite: A sedimentary rock which is primarily composed of the fossilized, siliceous remains of diatoms mixed with varying amounts of other clays and minerals.
silty loam: Loam which has a high proportion of silt in its composition.
main group molecular entity: A molecular entity containing one or more atoms from any of groups 1, 2, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, and 18 of the periodic table.
mud: An environmental material which is a liquid or semi-liquid mixture of water and some combination of soil, silt, and clay particles.
embankment dam: A dam which is created by the placement and compaction of a complex semi-plastic mound of various compositions of soil, sand, clay, or rock.
underground water body: A geographical feature associated with water that is under the surface of the earth.
concentration of soil organic matter in: The concentration of a soil organic matter when measured in soil.
photovoltaic system: A photovoltaic system is a power system designed to supply usable solar power by means of photovoltaics. It consists of an arrangement of several components, including solar panels to absorb and convert sunlight into electricity, a solar inverter to change the electric current from DC to AC, as well as mounting, cabling and other electrical accessories to set up a working system.
amount: The number of entities of this type that are part of the whole organism.
desublimation process: Desublimation is a process in which a portion of some gas undergoes a phase transition into a portion of some solid.
sludge: The residual semi-solid material left from domestic or industrial processes, or wastewater treatment processes.
opposite: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being positioned on opposite sides on the same plane.
obtuse: A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being roundish, a little inclining to be oblong.
Kaaba: A building which is at the center of Islam's most important mosque, the Great Mosque of Mecca.
artificial satellite: A human construction that has intentionally been placed into orbit.
area of perennial water ice: An area of a planet's surface which is primarily composed of water ice, present throughout multiple years, in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.
shower curtain: A manufactured product which is composed of flexible material and is intended to be hung such that it impedes the spray of water between a shower fixture and the rest of a room.
polyatomic entity: Any molecular entity consisting of more than one atom.
temperature of environmental material: The temperature of some environmental material.
material pooling disposition: The disposition of an environmental system to sequester and store some material entity.
speed of soil water infiltration: The speed of some soil water infiltration.
katafront: A weather front at which warm air is descending to lower altitudes along the frontal surface.
group home facility: A long-term care facility which is used to provide care for people with complex health needs, and which typically has at least one caregiver in attendance twenty four hours a day.
thermocline: A cline across which temperature changes rapidly.
subtropical desert biome: .A subtropical desert ecosytem which is in its climactic successional state.
coal mine lake sediment: Coal mine lake sediment is lake sediment which covers the bottom of a coal mine lake.
ultraviolet stellar radiation: A stellar radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted from a star at wavelengths between 10 nm and 400 nm.
quarrying: A mining process during which rock or mineral deposits are extracted from the terrestrial surface layers of an astronomical body.
puddle of water: A puddle is a small accumulation of water, on a surface. It can form either by pooling in a depression on the surface, or by surface tension upon a flat surface.
cirrostratus fibratus cloud: A cirrostratus cloud which occurs as a detached unit or a thin veil and consists of nearly straight or irregularly curved filaments that do not terminate in hooks or tufts.
water ice sublimation process: A sublimation process during which water ice transitions into a gaseous state.
shell: A rigid covering that envelops an object.
multi-species collection of microbes: A multi-species collection of organisms that consists of two or more microbes from at least two species.
astronomical object: An object which is composed of one or more gravitationally bound structures that are associated with a position in space.
pack ice mass: A drift ice mass which has an ice concentration above or equal to 7/10: which covers 70% or more of a given area of a water body.
private prison: A prison facility which is owned and operated by a private corporation.
conveyor belt component: A manufactured product which is 1) an endless belt of flexible material stretched between two drums; 2) conveys material between drum locations.
canopy: A vegetation layer which is formed by a collection of individual plant crowns, themselves constituting part of the aboveground portion of a plant community.
community service centre: A public building in which health, recreation or other public services to a local community are provided.
biogeochemical process: A process during which chemicals that are involved in natural ecosystem processes are transported or transformed, and which impact the activity of biological entities
honeycomb: A modular structure created by bees (Anthophila) from beeswax, consisting of a mass of hexagonal prismatic cells used to store honey, pollen, and house brood (eggs, larvae, and pupae).
diesel exhaust: A gas which results from the incomplete or complete combustion of diesel fuel.
tea beverage (liquid): A beverage prepared from the cured leaves of Camellia sinensis by combination with hot or boiling water.
glacial bed: A glacial surface layer which is adjacent to the bedrock or debris over which a glacier flows.
subalpine biome: A biome which is subject to subapline altitudinal conditions.
road traffic noise: A noise produced by road traffic and automobiles.
decreased mass: A mass which is lower than normal or average.
distributed: A spatial pattern inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being spread out or scattered about or divided up.
increased mass: A mass which is higher than normal or average.
indoor toilet: An indoor toilet is a room which contains a sanitation fixture used primarily for the disposal of human urine and faeces.
alkaline salt lake: A saline lake which has a high pH.
geographic feature: An astrononmical body part which delimited by physical discontinuities with its surroundings.
environmental monitoring: An process in which environmental parameters and variables are continually assayed.
agency food product type: An agency food product type is a class of food product defined by an agency or consortium.
quality of a liquid: A physical quality inhering in an entity exhibiting the physical characteristics of an amorphous (non-crystalline) form of matter between a gas and a solid that has a definite volume, but no definite shape.
quality of a gas: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting the physical characteristics of an entity consisting of particles that have neither a defined volume nor defined shape.
flexible: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ability of being turned, bowed, or twisted without breaking.
quality of a solid: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting the physical characteristics of an entity characterized by particles arranged such that their shape and volume are relatively stable.
inflexible: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's inability of being turned, bowed, or twisted without breaking.
flexibility: A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to being turned, bowed, or twisted without breaking.
irradiation by photosynthetically active: Irradiation during which a material entity receives energy through photosynthetically active radiation.
alimentary part of gastrointestinal syst: The part of the digestive system that excludes the hepatobiliary system.
large freshwater lake ecosystem: A freshwater lake ecosystem which has its functions and composition determined by a large freshwater lake.
large river delta biome: A large freshwater river delta ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
periglacial lake: A lake, part of whose margin is formed by an ice mass, ice cap or glacier, the ice having obstructed the natural drainage of the land.
consequent stream: A stream whose course is a direct consequence of the original slope of the surface upon which it developed, i.e., a stream that follows the slope of the original land.
cream food product: A dairy product that is composed of the higher-butterfat  layer skimmed from the top of milk before homogenization.
fungal structure: An anatomical structure that forms all or part of a fungus.
cave wall: A solid surface layer which 1)  forms part of the boundary between the cavity of a cave and its solid container and 2) is roughtly perpendicular to the cave floor.
agricultural fairground: A fairground which is used to exhibit agricultural technology, livestock, and farm-related activity.
monomictic lake: A monomictic  lake is a holomictic lake which mixes from top to bottom during one mixing period each year.
scroll plane: A plain where a stream meanders across an area with a very low gradient, usually with a fairly continuous discharge. In addition to meanders, scroll plains are also characterised by many oxbow lakes.
prepared food product: Food product that is 1) ready or nearly ready for consumption; 2) usually a composite of several foods or ingredients that often belong to distinct product types; 3) usually formulated, mixed and partially or fully cooked.
biotransformation process: A planned process involving the deliberate use of biological agents, such as microbes or enzymes, to chemically modify substances in a controlled setting. This process is typically utilized to enhance the value or reduce the environmental impact of various materials.
pasta food product: A food made from an unleavened dough of wheat or buckwheat  flour and water, sometimes with other ingredients such as eggs and vegetable  extracts.
fluvisol: Fluvisols accommodate genetically young, azonal soils in alluvial deposits.
food (preserved): Food material which is the output of a food preservation process.
water-based rain: Rain which is composed of water droplets falling to a planetary surface during a rainfall process.
tributary: A stream or river which flows into another river (a parent river) or body of water but which may not flow directly into the sea.
alpine biome: A biome which is subject to alpine altitudinal conditions.
ecto-epithelium: Epithelium composed of cells that develops from the ectoderm[FMA,modified].
periglacial process: A frost action process which occurs in cold environments which are not part of a glacier.
door: A manufactured product which is composed of a hinged, sliding, or revolving barrier which is installed at the entrance to a building, room, vehicle, or in the framework of a cabinet.
multi-component plant food product:
SIREN DB annotation:
* part of plant FOODON:03420174
anthropised terrestrial environmental zo: A terrestrial zone which is bounded by constructed, manufactured, or other anthropogenic material entities.
sausage (smoked): Sausage which is cured with a food smoking process.
mine: An excavation in the Earth for the purpose of extracting earth materials.
liquid planetary core: A liquid planetary core is a planetary core which is primarily composed of liquid material.
lake sediment: Lake sediment is sediment which covers the bottom of a lake. Lake sediments are comprised mainly of clastic material (sediment of clay, silt, and sand sizes), organic debris, chemical precipitates, or combinations of these.
sleet pellet: An ice mass which is primarily composed of frozen or mostly frozen raindrops or refrozen partially melted snowflakes.
shipwreck: Anthropogenic litter which consists of an abandoned ship's remains.
overflow structure: A structure which is built into the container of a water body which allows water to flow out of the container when the volume of the water contained exceeds that of its cavity.
convergent tectonic movement: A process during which pieces of a planetary crust and uppermost mantle move towards one another.
ecosystem process: An environmental process either driven by or primarily impacting the parts or emergent properties of an ecosystem.
kelp forest: Kelp forests are underwater areas with a high density of kelp. They are recognized as one of the most productive and dynamic ecosystems on Earth. Smaller areas of anchored kelp are called kelp beds.
cis-dichloroethane contaminated sediment: Organically enriched sediment which has increased levels of cis-dichloroethane.
flood: An unusual accumulation of water above the ground caused by high tide, heavy rain, melting snow or rapid runoff from paved areas.
ecological community: A multi-species collection of organisms of at least two different species, living in a particular area. Must have at least two populations of different species as members.
hypodermis: Lowermost layer of the integumentary system in vertebrates. Types of cells that are found in the hypodermis are fibroblasts, adipose cells, and macrophages. It is derived from the mesoderm, but unlike the dermis, it is not derived from the dermatome region of the mesoderm. The hypodermis is used mainly for fat storage[WP].
viscus: An organ that is located within the body cavity (or in its extension, in the scrotum); it consists of organ parts that are embryologically derived from endoderm, splanchnic mesoderm or intermediate mesoderm; together with other organs, the viscus constitutes the respiratory, gastrointestinal, urinary, reproductive and immune systems, or is the central organ of the cardiovascular system. Examples: heart, lung, esophagus, kidney, ovary, spleen.
marine wind mixed layer: The upper part of the marine water column with generally uniform properties resulting from wind-driven mixing.
mass-wasting-driven seismic vibration: A seismic vibration process which is caused by mass wasting.
tree line ecotone: An ecotone which overlaps at least one biome which supports the growth and persistence of trees and at least one that does not. Before ceasing altogether, tree growth becomes sparse and trees appear stunted as conditions become less favourable along this ecotone.
watershed: The separation between neighbouring drainage basins (catchments). In hilly country, the divide lies along topographical peaks and ridges, but in flat country or on a high plateau (especially where the ground is marshy) the divide may be invisible - just a more or less notional line on the ground on either side of which falling raindrops will start a journey to different rivers, and even to different sides of a country or continent.
barley malt vinegar: Vinegar is made by malting barley, causing the starch in the grain to turn to maltose.
talus cave: A talus cave is a cave formed by the openings between large boulders which have fallen into a random heap.
hard-frozen soil: Frozen soil which is firmly cemented by water ice, is subject to brittle failure, and exhibits practically no consolidation under load.
alkaline hot spring: A alkaline spring through which groundwater, heated by geothermal energy, flows.
apiary: An apiary is a place where beehives of honey bees are kept and maintained by beekeepers.
warming of a gas: A process of warming a fluid during which the thermal energy in a volume of gas increases.
grape must: A grape berry food product which is the juice of freshly pressed grapes that contains some amount of pulp, skins, stems, and seeds.
acidic water-based rain: Water-based rain which has increased acidity.
chemically contaminated sediment: Sediment which contains some chemical contaminant.
building part: A building part is a construction which is part of a building.
drainage canal: Artificial watercourse with no flow or a controlled flow used drainage.
latrine: A latrine is a toilet which is of simple construction (relative to a flush or chemical toilet) and typically intended for communal use.
fog: A visible mass of cloud water droplets or ice crystals suspended in the air at or near the surface of an astronomical body.
toxic waste: Waste which contains toxic components (e.g., heavy metals or radiation) which can cause harm to organisms and/or the environment.
area of drift ice: An area in which masses of drift ice aggregate such that they cover less than 7/10ths of the surface the water body they are floating in.
heat-treated animal manure: Manure which has been subjected to heat treatment for solidification and/or sterilization purposes.
planet: A planet is an astronomical body orbiting a star or stellar remnant that is massive enough to be rounded by its own gravity, is not massive enough to cause thermonuclear fusion, and has cleared its neighbouring region of planetesimals.
postcranial axial skeletal system: Subdivision of the skeletal system which consists of the postcranial axial skeleton plus associated joints.
axial skeletal system: Subdivision of the skeletal system which consists of the axial skeleton plus associated joints.
nonsynovial joint: Joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages are connected by ligaments or fibrocartilage without an intervening synovial cavity. Examples: sagittal suture, inferior tibiofibular syndesmosis, costochondral joint, pubic symphysis.
thermoplasticity: A disposition inhering in a bearer by virtue of that bearer's ability to, repeatedly, become plastic on heating and harden again on cooling.
cirrocumulus castellanus cloud: A cirrocumulus cloud which 1) has linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances which resemble crenellated turrets or towers, some of which are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts, 2) possess a lower region or base which connects these protuberances.
cell culturing unit: A biomaterial culturing unit which is designed to promote the growth and propagation of cells in an artificial medium.
wood stain: A stain which has colorants dissolved and/or suspended in a vehicle or solvent, used to add color to wood.
cellophane: A thin, transparent sheet made of regenerated cellulose.
lysocline: A cline across which one or more solid environmental materials dissolve into their surrounding fluid.
ice cave congelation ice: Freshwater congelation ice which has formed on a solid substrate in an ice cave.
gorgonzola cheese food product: A drum of very rich, creamy, pungent blue-veined cow's milk cheese. It has a white paste with blue veining and a brined rind. It is made in Gorgonzola, near Milan.
meat sausage (cooked): A sausage made with fresh meats, and then fully cooked.
cypress dome: A cypress dome swamp is a dome swamp which has a plant community dominated by Cupressaceae, often swamp cypresses. Swamp cypresses typically belong to the genus Taxodium or the species Glyptostrobus pensilis and Actinostrobus pyramidalis.
peat swamp: Forested peatlands including both rain- and groundwater-fed types, commonly recorded in tropical regions with high rainfall.
marine layer: A layer that is part of a marine water body.
lens vesicle: Portion of tissue that gives rise to the lens.
radioactive spring: A mineral spring through which water with elevated levels of radioactive material flows.
