oceanic benthopelagic zone biome: The benthopelagic zone biome comprises regions of the marine water column which usually coincide with the benthic boundary layer (BBL) - the layer of isothermal and isohaline water contiguous to the sea floor. A general reversal in the declining gradient of pelagic biomass may be observed here, perhaps explained by viable nutrition on the sea floor being resuspended by bottom currents. This zone typically extends 100 m above the seafloor, but may reach upto1000 m during benthic storms.
rate: A quality of a single process inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's occurrence per unit time.
viability: An organismal quality inhering in a bearer or a population by virtue of the bearer's disposition to survive and develop normally or the number of surviving individuals in a given population.
time: A quality in which events occur in sequence.
karst cave: A cave which is part of a karst formation.
lunar rainbow: A lunar rainbow is a rainbow produced by the refraction of light, which has been reflected from a moon's surface, by water droplets in an astronomical body's atmosphere.
wooden building floor: A wooden building floor is a building floor that is composed primarily of wood.
estuarine mud: Mud which is part of an estuary.
temperate broadleaf forest biome: A broadleaf forest which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
fruit or vegetable product (us cfr): Fruits and vegetables in all forms. [FDA CFSAN 1995]
primary circulatory organ: A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, keeps up the circulation of the blood or analogs[GO,modified].
meconium: A dark greenish mass that accumulates in the bowel during fetal life and is discharged shortly after birth.
estuarine coastal pycnocline: A pycnocline which is part of an estuarine water body, spanning from the shore to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.
sausage (raw): A sausage made from meats that have not been previously cured.
joint of girdle: A skeletal joint that is part of a appendage girdle region.
invariant: A variability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's lacking or not exhibiting variation.
obsolete freshwater habitat: A habitat that is in or on a body of water containing low concentrations of dissolved salts and other total dissolved solids (<0.5 grams dissolved salts per litre).
inverse estuary: An estuary which is located in regions where evaporation greatly exceeds the inflow of fresh water, forming a zone of maximum salinity towards which both riverine and marine water masses flow, before sinking and spreading along the bottom in both seaward and landward directions.
microbial enhanced oil recovery: A biotransformation that uses microorganisms to increase the extraction efficiency of oil from reservoirs. This process may involve the alteration of oil viscosity, the modification of reservoir properties, or the production of biosurfactants.
tela choroidea: A structure found in the walls of the ventricles of the brain, consisting of part of the meninges (pia mater in mammals) plus ependyma[cjm].
tela choroidea of telencephalic ventricl: Tela chorioidea that lines the telencephalic ventricle.
ventricular system of central nervous sy: A set of structures containing cerebrospinal fluid in the brain. It is continuous with the central canal of the spinal cord[WP].
water ice surface layer: An ice surface layer which is primarily composed of water ice.
rock-precursor intrusion process: A process whereby the precursors of rock, such as magma or sedimentary particles, fill a fracture in a mass of rock.
estuarine tidal riverine open water lowe: A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to end of the estuary most distal from the coast.
active layer in a cryosphere: A layer of environmental material which is subject to freeze-thaw cycles.
spatter cone: A volcanic cone formed of molten lava ejected from a vent somewhat like taffy. Expanding gases in the lava fountains tear the liquid rock into irregular gobs that fall back to earth, forming a heap around the vent. The still partly liquid rock splashed down and over the sides of the developing mound is called spatter. Because spatter is not fully solid when it lands, the individual deposits are very irregular in shape and weld together as they cool, and in this way particularly differ from cinder and ash.
lake channel: A channel of a watercourse which contains lake water.
hoar crystal: A water ice crystal which is a part of a deposit of hoarfrost and which only grows by desublimation.
mini-Neptune: A gas planet which has an atmosphere composed of hydrogen and helium  - probably with deep layers of ice, rock or liquid oceans (made of water, ammonia, a mixture of both, or heavier volatiles) - and a small core made of low-density volatiles.
haze formation event: A haze formation process which has an increased rate relative to that which is usually present in a given site.
falling sleet: An object aggregate which is primarily composed of particles of water in liquid, frozen, or partially frozen states.
erosional cave: A cave formed by erosion caused by flowing streams carrying rocks or sediments.
multi-species collection of organisms: A collection of organisms that consists of two or more organisms from at least two species.
microburst: A downburst during which high winds occur over an area less than four kilometres in diameter.
anafront: A weather front at which warm air is ascending to high altitudes along the frontal surface.
xanthan gum: A polysaccharide that functions as an emulsifier, stabilizer, and thickener in mixtures.
proglacial lake: A lake formed either by the damming action of a moraine or ice dam during the retreat of a melting glacier, or one formed by meltwater trapped against an ice mass due to isostatic depression of the crust around the ice.
bodily fluid material: An organic material which is primarily composed of some natural bodily fluid or secretion such as blood, semen, saliva, blood plasma, intracellular and interstitial fluids.
tropical: A tropical condition is an environmental condition in which an environmental system receives high yearly solar irradiance per unit area and, on Earth, the Sun reaches a subsolar point at least once during the solar year. This results in a hot and moist year-round climate at low elevations, which have a monthly average temperature above 18 degrees Celsius.
sawmill: A building within which logs are cut into lumber products.
food shop: A shop in which a business offers food products for sale or trade.
big-box store: A store which is physically large and is part of a retail chain.
meander: A bend in a stream. A stream flowing through a wide valley or flat plain will tend to form a meanders as it alternatively erodes and deposits sediments along its course.
sulfate: A sulfur oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of both OH groups of sulfuric acid.
clay loam: Loam which has a high proportion of clay in its composition.
synthetic polymer: A polymer which is the output of a manufacturing process.
research facility: A facility which supports the undertaking of scientific research or measurements.
chicken egg food product: An avian egg food product having chicken eggs or derivatives as a defining ingredient.
ophiolites: A planetary structural layer which consists of oceanic crust and the underlying upper mantle and has been uplifted and exposed above sea level.
a. primary food commodities of plant or: LanguaL curation note: This term is for CLASSIFICATION ONLY; DO NOT USE term in indexing. Use a more precise narrower term.
hailfall: A hydrological process during which hail stones fall to the surface of an astronomical body.
landslide process: A landslide is a process whereby a large mass of earth and rocks moves down a hill or a mountainside.
solubility: A molecular quality that inheres in a molecular entity by virtue of the bearer's disposition to dissolve in a liquid.
field capacity: A concentration of liquid water in soil arrived at after water which is not retained by the soil has drained away.
animal litter: Straw or other material strewn in an animal's enclosure (e.g. a stable) for it to sleep on and to absorb its faeces and urine.
freshwater wetland ecosystem: A wetland which is inundated with water that contains low concentrations of salts.
water ice core: An ice mass which has been drilled from an accumulation of snow and ice that has built up over many years and that has recrystallized and has trapped air bubbles from previous time periods.
methane-releasing thermokarst lake: A thermokarst lake through which methane gas released from thawing permafrost, or other methane stores, rises and escapes to the atmosphere.
monsoon season: A season during which changes in atmospheric circulation associated with the asymmetric heating of land and sea cause moisture to be brought inland by monsoon winds, leading to increased rainfall as moisture-laden air rises  and cools over land.
dry stream: A stream channel through which no water flows and which has dried, containing no appreciable accumulations of water.
impermeable surface layer: A surface layer through which liquids or gases cannot pass.
clay fermentation pit: A fermentation pit which is constructed from clay.
obsolete marine mesoscale eddy: A marine mesoscale eddy is a current of marine water which has a typical horizontal diameter of less than 100 km and persists for approximately one month.
planned revegetation: A planned process during which human agents establish plant communities in ecosystems which have previously been, partially or wholly, stripped of existing plant communities.
integumentary adnexa: Anatomical structure embedded in or located in the integument that is part of the integumental system. Examples: hair, follicles, skin glands, claws, nails, feathers.
sea shore: That part of the land in immediate contact with a sea, including the intertidal zone.
factory: A factory (previously manufactory) or manufacturing plant is an industrial site, usually consisting of buildings and machinery, or more commonly a complex having several buildings, where workers manufacture goods or operate machines processing one product into another.
candy food product: A confection made from a concentrated solution of sugar in water, to which flavorings and colorants are added.
population of organisms: A collection of organisms, all of the same species, that live in the same place.
sandy loam: Loam which has a high proportion of sand in its composition.
fragmentation process: An environmental system process during which a material entity breaks into pieces or parts.
glory: A photometeor which is formed by wave interference of light refracted within water droplets which constitute mist or clouds and consists of one or more concentric, successively dimmer rings, each of which has red wavelengths distant to the glory's centre and blue wavelengths towards the centre.
subtropical broadleaf forest biome: A subtropical broadleaf forest in which is in its climactic successional state.
steakhouse: A restaurant which specializes in serving steaks and pork chops.
troposphere: The lowest of the concentric layers of the atmosphere, occurring between the Earth's surface and the tropopause. It is the zone where atmospheric turbulence is at its greatest and where the bulk of the Earth's weather is generated. It contains almost all the water vapour and aerosols and three-quarters of the total gaseous mass of the atmosphere. Throughout the troposphere temperature decreases with height at a mean rate of 6.5°C/km and the whole zone is capped by either an inversion of temperature or an isothermal layer at the tropopause. (Source: WHIT)
obsolete haline habitat: A habitat characterized by a concentration of salt at least 2M. Inhabited by halophilic organisms.
limed soil: Soil which has been amended with mineral additives to increase its pH.
frost sorting: A frost action process during which the soil particles are differentially displaced according to their size ranges.
flush: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being level or even with another surface.
oblique to: A positional quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having a slanting direction (neither perpendicular nor parallel) relative to another entity.
paddy field: A flooded parcel of arable land used for growing rice and other semiaquatic crops.
anvil: A concave 3-D shape that inheres in the bearer by virtue of the bearer's shape that is wider at one end and narrow in the middle.
soy sauce food product: A condiment produced by fermenting soybeans with Aspergillus oryzae and Aspergillus soyae molds  along with roasted grain, water, and salt.
small freshwater lake biome: A small freshwater lake ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
ventricle of nervous system: A layer in the central nervous system that lines system of communicating cavities in the brain and spinal cord.
bread food product: A staple food prepared from a dough of flour (usually wheat) and water, usually by baking
broken: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's components no longer being in a single contiguous unit.
calcified: A composition quality inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's being encrusted or impregnated with calcium carbonate (CHEBI:3311).
wholeness: A structural quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer includes all its components.
bile material: A bodily fluid material which is composed primarily of bile, a bodily fluid consisting of a bitter, yellow or green alkaline fluid secreted by hepatocytes from the liver of most vertebrates. In many species, bile is stored in the gallbladder between meals and upon eating is discharged into the duodenum where the bile aids the process of digestion of lipids.
subglacial: A positional quality which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer in being in physical contact with or below a glacial bed.
levee: An artificial slope or wall, usually earthen, which parallels the course of a river, built for the purpose of containing the river.
mucus: Mucus is a bodily fluid consisting of a slippery secretion of the lining of the mucous membranes in the body. It is a viscous colloid containing antiseptic enzymes (such as lysozyme) and immunoglobulins. Mucus is produced by goblet cells in the mucous membranes that cover the surfaces of the membranes. It is made up of mucins and inorganic salts suspended in water.
interstitial fluid: Interstitial fluid is a bodily fluid consisting of a solution which bathes and surrounds the cells of multicellular animals. It is the main component of the extracellular fluid, which also includes plasma and transcellular fluid.
thoracic segment of trunk: Subdivision of trunk that lies between the head and the abdomen.
chyle: Chyle is a bodily fluid consisting of a milky fluid consisting of lymph and emulsified fats; formed in the small intestine during digestion of ingested fats.
chyme: A semifluid mass of partly digested food expelled by the stomach into the duodenum.
clay sediment: Sediment characterised by an average particle diameter between 1 and 3.9 micrometers.
ghost fishing: An anthropogenic environmental process during which abandoned, lost, or discarded fishing gear attracts and entangles organisms.
swiss cheese food product: A generic cheese common to many countries for several related varieties of cheese  which resemble the Swiss Emmental. Three types of bacteria are used in the production of Emmental cheese: Streptococcus salivarius subsp. thermophilus, Lactobacillus  (L. helveticus or Lactobacillus delbrueckii subsp. bulgaricus), and Propionibacter (P. freudenreichii or P. shermani). In a late stage of cheese production, the Propionibacter consumes the lactic acid excreted by the other bacteria, and releases carbon dioxide gas, which slowly forms the bubbles that develop the eyes. Swiss cheese without eyes is known as "blind."
basic cation exchange capacity: A cation exchange capacity which inheres in an environmental material by virtue of the material's ability to adsorb basic exchangeable cations.
salt mass: An accumulation of a salt, typically sodium chloride.
process boundary: p is a process boundary =Def. p is a temporal part of a process & p has no proper temporal parts. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [084-001])
part of a landmass: A solid astronomical body part which is part of the landmass of that body.
fumarole: A hole in the Earth's crust from which steam and gases are emitted.
subtropical woodland biome: A subtropical woodland ecosystem which is in its climactic successional state.
heavy snowfall: Snowfall which has an increased rate.
anthropogenic litter: A material entity which has been discarded outside waste management systems by humans or their technologies.
wetland area: An vegetated area which overlaps a wetland ecosystem.
area of barren land: An area of a planet's surface which is primarily composed of bedrock, desert pavement, scarp rock, talus, material exposed by slides, volcanic material, glacial debris, sand, material exposed during strip mining, gravel, and other accumulations of earthen material in contact with an atmospheric column extending from the planetary boundary layer to the planet's exosphere with little to no physical obstruction.
desert sand: Sand which is part of a desert.
obsolete intermittent watercourse: A watercourse whose flow is not continuous.
tempeh food product: A food product having tempeh as a defining ingredient
alpine soil: Soil which is part of an alpine environment.
increased variability of size: A variability of size which is relatively high.
variability of size: A variability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of whether the bearer exhibits size variation or change.
decreased variability of size: A variability of size which is relatively low.
nurdle: A plastic pellet which is produced such that its size allows it to be rapidly melted and used as input for further downstream manufacturing processes.
residential building: A human house which serves as a long-term shelter for its inhabitants and within which they store personal property.
natural gas processing plant: A refinery which is capable of processing natural gas. Natural-gas processing encompasses a range of industrial processes designed to purify raw natural gas by removing impurities, contaminants and higher molecular mass hydrocarbons to produce what is known as pipeline quality dry natural gas
glacier wind: A drainage wind which flows along the icy surface of a glacier.
freshwater lake: A lake of whose water contains low concentrations of salts.
tidal mudflat: A level tract lying at a small depth below the surface of water, or alternately covered and left bare by the tide.
plant anatomical entity: An anatomical entity that is or was part of a plant.
orange fruit beverage:
